1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d3 d6 6. Bg5 {This version of the
trendy Bg5 Italian lines makes the most sense to me, before White has castled
short (in case of ...h6 and ...g5) and only after ...d6 to prevent Black's
solid lines dropping the bishop back to e7. Having said that, Black still has
many good ways to play.} h6 7. Bh4 a6 (7... g5 $5 8. Bg3 a5 {still leaves
White no real alternatives to castling short:} 9. O-O Ba7 10. Na3 $132) 8. Nbd2
Ba7 9. a4 g5 10. Bg3 Qe7 11. O-O Nd7 (11... Nh7 {is another route for the
knight to g6 which can transpose:} 12. Kh1 $1 {is White's safest and
best-scoring plan, preparing Ng1 and f2-f3 to give an escape route for the
dark-squared bishop} Nf8 13. Ng1 h5 14. f3 Ng6 15. b4 $14) 12. b4 (12. Kh1 $1 {
will transpose to the note above}) 12... Nf8 13. d4 $5 {[%mdl 4] A promising
side line. Eine vielversprechende Nebenvariante.} h5 $6 {A surprising mistake,
playing this without ...Ng6 allows a thematic response} (13... Ng6 $1 14. b5
Na5 15. h3 h5 16. bxa6 (16. Bd5 $6 {�-� Firouzja,A (2759)-So,W (2770)
Paris GCT Rapid 2021 (1) allows Black to ignore the bxa6 threat:} h4 17. Bh2 g4
18. hxg4 Bxg4 19. bxa6 h3 20. g3 c6 $17) 16... bxa6 17. Bd5 c6 18. dxe5 $1 dxe5
(18... cxd5 19. exd6 $13 {seems promising for White}) 19. Nb3 $1 {when a
sample line continues} h4 20. Nxa5 hxg3 21. Bxc6+ Kf8 22. Bxa8 g4 23. Nc6 Bxf2+
24. Rxf2 gxf2+ $13) 14. b5 Nd8 $2 (14... Na5 15. h4 g4 16. Nxe5 dxe5 17. Bxe5
Rg8 $13 {the piece sacrifice is still promising but of course Black has better
chances than with the knight passive as in the game}) 15. h4 $146 ({Vorgänger:
} 15. h3 Ng6 16. Bd5 g4 17. hxg4 hxg4 18. Nh2 exd4 19. Nc4 dxc3 20. b6 Bxb6 21.
Nxb6 cxb6 {0-1 (44) So,W (2753)-Gukesh,D (2758) Berlin 2023}) 15... g4 16. Nxe5
$1 (16. Ne1 Ng6 17. Nd3 {0-1 Kosteniuk,A (2546)-Barp,A (2424) Titled Tuesday
intern op 2nd April blitz 2019 (10)} Nxh4 18. dxe5 $16 {even this way of
playing is promising with Black's knight passive on d8}) 16... dxe5 17. Bxe5
Rg8 18. Bg3 Ng6 19. Bd3 (19. e5 $1 {preparing Ne4 is logical. Arjun must have
been worried about} Bf5 {when} 20. Qe1 $1 Nxh4 21. f3 $1 {opens lines with
devastating effect:} Nxf3+ 22. gxf3 gxf3 23. Kh1 $18) 19... Nxh4 20. e5 Kf8 21.
Ne4 Nf5 $6 (21... Ng6 22. Nf6 h4 $1 23. Nxg8 $6 Kxg8 24. Bh2 h3 $132 {succeeds
in opening the kingside, since White can hardly play g3}) 22. Nf6 Rh8 23. Qd2
Nxg3 (23... h4 24. Bf4 $18 {now only helps White with Bxf5 threatened}) 24.
fxg3 Qxe5 25. Rae1 (25. Bh7 $1 {is apparently cleaner, preventing the
sacrifice in the game} Qd6 26. Qh6+ Ke7 27. Rae1+ Be6 28. Qg7 Rf8 29. Qg5 $18)
25... Bxd4+ 26. cxd4 Qxd4+ 27. Rf2 Ne6 28. Re4 Qd6 29. Qc3 Rh6 30. bxa6 bxa6
31. Bc4 Rb8 32. Re1 Rb4 33. Ne4 Qb6 34. a5 Rxc4 {Black continues to find
strong defensive resources to get back into the game} 35. Qd2 (35. Qxc4 Qd4 36.
Qc1 Kg7 {is also winning but coming up with a plan is less simple}) 35... Qxf2+
36. Qxf2 Nd4 37. Ng5 Nf5 38. Ne4 $6 {Arjun begins to lose the thread of the
game as he struggles to coordinate his pieces playing with the extra queen.} (
38. Qd2 Nd6 39. Rf1 {looks like the best setup, threatening Nxf7 to start with.
}) 38... Rhc6 39. Qb2 Rd4 40. Qb8 Rd8 41. Rf1 Re8 42. Qb4+ Re7 43. Nc3 Be6 44.
Nd5 Bxd5 45. Rxf5 Rc4 46. Qa3 Be6 47. Rxh5 Ke8 48. Rh8+ Kd7 49. Qd3+ Kc6 50.
Rh6 Rc1+ $2 {Playing for counterplay against the White king, but a simpler
approach was stronger} (50... Kb5 $1 {Black can cover his king from all angles:
} 51. Rh5+ c5 52. Rh8 Rb7 $13 {and any result is possible if the a5-pawn falls}
) 51. Kh2 Rd7 52. Qxa6+ Kc5 53. Rh5+ $1 {Just in time to prevent Rdd1 and
trade pieces} Rd5 54. Rxd5+ Bxd5 55. Qd3 $2 (55. Qa7+ Kd6 56. Qb8 $1 Ra1 57.
Qb4+ $18 {Collects the g4-pawn with check since} Kc6 $2 58. Qc3+ $18 {is worse.
}) 55... Rc4 56. Qd1 Bc6 $2 {Keeping control of the queening square, but now
White manages to protect the pawn on a7.} (56... Be6 {keeps everything
defended and White's pawn should not be able to advance further:} 57. a6 Kb6
$11) 57. a6 Ra4 (57... Kb6 58. Qb3+ Bb5 59. a7 $18 {is the problem.}) 58. a7
Ra6 59. Qb3 f5 60. Kg1 Bb5 61. Qe3+ Kd5 62. Kf2 c5 63. Qe7 Bc6 64. Ke3 Kc4 65.
Qe6+ Kb5 66. Qb3+ Ka5 67. Qb8 Bxg2 68. Kd3 Rb6 69. Kc4 $1 Rb4+ 70. Kxc5 1-0


