1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 5. Qe3 {This queen retreat is not an
especially critical try for an advantage, but in the early middlegame Black
will need to find a constructive plan as otherwise the position can slip away
relatively quickly.} g6 ({For instance:} 5... Nf6 6. h3 d5 7. exd5 Nxd5 8. Qb3
e6 9. Be2 Be7 10. c4 Nf6 11. O-O O-O 12. Rd1 Qc7 13. Nc3 a6 14. Be3 $14 {
and White was already very comfortable in Vaibhav,S-Williams,S Titled Tuesday
2020.}) 6. h3 Bg7 ({Years ago I had a game as White against the Serbian GM
Zlatko Ilincic, which continued with} 6... Bh6 7. Qc3 Qa5 8. Qxa5 Nxa5 9. Bxh6
Nxh6 10. Nc3 Nc6 11. O-O-O $14 {and it seems for now that White is slightly
better, but of course Black is so solid that a comparable degree of experience
would have been necessary in order to even try and wear him down.}) (6... Nf6
7. Bc4 {should be similar to the game.}) 7. Bc4 Nf6 8. Nc3 O-O 9. O-O Nd7 {
This knight tour ends up looking not especially purposeful.} ({A more solid
construction would be the Hedgehog-esque} 9... a6 10. a4 b6 11. Qe2 Bb7 12. Bf4
Qc7 13. Rfe1 e6 14. Rad1 Ne5 $11 {of Benjamin,J-Gufeld,E New York op 1989,
which Black later won.}) 10. Rd1 Nb6 (10... b6 $5 {as in 1-0 Aronian,L-Carlsen,
M INT 2020 is best met by the transfer of the queen to h4:} 11. Qf4 Bb7 12. Qh4
{and this seems to be in some sense a fitting punishment for the departure of
Black's king's knight from f6.}) 11. Bb3 {White has emerged from the opening
with a slight advantage.} Be6 (11... Na5 12. Qg5 Nbc4 13. Qh4 $14) 12. Qf4 Bxb3
13. cxb3 e5 14. Qg3 Nd4 $6 ({Preferable was} 14... f5 $5 15. exf5 gxf5 16. Bh6
Rf7 17. Nb5 $14 {with a sharp position where White's better development makes
some impact on proceedings.} (17. Nh4 $5)) 15. Be3 $1 {Probably Black didn't
expect this move to be possible.} Nc2 16. Bg5 Qe8 (16... f6 17. Rac1 Nd4 18.
Be3 $16) 17. Rac1 Nd4 18. Be3 f5 19. exf5 $6 ({It was not all that hard to
calculate the line} 19. Nxd4 f4 20. Bxf4 exd4 21. Nb1 $1 (21. Bxd6 {is also a
bit better for White, but it's silly to go into this.} dxc3 22. Bxf8 cxb2 23.
Bxg7 bxc1=Q 24. Rxc1 Kxg7 25. Rc7+ Kg8 26. Qc3 Qf8 27. Rxb7 $40) 21... Qxe4 22.
Bxd6 $16 {when Black doesn't have enough compensation.}) 19... Nxf5 20. Qg4 Rc8
{Now White can play for static control again.} ({Preferable was} 20... Nxe3 21.
fxe3 Bh6 22. Qe4 Qe6 {intending ...Qf5, and White's control of the position is
not as firm as they would like.}) 21. Bxb6 axb6 22. Qe4 Rc6 23. Nd5 Bh6 24. Rc3
Qf7 25. Kh1 Kh8 26. a4 Bg7 27. b4 Nd4 28. Nxd4 $5 {White makes a decision to
cash in the positional dominance for an extra pawn.} ({A move like} 28. Rcd3 {
would have kept the status quo for a bit longer.}) 28... Rxc3 29. bxc3 exd4 30.
cxd4 Qxf2 31. b5 Bh6 32. Nxb6 Bf4 33. Qf3 $6 (33. Nd5 Bg3 34. Rg1 Rc8 35. Ne3
$16) 33... Qc2 $6 {Repaying the favour.} ({Black is so active after} 33... Bg3
34. Qxf2 Rxf2 $44 {that White should be somewhat careful not to create losing
chances.}) 34. Qd3 Qc7 35. Nd5 Qf7 36. Qf3 Bg5 37. Rf1 ({Even simpler looks to
have been} 37. Qxf7 Rxf7 38. a5 $18) 37... Qxf3 38. Rxf3 Ra8 39. Nb6 Re8 40.
Rf7 Be3 41. Rxb7 Bxd4 42. a5 h5 43. h4 Re1+ 44. Kh2 g5 $1 {An excellent
practical try.} (44... Be5+ 45. g3 g5 {is too slow, as White simply pushes.}
46. a6 gxh4 47. a7) 45. g3 $2 {Maybe White is still winning after this, but it
becomes a very close thing.} ({It's not too late to blunder and lose the
thread entirely: after} 45. hxg5 $4 Be5+ 46. g3 h4 {Black's counterplay comes
with one tempo extra, and that's a huge difference in such positions. In fact
White can't even hold here, despite the two extra pawns.} 47. a6 hxg3+ 48. Kg2
Re2+ 49. Kh3 Rh2+ 50. Kg4 g2 $19) ({The added complication of ...Bg1 ideas
makes it harder to compute, but} 45. a6 Bg1+ {is not actually that threatening:
} 46. Kh3 $18) 45... g4 46. Rd7 Re2+ 47. Kh1 Re1+ 48. Kg2 Re2+ 49. Kf1 Rf2+ 50.
Ke1 Ra2 ({Some truly last-ditch defending might have left Black with a chance
to save the game:} 50... Rb2 $1 51. Kd1 Rxb5 52. Rxd6 Bf2 53. Rd5 Rb3 54. Rxh5+
Kg7 {and somehow, despite the two pawn deficit, Black is not a million miles
away from the drawn RN v R endgame.} 55. Rg5+ Kh6 56. Rxg4 Bxg3 57. Kc2 Rf3 58.
a6 Bb8 $16) 51. Nc4 Bf2+ 52. Kd1 Bxg3 53. b6 $18 Bf4 54. b7 d5 55. Nd6 Rb2 56.
Rd8+ Kh7 57. b8=Q Rxb8 58. Rxb8 Bxd6 59. Rb7+ 1-0


