1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {The Kalashnikov is a rare guest at
the top level, but it used to be Teimour's trusty weapon for years.} 5. Nb5 d6
6. c4 Be7 {The most common move. As usual, Black keeps in mind a possible ...
Bg5 exchange.} (6... Be6 7. N1c3 ({A solid alternative is} 7. Bd3 $5 {Korobov,
A (2658)-Stremavicius,T (2544) Vrnjacka Banja SRB 2023 [Roiz,M]}) 7... a6 8.
Na3 g6 {yielded Black a memorable victory in Anand,V (2753)-Maghsoodloo,P 
(2676) chess.com INT 2020 [Roiz,M]}) 7. N1c3 a6 8. Na3 f5 {The most aggressive,
but risky, choice.} (8... Nf6 {was also successfully employed by GM Radjabov a
long time ago:} 9. Nc2 Be6 10. Be2 Rc8 {Kramnik,V (2759)-Radjabov,T (2756)
Baku (rapid) 2009 [Richard Palliser]}) 9. exf5 {Preventing the nasty ...f5-f4.}
Bxf5 10. Bd3 Be6 11. Nc2 ({Another common way is} 11. O-O Nf6 12. Nc2 O-O (
12... d5 $5 13. cxd5 Bxd5 14. Nxd5 Qxd5 15. Ne3 Qd7 {might be acceptable for
Black, although giving up the light-squared bishop isn't to everyone's taste.})
13. Ne3 ({After} 13. b3 Qd7 14. Bb2 Bd8 {White can hope only for a tiny
advantage. See the notes to Leitao,R (2567)-Nataf,I (2526) New Delhi IND 2000 
[Fed]}) 13... Nd4 ({After} 13... Qd7 14. Ned5 Bd8 15. Be3 Rc8 16. Rc1 Kh8 17.
b3 $14 {Black didn't have proper compensation for his structural drawbacks in
Michiels, B - Potapov,P Khanty-Mansiysk 2010}) 14. b3 Qd7 {Black connects his
rooks and vacates d8 for the bishop transfer.} 15. Ne4 Rae8 16. Nxf6+ Bxf6 17.
Be4 $14 {White has a slight, but stable plus. Catt,P - Legemaat,G ICCF email
2019}) 11... Nf6 12. Bg5 {White is interested in liquidating Nf6 to fix
control of d5. However, this move isn't well-timed.} (12. Ne3 O-O 13. O-O {
could transpose to a position from the above-mentioned note.}) 12... O-O ({
Seemingly, the energetic} 12... e4 $1 13. Be2 d5 {would have invited favorable
simplifications and solve all the issues:} 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. cxd5 Bxc3+ 16.
bxc3 Qxd5 $11) 13. O-O Ng4 {Again, the most common move. Teimour decides not
to follow his own play,} ({although after} 13... Qd7 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Ne3 f5
16. Ned5 Bd8 {Black obtained an excellent position and eventually won in
Akopian,V - Radjabov,T Astrakhan 2010}) 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 {The exchange of bishops
makes Black's play easier, though the Pd6 is still somewhat weak.} 15. h3 {
A new move for our PGN Archive. It hardly offers White anything special.} ({
After} 15. Ne3 Qh4 16. Nxg4 Bxg4 17. f3 (17. Qd2 $5 {looks more promising.})
17... Be6 {Black was solid in Dvoirys,S (2590)-Nataf,I (2504) Koszalin POL
1999 [Fed]}) 15... Nf6 16. Qe2 {A quiet choice. Arjun decides not to occupy
the central squares so quickly.} ({After} 16. Nd5 Qf7 17. Nxf6+ gxf6 18. b3 f5
{Black was close to equalizing in Majdan,J - Socko,M Ostrow Wielkopolski 2020})
16... Rae8 {This innovation is a certain improvement} ({over} 16... Qf7 {
Ludwig,J - Gara,A Budapest 2017 Here White could have developed some activity
with} 17. f4 $1 exf4 18. Rxf4 $14) 17. Rad1 Qf7 $6 {Untypically for him,
Teimour misses a great tactical opportunity!} ({After} 17... Bxh3 $1 18. gxh3
e4 {White's bishop is trapped. A likely continuation is} 19. Rfe1 exd3 $11 {
with major simplifications.}) 18. Ne4 {Now White has slight, but long-lasting
pressure.} Nxe4 19. Qxe4 g6 20. b3 Qc7 ({After} 20... d5 21. cxd5 Bxd5 22. Qe3
$14 {Black fails to fully equalize because his Pe5 is weak.}) 21. Qe3 Ne7 22.
Qd2 ({Another decent option was} 22. Be4 $5 Bf5 23. Qd3 $14 {, vacating e3 for
Nc2.}) 22... Rd8 23. Ne3 Rf4 (23... d5 24. cxd5 Nxd5 25. Nxd5 Rxd5 26. Qe3 $14)
24. g3 $6 {There was no reason for playing this committing move.} ({More to
the point was} 24. f3 Qc5 25. Be4 b5 26. Kh2 $14 {Black is doomed to passive
defense.}) 24... Rff8 25. Kh2 Qc8 {Now it is much tougher for White to make
any progress because his heavy pieces are tied to defending f2.} 26. h4 Qc6 (
26... Qc5 $5 {, followed by Nc3-d4 looks good enough too.}) 27. Qc2 Nf5 ({
The most convincing way to equalize was} 27... d5 $1 28. cxd5 Qxc2 29. Bxc2
Nxd5 {, but Radjabov's move isn't bad.}) 28. Bxf5 ({After} 28. Be4 Nxe3 29.
fxe3 Qc7 {White has a tiny advantage, but Black's defensive task doesn't seem
tough.}) 28... Bxf5 29. Nxf5 Rxf5 $11 {The position is too simple now. Black
has easy play along the f-file.} 30. Rd5 Rdf8 31. Kg2 b5 {A thematic break.}
32. Qe4 bxc4 33. Qxc4 Qxc4 34. bxc4 Rc8 {The simplest.} 35. Rxd6 Rxc4 36. Rxa6
Rc2 {Technically speaking, White is a pawn up. Of course, it has no value here.
} 37. Ra8+ Kg7 38. Ra7+ Kg8 39. a4 e4 40. Re7 Re2 41. Kg1 h5 42. Rc7 Ra2 43.
Rc4 Re2 44. Rc7 Ra2 45. Ra7 Rf7 46. Rxf7 1/2-1/2


