1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Be2 $5 {Rameshbabu opts for a relatively rare line to
confuse his opponent. However, later the game comes back to usual Scheveningen
paths.} Nc6 4. O-O Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 (5... d5 6. exd5 Nxd5 {is another common
choice, but this position belongs to another section.}) 6. d4 {There is
nothing else left.} cxd4 7. Nxd4 Qc7 8. Be3 Be7 {Arjun prefers to test his
young opponent in Scheveningen type positions.} (8... Bb4 {is a common choice
by Taimanov players, but recently Black faces some problems after} 9. Na4 Be7
10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Nb6 Rb8 12. Nxc8 Qxc8 13. Bd4 {For instance, see my notes to
Rizouk,A (2527)-Cruz,C (2554) Catalonia ESP 2014 [Roiz, M]}) 9. f4 d6 10. a4
O-O 11. Kh1 Bd7 {The only drawback of this natural developing move is blocking
d7, as Black sometimes needs it for his knight, especially in case White goes
for an aggressive g2-g4-g5 push.} (11... Re8 {is by far the most common move,
when some theoretical lines are explored till move 30-40. Those positions
became very popular after the 1st Karpov - Kasparov match.}) 12. Nb3 Na5 $6 {
A risky move that was tried by many strong players, including Nakamura and
Volokitin. Black is happy with possible damage to his pawn chain after Nxa5,
but it also diminishes control of e5.} (12... b6 {is the only move that we saw
on our site, a long time ago:} 13. g4 {1/2 (43) Dolmatov,S (2587)-Jakovenko,D 
(2521) Elista RUS 2001 [John Fedorowicz]} (13. Bf3 $5 Rae8 {Black tried many
other moves, but this one looks the most flexible because Black can play ..Bc8
without disconnecting his rooks.} 14. g4 Bc8 15. g5 Nd7 16. Bg2 {later led to
a standard complex struggle in Aravindh,C - Sandipan,C Caleta 2016}) {In my
opinion, the energetic} 13... d5 $1 {would have offered Black sufficient
counterplay. For instance,} 14. e5 Ne4 15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. c3 Rfd8 17. Qe1 Na5 $1
{, and then 18.Na5 bxa5 is good because it will make b2 very vulnerable. In
fact, Black scored 2.5/4 in this position.}) 13. e5 $1 Ne8 ({After} 13... dxe5
14. fxe5 Nd5 15. Nxd5 exd5 16. Nxa5 Qxa5 17. c3 $16 {White had both more
active pieces and a superior pawn structure in Barria Zuniga,D - Gatica
Miranda, J Santiago de Chile 1994}) 14. Nxa5 Qxa5 15. Ne4 {Black's main issue
is the poor Ne8. It will be hard to improve it and connect the rooks.} Qc7 ({
After} 15... d5 16. Ng5 g6 17. c3 Ng7 18. Nf3 $16 {Black has an awful setup
a-la French, where his king is exposed and his minor pieces have no good
prospects.}) 16. a5 $1 {White grabs more space and secures b6 for his bishop.}
Bc6 ({Hardly better is} 16... Rc8 17. c4 Bc6 18. Bb6 Qd7 19. Qc2 f5 {This
position occurred in Kraemer,M - Volokitin,A Germany 2014 Now the strong} 20.
Nc5 $1 dxc5 21. Rad1 Nd6 22. exd6 {would have put Black in a critical
situation because of the strong Pd6.}) 17. Bb6 Qd7 18. Bf3 ({Possibly even
more unpleasant for Black would be} 18. Qd4 $5 dxe5 19. Qxd7 Bxd7 20. fxe5 $16
{The Ne8 is stuck and Black struggles to involve his rook as well.}) 18... Rc8
19. Rf2 {This move is aimed to increase pressure on d6.} Bd5 $2 {This
innovation doesn't really make Black's position more attractive.} (19... f5 $6
{was seen in Madan,A - Ali,G Liverpool 2007 Here the simple} 20. Nxd6 Bxf3 21.
gxf3 Nxd6 22. Rd2 {would have put Black on the verge of collapse.}) ({In my
opinion, the best attempt to liberate the poor Ne8 was} 19... dxe5 $1 20. Rd2 (
{Also after} 20. Qxd7 Bxd7 21. fxe5 Bc6 22. Rd1 f5 $1 {Black has good chances
for a successful defence.}) 20... Bd5 21. fxe5 Qc6 $14 {The issues with Ne8
are still real, but the other pieces are well placed now, and Black can
consider counter-attacking measures with ...f7-f6.}) 20. b3 $1 {A strong
response. White declares his intention to drive his opponent's bishop away
with c2-c4.} dxe5 $2 {This loses on the spot, although Black's task was
already very tough.} ({For instance, after} 20... Qc6 21. Ra4 Bd8 22. Rc4 Qd7
23. Rxc8 Qxc8 24. Qd4 $1 $16) ({or} 20... f5 21. Nxd6 Bxd6 22. c4 Bxf3 23. gxf3
Qc6 24. exd6 Nxd6 25. Rd2 $16 {Black's rooks are paralyzed by the strong Bb6.})
21. c4 $1 f5 (21... Bc6 22. Rd2 $18) 22. cxd5 fxe4 23. Bg4 $18 {Black's poor
piece coordination is especially clear now.} Nc7 24. Bxc7 Qxc7 25. Bxe6+ Kh8
26. Bxc8 Rxc8 27. Rf1 ({Simpler is} 27. Re2 exf4 28. Rxe4 $18) 27... Rd8 28.
Rc1 Qd6 29. Qe2 Qxd5 (29... exf4 30. Qxe4 g5 31. Rfe1 {is hopeless, too.}) 30.
Rfd1 Qxa5 31. Rxd8+ Qxd8 32. Qxe4 {The rest is just agony.} Ba3 33. Re1 Qg8 34.
Qa4 Bb2 35. fxe5 Bc3 36. Re3 Qf8 37. Qc4 b5 38. Rf3 Qd8 39. Qd3 1-0


