1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 Nbd7 (4... dxc4 5. e4 (5. e3 a6 6. a4 c5 7.
Bxc4 Nc6 8. O-O Be7 9. Qe2 cxd4 10. Rd1 e5 (10... O-O 11. exd4 {[%csl Bd5]
[%cal Bc1g5,Bf3e5,Bd4d5,Ba1c1,Bc6b4,Bb4d5,Bf6d5,Bb7b6,Bc8b7,Ba8c8] �-�
Dubov,D (2714)-So,W (2770) Goldmoney Asian Prelim rapid 2021 (6.4) Once again
a typical isolated pawn position with the possible plans that are used here
for both sides. The d5 square plays a fundamental role in the blocking
strategy and the possibility of White's d4-d5 advance.}) 11. exd4 exd4 12. Nxd4
Nxd4 {[ Yue, W- Shanglei, L CHN-cht 2018. Check the game.} 13. Qe5 {[%csl Bd4]}
O-O 14. Rxd4 Qb6 {A somewhat complex position, but it is not far from equality.
}) 5... Bb4 6. e5 {this seems like a normal move but it is an error as has
been previously analyzed in similar positions due to the c-pawn defense
options.} Nd5 7. Bd2 Nb6 8. Be2 Nc6 9. Ne4 a5 10. a3 Be7 11. Bc3 Qd5 12. Qc2
Bd7 13. O-O Nb8 {[%cal Bd7a4] Black has a satisfactory position.}) 5. cxd5 exd5
6. Bg5 Bb4 7. e3 c5 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Bd8a5] Putting pressure on the center and
enabling the a5 square for the queen.} 8. Bd3 Qa5 9. Qc2 (9. O-O cxd4 $2 (9...
c4 {a logical sequence, it makes much more sense to keep the center closed.}
10. Bc2 Bxc3 11. bxc3 Qxc3 {I extend a special invitation to the reader to
immerse themselves in a double-edged attacking game led by the Hungarian GM
Banusz Tamas with the white pieces. [ Tamas, B - Ante, B Zagreb Open 2011.
Check the game.}) 10. exd4 Bxc3 $4 {[%csl Be8] This would go against the
concepts and fundamentals, the black king is quite exposed so 10...Bxc3 would
be a serious error due to Qe2+ and the pawn does not compensate having the
king in the center.} 11. Qe2+ Ne4 12. Bxe4 O-O 13. Bc2 Bxb2 14. Rab1 Ba3 15.
Rb3 Bd6 16. Nh4 g6 17. Nf5 $1 gxf5 18. Bxf5 $18 {[%cal Bb1h7,Bb3h3,Be2h5] The
pieces do not get to the defense in time.}) 9... c4 10. Bf5 O-O 11. O-O Re8 {
0-1 Svidler,P (2750)-Kramnik,V (2790) Amber-rapid 19th 2010 (9)} 12. Nd2 {
[%csl Be4] a logical move, preventing the knight's future jumps to e4.} h6 13.
Bh4 Qa6 14. Rfb1 {[%csl Bc4,Bd5][%cal Bb2b3] White must break the d5-c4 pawn
chain to justify the knight on d2 and the rook on b1.} Qc6 (14... g5 15. Bg3
Nf8 {[%csl Bf5][%cal Bc8f5,Ba6e6] was an interesting option, seeking to
eliminate the most active white piece. Unlike ...g5 in the Grischuck-Vachier
game, Black is now well prepared for that advance and with the possibility of
activating the queen via e6.} 16. a4 Bxf5 17. Qxf5 Qe6 18. Qxe6 fxe6 19. Nf3 a5
20. Ne5 Kg7 21. h4 Ng6 22. hxg5 hxg5 23. f3 $11 {The position is balanced, but
from a human point of view it may be easier to play with the black pieces.})
15. a4 b6 16. b3 cxb3 (16... g5 17. Bg3 Nc5 $1 {[%csl Bc2,Bc3,Bf5] Taking
advantage of the tactic involving the queen's overload.} 18. dxc5 $4 (18. Bxc8
Bxc3 19. Qxc3 Nce4 {[%csl Bc3] Intermedia!} 20. Nxe4 Nxe4 21. Qc2 Raxc8 $17 {
With a more than satisfactory position for Arjun, the knight on e4 is very
strong and the pawn on c4 could be a major threat in the endgame.}) 18... Bxf5
{[%csl Bc3]} 19. Qxf5 Bxc3 20. Ra2 bxc5 21. bxc4 d4 22. exd4 cxd4 $19 {[%csl
Ba4,Bc4,Be1] White cannot coordinate, there are too many weaknesses in the
position.}) 17. Rxb3 a5 18. Rc1 Ba6 19. Qd1 Qb7 (19... Rac8 {[%csl Bf6][%cal
Bf5d7]} 20. Bxf6 gxf6 $4 (20... Nxf6 21. Bxc8 Rxc8 $18) (20... Qxf6 21. Bxd7)
21. Qg4+ Kh8 22. Bxd7) 20. Na2 Bxd2 21. Qxd2 Bc4 22. Rb2 Ne4 23. Qd1 $6 (23.
Bxe4 Rxe4 24. Bg3 Rc8 25. Nc3 Re6 26. h3 $11 {He had to enter this ending of
opposing bishops, objectively the position is equal.}) 23... Nd6 24. Bb1 Ne4
25. Nc3 (25. f3 $1 {[%csl Be4][%cal Bb1h7,Bd1c2,Bh4f2] is typical in these
positions, it seems to leave a very weak point on e3 but the bishop on h4 will
defend this well. It is important to dislodge that knight and White would even
maintain chances of attacking on the kingside.}) 25... Nxc3 26. Rxc3 Rac8 27.
h3 Rc6 28. Bf5 Nf8 29. Qc2 Ne6 30. Qb1 Rec8 31. Rbc2 g6 32. Bxe6 Rxe6 33. Bg3
Qd7 34. Qa1 Rec6 35. Rc1 Bb3 36. Rxc6 Rxc6 37. Rxc6 Qxc6 38. Qa3 {Looking for
activity, there are also mating threats against the black king, Arjun must be
somewhat careful.} Bxa4 39. Qe7 Qd7 40. Qf6 {[%csl Bb6][%cal Bf6b6,Bg3e5]} Qe6
41. Qd8+ Be8 42. Bc7 a4 43. Bxb6 Qd7 (43... a3 44. Bc5 a2 45. Qa5 $11) 44. Qa8
Qc6 45. Qa7 a3 46. Bc5 Qa4 47. Qxa4 Bxa4 48. Bxa3 h5 49. Kh2 Bb5 50. Kg3 Bf1
51. f3 f5 52. Kf2 Bc4 53. Bd6 Kf7 54. Be5 Bb5 55. h4 Bc4 56. Bf4 Bb5 57. Bg5
Bc4 58. Kg3 Bf1 59. Kf2 Bc4 60. Kg3 1/2-1/2


