1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 d6 7. Be2 Nxd4 8.
Qxd4 Bg7 9. Be3 O-O 10. Qd3 {With Black now castled and the g7-bishop
protected, Black was threatening a discovered attack and so her majesty had to
be withdrawn.} ({We have seen this and 10 Qd1 on the site before but} 10. Qd2 {
is overwhelmingly more popular when you will find plenty on here with each of}
Be6 {, 10...Qa5 and 10...a5 in the archives.}) 10... a6 ({The white queen is
slightly awkward looking on d3 but given the results in practice (quite good!),
should not be under-estimated. Now not dissimilar to when her majesty is on d2,
Black's main three plans are: 1) Razz the a-pawn down to a4 to facilitate a ...
Qa5.2) Park that a-pawn on a5 when in controlling the b4-square, a ...Nd7-c5
plan is facilitated. 3) Target the c4-pawn through the likes of ...Be6 and ...
Rc8.4) Look to make a ...b5 pawn break. With that in mind, it will come as no
great surprise that previously we've covered each of} 10... a5 {10...Be6, 10...
Nd7, 10...Bd7 as well as 10...Ng4 but the text is a first, clearly with plan 4
in mind!}) 11. O-O Bd7 {Black is somewhat telegraphing his ...b5 pawn break
plan but if White attempted to prevent it through a2-a4 then at the very least
Black could play ...a5 securing the b4-square and hence with an obvious ...Bc6,
...Nd7-c5 plan to follow.} 12. Bd4 (12. Rfd1 b5 13. cxb5 axb5 14. Nxb5 Bxb5 15.
Qxb5 Rb8 16. Qc4 Rxb2 {might be a better version of the main game because of}
17. e5 {as would}) (12. f3 b5 13. cxb5 axb5 14. Nxb5 Bxb5 15. Qxb5 Rb8 16. Qd3
Rxb2 ({or} 16... Nd7)) ({However} 12. Rac1 b5 13. cxb5 axb5 14. Nxb5 Rxa2 {
wouldn't!}) 12... b5 13. cxb5 (13. Rfd1 bxc4 14. Qxc4 Qb8 {facilitates
bringing the other rook to c8.}) 13... axb5 14. Nxb5 ({It's too late for} 14.
f3 $6 {now with} b4 15. Nd5 $2 Nxd5 16. exd5 Bb5 $1 {a handy tactic to note.})
14... Bxb5 15. Qxb5 Nxe4 16. Bxg7 ({White might like to preserve his bishop
pair but} 16. Bb6 Qb8 {is no better than 'murky' with Black's minor pieces
pretty handy too.}) 16... Kxg7 17. a4 {It's great to see this type of position
played out by very strong players and very instructive it is too. Many club
players might be of the opinion that White is much better because he has a
bishop for a knight and outside passed pawns. That opinion would be incorrect
though. I often say that for any endgames involving rooks, strong centre pawns
still rule whilst the presence of queens on the board here too means that the
knight is not the inferior minor piece.} (17. Bf3 Rb8 18. Qe2 Nf6 {is
objectively equal although frankly I'd still prefer to play with the black
pieces.}) 17... d5 18. a5 Qd6 {Centralising her majesty and paving the way for
the other rook to swing to the queenside.} (18... Rb8 {is possible too but
after} 19. Qd3 {not} Rxb2 $4 20. Qd4+) 19. Rfd1 ({Upon} 19. a6 $2 Rfb8 20. Qd3
Nc5 {White's queenside pawns are disjointed with at least one not unlikely to
drop off soon.}) 19... e6 {Black has a rock solid centre and can focus on
dealing with those opposition passed pawns.} 20. Qa4 {Coming out of the way of
the b-pawn but specifically threatening Qxe4.} Qc5 21. Qd4+ Qxd4 22. Rxd4 {
With my previous comments still applying to this endgame. Provided a
successful white promotion isn't imminent, whilst the rooks are on, I favour
the centre pawns.} Rfb8 23. Ra2 ({Or} 23. b4 $6 Nc3 24. Kf1 Ra7 25. Rc1 e5 26.
Rd2 d4 {when those a- and b-pawns are going nowhere.}) 23... Kf6 {Controlling
the centre makes for far easier king activation.} 24. Kf1 Ke5 25. Rda4 Nc5 ({
The flexible 25...Ra7 and} 25... Nd2+ 26. Ke1 Nb3 {also appealed.}) 26. R4a3
Kd6 27. Ke1 Ra7 28. a6 e5 (28... Nb3 {also looked good but one certainly can't
fault advancing those centre pawns.}) 29. Ra5 f5 {This is much more fun for
Black!} 30. Kd1 Rb4 {Flexible and rubbing in the fact that White's b-pawn
won't be going anywhere fast if at all.} 31. Kc2 Rc7 ({Or the immediate} 31...
d4 $1 {This is so grovelly for White!}) 32. a7 {A case of 'fingers crossed'
and 'do your worst'!} Nb3+ 33. Kd3 ({And not} 33. Kb1 $4 Rc1# {nor}) (33. Kd1
$4 Rc1#) 33... Rd4+ 34. Ke3 Re4+ ({And essentially Black now bales out for the
draw although even now I'm not sure about} 34... Rxa7 35. Rxa7 f4+ 36. Kf3 Nd2+
37. Kg4 f3+ 38. Kg5 h6+ $1 (38... fxe2 39. R7a6+ Kc5 40. R6a5+ Kb4 41. R5a4+
Kb3 42. R4a3+ Kc2 43. b4+ Kb1 44. Ra1+ Kc2 45. R1a2+ Kd1 46. Ra1+ Kc2 {is an
amusing perpetual and so instead Black looks to create some 'luft' on the
kingside.}) {e.g.} 39. Kxh6 Rh4+ 40. Kxg6 Rg4+ 41. Kh5 fxe2 42. R7a6+ Kc5 43.
Ra1 Rxg2 {Crazy stuff!}) (34... f4+ 35. Kf3 Nd2+ 36. Kg4 f3+ 37. Kg5 Rxa7 {
would transpose to the above.}) 35. Kd3 Nc1+ 36. Kd2 Nb3+ 37. Kd3 {Retreating
to d1 or e1 would allow the mate in one ...Rc1.} Nc1+ 38. Kd2 Nb3+ 1/2-1/2


