1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 dxc4 5. Qa4+ {A new move for our site.} ({
Just in April of this year we focused on several tabiyas in the Catalan after} 
5. Bg2) 5... Nbd7 6. Qxc4 (6. Bg2 {Was tried successfully by Le last year
against Duda in the Crypto cup.} a6 7. Qxc4 b5 8. Qd3 Bb7 9. O-O c5 10. a4 (10.
dxc5 $1 {Was White's last chance to hold equality.}) 10... cxd4 11. axb5 axb5
12. Rxa8 Qxa8 13. Na3 $6 (13. Bf4 $1 {When White is only slightly worse.})
13... Bxa3 (13... Bc5 $1 $17) 14. bxa3 e5 15. Qxb5 {Black's center is
impressive at first glance and that intuition is indeed correct.} O-O {should
have given Black a pleasant edge. Bb7-a6 and Rf8-b8 or Rf8-c8 offer him a nice
initiative.}) 6... a6 7. Bg2 b5 8. Qb3 $6 (8. Qc6 $1 {Gives a slightly dubious
impression but doesn't risk too much.} Rb8 9. Bf4 Nd5 10. Bg5 (10. O-O Nxf4 11.
gxf4 Bd6 {Only Black can be better after Bc8-b7 and c7-c5.}) 10... Be7 11. Bxe7
Qxe7 12. Nc3 Bb7 (12... Qb4 $5 13. O-O Nxc3 14. bxc3 (14. Qxc3 Qxc3 15. bxc3
Bb7 {Black again has no problems.}) 14... Qd6 $13) 13. Nxd5 Bxc6 14. Nxe7 Kxe7
15. O-O (15. Rc1 $5 {seems like a better try.} Bxf3 (15... Bd5 $1 {was
necessary to hold the balance. Taking the pawn allows Black a good initiative.}
16. Rxc7 Rhc8 $132) 16. Bxf3 $14 Rhc8 17. Bc6 {And the c6 outpost offers White
a slight edge.}) 15... Bxf3 16. Bxf3 $11 {was Laznicka -- Navara, 1/2, 2020.})
(8. Qd3 {Would have also been better, when things transpose to that Le -- Duda
game in that last note.}) 8... Bb7 {After this the computer is certain White
is just worse, quite the poor opening outcome for the first player!} 9. a4 c5
$1 {Thematic and strong. White can't win b5 due to the zwischenzug of ...c5-c4.
} 10. axb5 c4 $1 $17 {White's position is just sad. It is clear things have
gone wrong when he has to make so many backward moves with the queen.} 11. Qd1
axb5 12. Rxa8 Qxa8 {Black's queenside is impressive and compared to thematic
positions White is down a few tempi.} 13. O-O Qa1 14. Nfd2 $2 (14. Nc3 $1 $17 {
would have kept the disadvantage manageable.}) 14... Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Bb4 16. Qc2
O-O 17. Nc3 Qa6 {Black's play is very simple. He will place his rook somewhere
on the queenside and gradually expand there. White hasn't a sliver of
counterplay.} 18. Nf3 Qb7 19. Bg5 Ra8 20. Rb1 Bf8 21. b3 cxb3 22. Rxb3 b4 23.
Bxf6 $6 (23. Qd3 $1 {was the last chance to hold on.}) 23... Nxf6 $19 {
Erigaisi went on to win a good game. An opening gone awry for White but kudos
to Erigaisi on the good technique.} 24. Nb1 Rc8 25. Qd3 g5 26. h3 h5 27. d5 g4
28. hxg4 hxg4 29. Ne5 Nxd5 30. e4 Nf6 31. Nd2 Rc1 32. Qe3 Rc5 33. Nd3 Rb5 34.
Kg1 Qb6 35. Qe2 Qd4 36. e5 Nd7 37. Ne4 Nxe5 38. Nxe5 Qxe5 39. Qxg4+ Bg7 40. Qf3
Rb8 41. Kg2 f5 42. Ng5 Qd5 43. Kf1 Qxf3 44. Nxf3 Bc3 45. Ng5 e5 46. g4 fxg4 47.
Ne4 Bd4 48. Ke2 Kf7 49. Kd3 Ke6 50. Kc4 Rc8+ 51. Kd3 Bc3 52. Rb1 Rd8+ 53. Ke3
Bd4+ 54. Ke2 Rb8 55. Rb3 Kd5 56. Nd2 Rf8 57. f3 g3 58. Kf1 Bc3 0-1


