Attack, 9 Bc4 Bd7 10 0-0-0 Rc8} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5.
Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 Nc6 8. Qd2 O-O 9. Bc4 Bd7 10. O-O-O Rc8 11. Nxc6 {
And there's that move again but making its debut on the site for the first
time in this particular position. To be fair Black has three plausible ways to
recapture but whereas ...bxc6 might be automatic in other scenarios where
White can't then flick in e4-e5, the whole bringing the rook to the (once)
half-open c-file is basically time wasted and arguably detrimental. In
addition of course, White's light-squared bishop would not require withdrawal
either. As the pawn would control the d5-square, I wouldn't rule that out but
with the rook recapture immediately hitting the bishop, the talented Indian's
choice feels like a reasonable middle ground!} ({Relevant to my comments to
Black's 12th move in this game,} 11. Bb3 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 b5 {is of course the
Topalov System where in some hopefully useful Maths, amongst the main 4 moves,}
13. Nd5 {is played 57% of the time, 13 h4 19% of the time, 13 Bxa7 appears 14%
with 13 e5 just 10%.}) 11... Bxc6 {The bishop controls the d5-square with the
option for a discovered attack against its opposite number with the d7-square
vacated for the knight too.} 12. Bb3 {[%cal Oh2h4] The natural retreat that
deals with the just hinted at threat of ...Bxe4.} (12. Bxa7 b6 13. e5 Nd7 14.
exd6 e6 $17) 12... a5 {Here basically is the split in plans for Black. The
text looks to put the bishop to good use by bringing ...a4 to the party but of
course as in the game he must be prepared for White to immediately halt this
pawn himself. The other move which suggests itself is} (12... b5 $5 {[%eval 50,
20] 12...a5 0.14 which the eagle-eyed amongst you may have noticed is just a
Topalov System but with White's bishop on e3 rather than d4 and Black's bishop
on c6 rather than d7. With that comparison in mind, it strikes me that the 57%
13 Nd5 move is off the table as a threat given Black can simply trade it for
his bishop (currently on c6 rather than d7!) whilst 13 e5 is poor. I think the
race is looking okay for Black after 13 h4 a5 and that then goes some way to
explaining why practical play has seen} 13. Bxa7 b4 {when} 14. Nd5 Nxd5 $1 15.
exd5 Qa5 $1 16. dxc6 ({Upon} 16. Be3 {[%eval -46,24] 16.dxc6 0.27} Ba4 {
will bring forth plenty of a-file pressure.}) ({Note} 16. Bd4 Bxd5 $1 17. Bxg7
$2 {[%eval -425,21]} ({White should play} 17. Qg5 $15 {[%eval -56,22]} Rc5 18.
Qe3 Bxb3 19. Qxb3 Bxd4 20. Rxd4) 17... Bxb3 {would be winning for Black.})
16... Qxa7 {has occurred in practice e. g.} 17. Qxb4 Rxc6 18. Rhe1 $1 Ra6 (
18... e6 {(looking to get in ...d5)} 19. Rxd6 Qe7 $1 20. Rd4 $1 Qg5+ 21. f4
Qxg2 22. Rd2 $1 {would also be imbalanced fun. Black's kingside is rock solid
whilst it will be difficult for White to advance his big queenside pawn
majority with so many pieces on.}) 19. Rd5 {with clear half-open files, Dragon
bishop etc. compensation for the pawn in Paravyan,D (2601)-Zakhartsov,V (2547)
Sochi RUS 2023.}) 13. a4 {Obviously making it more difficult to get in ...b5
though this weakens the b4-square and the bishop position on b3.} Qe8 $1 14.
Qe2 {White is slightly better.} ({Preventing the ...b5 break which given say} 
14. h4 {[%eval -1,22] 14.Qe2 0.43} b5 15. axb5 Bxb5 16. h5 {[%eval -103,21]} ({
Better is} 16. Bh6 $15 {[%eval -44,21]} Bxh6 17. Qxh6) 16... a4 $1 $17 17. Ba2
