1. e4 ({I feel compelled to include some comments on a line I played in the
past with similar patterns, definitely thematically but also psychologically.} 
1. b3 e5 2. Bb2 Nc6 3. Nf3 e4 4. Nd4 (4. Ne5 $6 Nxe5 5. Bxe5 {and now even} h5
$5 $15 {is decidedly unpleasant for White.}) 4... Qf6 (4... Nf6 {was played by
my opponent in Fernandez,D-Hawkins,J Cardiff 2014, after about half an hour of
considering calling my bluff!}) 5. e3 Bc5 {In this version, White is best off
not supporting the d4-knight a second time.} 6. Nc3 $1 (6. c3 Nge7 {is at
least equal for Black since the e4-pawn exerts a cramping influence.}) 6...
Nxd4 7. Nd5 Nf3+ (7... Qd6 8. exd4 Qxd5 9. dxc5 $40) 8. gxf3 Qxb2 9. Nxc7+ Kf8
10. Nxa8 $14 {With complications that are great fun to analyse (and slightly
better for White) but this is not the place.}) 1... c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3 b6 4. d4
cxd4 5. Nxd4 {The jury is out on whether I should really be claiming this
position as 'mine', but due to the 3.b3 (and overall rarity of White
fianchettoing the queen's bishop in non-Maroczy Open Sicilians) I think it's
fair enough.} Bb7 {There was another recent game that followed the same path,
and the choice of which one to use as the stem was not simple: 2700's, or
'better' opening play?!} 6. Bd3 {I'm not so sure this will gain many
supporters, while the alternative actually might.} ({The initially
clunky-looking} 6. Nd2 $5 {anticipates the challenge in the next note, and a
transposition to later on in the main game is quite likely (White can
typically proceed with Bd3 next move). But it seems like Black can go for it
anyway, provided they are willing to snatch a very hot pawn.} Bc5 7. Bb2 Qf6 8.
Nc4 $1 Qh4 (8... Bxe4 $6 9. Qd2 $1 $16 {is very slow for Black, and it doesn't
look like there's any acceptable defence to the idea of Nb5 next.}) 9. Be2 Bxe4
{For someone who was probably surprised by the opening, Black's reaction was
excellent.} 10. O-O (10. Qd2 Nc6 11. O-O-O Nf6 $132) 10... Nf6 11. Nb5 O-O 12.
Nc7 d5 $1 13. Nd2 Nc6 $1 (13... Bd6 $4 14. g3 Qh3 15. Nxe4 Bxc7 16. Nxf6+ gxf6
17. c4 $18 {Winning back a pawn due to the Bf3 ideas, and also bearing in mind
White's raking bishops it's not a surprise Black never really got another
chance in Erdos,V-Dotzer,L Mali Losinj 2023.}) 14. Nxa8 Rxa8 15. g3 Qh3 16.
Nxe4 dxe4 17. Bxf6 gxf6 $44 {Black probably has fair compensation here, though
it still needs to be proved.}) 6... Nc6 {It feels harsh to give such a move
the dubious mark, but in reality White's opening advantage is not in doubt
after it.} (6... Bc5 $5 {is the principled path.} 7. Bb2 (7. Be3 d5 $132) (7.
Nf3 {is safer but clearly fine for Black.} Nf6 8. Nbd2 Nc6 9. a3 $5 {
Buyandalai,T-Lock,G Uxbridge 2010} Qc7 $132) 7... Qf6 {If not for this move,
there is little point challenging quite so ardently on the previous move. But
this calls White's bluff.} 8. c3 Nc6 9. O-O (9. Na3 Nxd4 10. cxd4 Bxd4 11. Bxd4
Qxd4 12. O-O a6 $15 {fails to convince}) ({I don't think anyone really wants
to play moves like} 9. Bc2 {, and almost anything is OK for Black here.} Ba6 $5
10. Qd2 Rc8 $15 {Jones,G-Khairullin,I Belfort 2005 incidentally your columnist
was also playing this event in the under-10's!}) 9... Nxd4 10. b4 $1 $146 {
The only way White gets good play against 7...Qf6, but Black still has a good
choice between snatching the pawn on b4 (likely not very practical) or bailing
out with} Nf3+ 11. Qxf3 Qxf3 12. gxf3 Bd6 $11 {into an ending with almost no
chance of being worse.}) 7. Nxc6 Bxc6 ({It pays to keep an eye out for funky
possibilities like} 7... Qf6 {, but here this doesn't really question the
concept.} 8. Be3 $5 Bxc6 (8... Qxa1 $4 9. Bd4 Qxa2 10. Nc3 Qa3 11. Nb5 $18 {
is the point, forking the queen and mate!}) 9. Nd2 Bb4 10. O-O $14) 8. Bb2 Nf6
9. Qe2 (9. Nd2 {also sufficed for an advantage in a high level game,
especially after Black compliantly shut in the king's bishop.} d6 (9... d5 $1 {
improves, but probably not by enough. White can play the Rubinstein structure
with the simple exd5, or try a variety of other thematic 'French' approaches.}
10. e5 Ne4 11. Qe2 Nc5 12. h4 $5 $36) 10. Qe2 $16 {Vachier Lagrave,M-Van Wely,
L Dubai 2014}) 9... Bc5 10. Nd2 O-O 11. O-O-O Qe7 12. Kb1 $14 {The opening
phase is complete and it should be obvious from experience that White's
attacking chances are preferable, as well as that the middlegame is liable to
become rather complicated.} Ba3 13. Ba1 a5 14. g4 a4 15. g5 Ne8 16. Nc4 Bc5 17.
f4 f6 18. h4 d6 19. Rh2 axb3 20. cxb3 Qb7 21. Qg4 Qf7 22. h5 f5 23. exf5 exf5
24. Qg3 Qa7 25. Ne3 Be4 26. Bxe4 fxe4 27. Nd5 e3 28. Nxe3 Qe7 29. Nd5 Qe6 30.
h6 Qe4+ 31. Qd3 Qxd3+ 32. Rxd3 g6 33. b4 Ra4 34. bxc5 bxc5 35. Re2 1-0


