1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. g4 Be6 10. Nxe6 fxe6 11. Be2 $5 ({A very rare continuation and
certainly novelty for the site. Regulars will be only too aware that in this
still popular line, main theory runs} 11. O-O-O Ne5 12. Be2 {(followed by 12...
Qc8) but instead the Chinese superstar of the chessboard deploys a spot of
prophylaxis (regards the f3-pawn).}) 11... d5 ({Careless would be} 11... Ne5 $6
{(expecting to transpose after 12 0-0-0) because of} 12. g5 $1 Nh5 13. f4 Nf7
14. Bxh5 gxh5 {with undesirable h-pawns.}) ({Equally} 11... Qc8 12. O-O-O Ne5 {
would return to normal lines but again White doesn't have to allow a
transposition and could say delay long castles in favour of 12 h4!?.}) {
Instead we get the natural thematic response.} 12. exd5 {And now we are
surprisingly in a unique position.} ({On the few occasions that this position
has been reached, White has continued with} 12. O-O-O {when} Nxg4 (12... d4 13.
Bxd4 Nxd4 14. Qxd4 Qxd4 15. Rxd4 Nd5 16. Rc4 Nxc3 17. bxc3 Be5 {is completely
equal but I like the dynamic 12...Qa5! swiftly activating her majesty.}) 13.
exd5 ({The point obviously being} 13. fxg4 d4) 13... Nxe3 14. Qxe3 exd5 15.
Nxd5 e5 $6 {should have been met by 16 h4! in Majoros,R (1997)-Pacher,M (2437)
Budapest 2021 but wasn't!} (15... e6 $5 16. Qxe6+ Kh8 {on the other hand is a
more dynamic approach with active piece play for the pawn.})) 12... Nxd5 {
Opening up both the rook and Dragon bishop.} 13. Nxd5 exd5 ({As White has the
bishop pair, it's quite logical to keep the queens on although} 13... Qxd5 14.
c3 ({Maybe} 14. Qxd5 exd5 15. O-O-O {offers White a little something.}) 14...
Rad8 15. Qxd5 ({or} 15. Qc2 Ne5) 15... exd5 {should be fine.}) 14. O-O-O e6 ({
Protecting the d5-pawn. Instead} 14... d4 $5 15. Bf2 Qd5 16. Kb1 {is a tough
one to call. Black has a well placed queen and generally good pieces although
White has the bishop pair and fewer pawn islands (albeit with a target on f3).}
