1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. c3 d5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. d4 Nf6 6. Na3 a6 7. Nc4 Nbd7 8. Be2
{One of two main moves for White here.} (8. a4 $5 {is the other one, 1/2 (32)
-1/2 (32) Smerdon,D (2513)-David,A (2565) Tromso NOR 2014 [Smerdon, David]})
8... b5 $1 {[%mdl 4] This looks like the most critical response from Black.
outshines the older 8...cxd4. erfolgreicher als das alte 8...cxd4.} (8... cxd4
9. Nxd4 $1 (9. Qxd4 $5 {is also possible, but Black should be able to equalise
after} Bc5 $1 10. Qxd5 Nxd5 11. a4 b6 12. O-O {1-0 (44) Bacrot,E (2653)-Predke,
A (2684) chess.com INT 2023, and now} a5 $5 $11 {[%cal Gc8a6] should give
Black his fair share of the chances.}) 9... e5 10. Nf5 Nc5 11. Nfe3 $5 {
looks pretty good for White after} Qxd1+ 12. Nxd1 Nfd7 13. Nde3 b5 14. Na5 Nf6
15. Nc6 $1 $14 {as given by Dave Smerdon in the archives.}) 9. Ne3 {A natural
retreat, gaining a tempo.} (9. Na5 $5 Bd6 {Black wants to dislodge the Knight
on a5 with ...Bd6-c7.} (9... Be7 10. O-O $14 {This looks a bit better for
White. If Black tries to kick the Knight away with} Bd8 $4 {White has the very
strong response} 11. Ng5 $1 Qd6 {If the Black dark-squared Bishop was on c7,
Black would be threatening mate here!} 12. Bf3 h6 {1-0 (38) Demchenko,A (2625)
-Rahman,Z (2459) chess.com INT 2023. Now,} 13. Ne4 $1 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 Ra7 15. Nc6
{leads to a crushing advantage in the ending after} Rc7 16. Nxd8 Kxd8 17. dxc5
Qxd1 18. Rxd1 Rxc5 19. Be3 $18 {with the two Bishops for White and Black's
King in the centre.}) 10. c4 $1 {White makes use of the pawn on b5 to open up
the position.} bxc4 11. Nxc4 O-O {Black needs to finish his development, even
at the expense of the dark-squared Bishop.} 12. Nxd6 Qxd6 13. dxc5 {White
continues to open things up for his Bishops.} Qxc5 (13... Qxd1+ $5 {is also
quite possible.} 14. Bxd1 Nxc5 15. O-O a5 $11 {gives Black enough counterplay
on the light squares.}) 14. O-O a5 15. Be3 Qb4 $11 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gf6d5]
Black has an outpost on the d5-square and should be able to engineer the
exchange of light-squared Bishops with ...Bc8-a6. Therefore, White's pair of
Bishops isn't too threatening and chances are equal.}) (9. Nfd2 $5 {is a
tactical attempt to take advantage of Black's exposed major pieces on the long
diagonal. The calm} Ra7 $1 {is a sufficient response, however.} 10. Bf3 Qf5 11.
Ne3 Qf4 $1 {The Queen looks potentially vulnerable here but she can easily
retreat to the "Sicilian" square on c7.} (11... Qg6 $6 {0-1 (63) Saravana,K 
(2244)-Das,S (2475) New Delhi IND 2022. This leaves the Queen somewhat out of
play after} 12. O-O cxd4 13. cxd4 Be7 14. a4 $14 {since White can pursue his
initiative on the Queenside.}) 12. a4 cxd4 13. cxd4 Qc7 $5 {Protecting the
Rook on a7 and clearing the way for ...Bf8-d6.} 14. axb5 axb5 15. Rxa7 Qxa7 16.
Qc2 Qb8 $1 17. Qc6 Bd6 $11 {with castling to follow and equal chances for
Black.}) 9... Qc6 (9... Qd6 $6 {1-0 (38) Shaw,J (2480) -Hanley,C (2387)
Blackpool ENG 2003 [Gary Lane]}) 10. a4 (10. O-O Bb7 $6 {This has been the
most common move in practice, although the sample space of games is admittedly
very small.} (10... Be7 $5 {looks like the most accurate move-order,
prioritising castling before White can open the centre.} 11. a4 (11. c4 O-O $1
$11 {is no problem for Black.}) 11... Bb7 {transposes to the mainline.}) 11. a4
$6 (11. c4 $1 $146 {looks stronger. Black is best advised to continue
developing with} Be7 $1 {and allow complications that arise after} 12. d5 exd5
13. Nf5 $1 bxc4 $1 14. Nxg7+ Kd8 $1 15. Nf5 {when White is a pawn down but
with Black's King stuck in the centre. Black's position is probably
objectively fine but difficult to handle in practice. For example,} Re8 16. Re1
Ne4 17. Bf1 $1 Qg6 18. Nxe7 Rxe7 19. Bf4 $44 {with at least enough
compensation.}) 11... Be7 $1 {transposes to the mainline.} (11... b4 $2 {
is much weaker:} 12. Bd2 $1 (12. cxb4 $1 cxb4 13. Bd2 $16 {is also very strong.
}) 12... bxc3 13. Bxc3 Rc8 14. Rc1 $16 {gives White a big lead in development.}
) 12. dxc5 Qxc5 13. Qb3 {White tries to keep up the pressure, but Black has a
way to neutralise it:} Nd5 $1 {White won't be able to cash in on b5 yet due to
the threat of ...Nd5-f4.} (13... b4 $6 14. Bd2 Ne4 (14... bxc3 $5 15. Qxb7 {
With White's King tucked away safely on g1, ...c3xd2 doesn't come with check.}
Rb8 (15... Ra7 $4 16. b4 $1 {is a very important tactical point, which clearly
wouldn't work for White with the King still on e1!} Rxb7 17. bxc5 cxd2 18. c6
$18) 16. Qxa6 cxd2 17. Nxd2 O-O 18. b3 Qb4 19. Rfd1 $14 {Black doesn't have
quite enough for the pawn here.}) 15. Be1 $1 a5 {and now} 16. Bb5 Nef6 17. cxb4
axb4 18. Nc2 $1 Rc8 19. Nfd4 $1 $16 {looks strong for White.} (19. Nxb4 $5 $14
{is also good.})) 14. Nc2 {White covers f4 and maintains the pressure on b5.} (
14. axb5 Nf4 $1 15. Nd4 Nxe2+ (15... O-O $5 $44 {gives Black good compensation.
}) 16. Nxe2 Qxb5 $11 {looks fine for Black.}) (14. Nxd5 Bxd5 15. Qc2 b4 16. Be3
Qc7 $11 {is nothing for White.}) 14... Qb6 $1 {Black clears the way for his
Knight to reach c5 with tempo.} 15. axb5 Nc5 16. Qc4 O-O $1 {Black has
excellent compensation. A sample line is} 17. Nfd4 axb5 18. Qxb5 Qc7 19. Rxa8
Rxa8 20. Nb4 Nxb4 (20... Ra5 $5 $44 {is also fine.}) 21. Qxb4 Ra4 $11 22. Qb5
Ra5 23. Qe8+ {After 23.Qb4 Black is not obliged to repeat the position and can
continue with 23...Bd6 with multiple threats.} (23. Qb4 {Black can repeat or
play on with} Bd6 $5 $44 (23... Ra4 $11)) 23... Bf8 $11 {repeats.} 24. Nb5 Qe5
25. Nd4 Ra2 $44 {Black has tremendous activity for the pawn. This whole line
looks fine for Black, but I'd prefer to start with 10...Be7 in order to avoid
the 11 c4! possibility.} (25... Qc7 $11 {repeats.})) 10... Bb7 $1 {This was
considered best by Gary Lane in the archives, and I think he was right!} (10...
Rb8 {is somewhat cooperative, and White has an edge following} 11. axb5 axb5
12. O-O Be7 13. dxc5 Qxc5 14. Nd4 $14 {1/2-1/2 (56) Alsina Leal,D (2480)
-Martinez Alcantara,J (2561) Linares ESP 2018}) (10... b4 {is exactly what
White is hoping for:} 11. cxb4 cxb4 12. Bd2 $16 {with a strong initiative on
the Queenside, 1-0 (28) Zhigalko,S (2669) -Hoffmann,M (2471) Bad Wiessee GER
2016}) 11. axb5 {White decides to release the tension along the a-file.} (11.
dxc5 {is another possibility, recommended by Lorenzini in his Alapin database
for Modern Chess.} Qxc5 {Black wants to meet Qd1-b3 with ...b5-b4.} ({
Capturing with the Bishop is probably slightly weaker after} 11... Bxc5 $6 12.
axb5 axb5 13. Rxa8+ Bxa8 14. Nd4 $14 {with strong pressure for White.}) 12.
axb5 (12. Qb3 $5 {is another try, keeping the tension for the moment.} b4 $1
13. O-O {White castles before trying to increase the pressure on the b-pawn.} (
13. Bd2 $6 {illustrates what happens if White plays with the King on e1:} bxc3
$1 14. Qxb7 cxd2+ $1 {This check saves Black: Compare with the analogous lines
after 10 0-0.} 15. Nxd2 Ra7 16. Qb3 Be7 $11 {followed by castling, with equal
chances.}) 13... Rb8 $11 {Black's Queenside is secured and he can look forward
to finishing his Kingside development.}) 12... axb5 13. Rxa8+ Bxa8 14. Nd4 {
This is the most ambitious attempt for White, inducing} b4 {which can be met by
} 15. Qa4 {although Black is holding after} Qc8 16. O-O bxc3 17. bxc3 Bc5 18.
Nb3 O-O $1 19. Nxc5 Nxc5 20. Qa7 $14 {Lorenzini stops here claiming an edge
for White, but my engine disagrees claiming zeroes after} Nce4 $11 {for
example. The fact that Black's position is weakness-free and White has no
targets on the Queenside negates the potential superiority of White's two
Bishops.}) 11... axb5 12. Rxa8+ Bxa8 13. O-O (13. dxc5 {would transpose to the
note to White's eleventh move.}) 13... Bd6 $6 {This leaves the Bishop somewhat
exposed.} (13... Be7 $1 {is safer, with no problems for Black after} 14. dxc5
Qxc5 $11) 14. dxc5 Qxc5 15. Qd4 $6 $146 {Not the most challenging attempt from
White.} ({Predecessor:} 15. Nc2 O-O 16. Be3 Qc7 17. Ncd4 Qb8 18. Bxb5 Ne5 19.
Be2 Neg4 20. Bc1 Bxh2+ 21. Kh1 {0-1 (27) Yoo,C (2532)-Praggnanandhaa,R (2624)
Chess.com INT 2022}) (15. Nd4 $1 {looks like the best way to take advantage of
the Bishop on d6.} b4 16. Nb5 Be7 17. cxb4 Qb6 {The Queen must protect the
c7-square. This gives White the opportunity to safeguard his extra pawn on b4
with} 18. Qc2 O-O 19. Bd2 $14 {retaining a slight advantage.}) (15. Bxb5 $5 {
is another tactical opportunity for White, but Black seems to be OK following}
Bxh2+ $1 16. Nxh2 Qxb5 17. Qd6 Qc5 $1 18. Qxc5 Nxc5 19. b4 Nd3 20. Rd1 Nxc1 21.
Rxc1 Kd7 $132 {Even though White's Queenside passers look scary, Black's
pieces should be sufficiently active to hold the balance.}) 15... Qc7 $6 {
Probably not the most accurate, although Black's position is also solid enough
after this retreat.} (15... Bxf3 $1 {seems to be a cleaner equaliser.} 16. Bxf3
O-O 17. Rd1 Qxd4 18. Rxd4 (18. cxd4 Nb6 $11 {looks very solid for Black.})
18... Bc5 19. Rd1 Ne5 20. Be2 Rb8 $11 {Black seems to have enough play despite
White's pair of Bishops due to his active pieces.}) 16. Qh4 $6 {This fails to
pose any challenges for Black.} (16. Bxb5 $1 {is critical. Black seems to have
enough compensation after} O-O $1 17. Rd1 Bc5 18. Qa4 Bxf3 19. gxf3 Ne5 20. Be2
Qb7 $44 {with counterplay against White's somewhat exposed King.}) 16... Bxf3
$1 17. Bxf3 O-O 18. Be2 Rb8 $11 {We've seen similar positions in some of the
earlier notes. Black is very solid and White's pieces don't coordinate very
well.} 19. Rd1 h6 (19... b4 $5 $132 {also gives Black enough counterplay.}) 20.
g3 {White tries to blunt the attack on h2 and free his Queen for active duty.}
(20. Nc2 {attempts to free the dark-squared Bishop, but Black's Knights are
hopping all over the place after} Ne5 21. Bf4 Nd5 22. Bg3 Nc4 $11 {with plenty
of activity.}) 20... Ne5 {Black's activity is becoming somewhat troubling for
White and he should seek exchanges.} 21. Bd2 $6 (21. Ng4 $5 {is better, but
Black is still fine after} Nfxg4 22. Bxg4 Be7 23. Qh5 Bf6 $1 $11 {[%cal Gb5b4]
With ...b5-b4 to follow, Black has enough play.}) 21... Ra8 $15 22. Qh3 $6 {
The Queen remains out of play here.} (22. c4 $5 {is a better try.} b4 23. Nc2
Ng6 24. Qd4 Bc5 25. Qd3 Ne5 26. Qb3 Qb7 $15 {only slightly favours Black.})
22... Ra2 $6 {This is natural and works out perfectly in the game, but it's
not the most accurate way for Black to pursue the initiative.} (22... Bc5 $1
$17 {[%cal Gf6e4,Ga8a2,Gc7a7] is a very strong preparatory move. Black follow
up by invading on a2 with the Rook and placing the Queen on a7, with ...Nf6-e4
also looking like a powerful idea. White is under serious pressure.}) 23. Rb1
$4 {The Rook is too passive here.} (23. Bc1 $1 {holds firm and limits Black to
a slight edge after} Bc5 $15) 23... Ne4 $1 24. Be1 Bc5 $19 {Black now has a
decisive advantage and doesn't let the win slip.} 25. Qg2 f5 26. Nc2 $6 (26.
Bxb5 {was a better try, but Black is still winning after} Bxe3 27. fxe3 Qb6 28.
Qe2 Ng5 $19 {with a very strong attack.}) 26... b4 27. c4 Qb6 (27... b3 28. Na1
Qb7 $19 {looks even better.}) 28. Bf3 b3 {White is bound to lose material
sooner or later.} 29. Bxe4 fxe4 30. Ne3 Bxe3 31. fxe3 (31. Qxe4 {is preferred
by the engine, but Black is obviously winning after} Bd4 $19) 31... Qxe3+ 32.
Qf2 Nf3+ (32... Qd3 {is also crushing:} 33. Rc1 Ng4 34. Qd2 Qxd2 35. Bxd2 Rxb2
$19 {with an easy win.}) 33. Kg2 Nxe1+ (33... Qd3 $19 {also works, but Black
sees that the Rook ending is winning and goes for that instead.}) 34. Rxe1
Qxf2+ 35. Kxf2 Rxb2+ 36. Ke3 Rxh2 $19 {Black has too many extra pawns.} 37.
Kxe4 Kf7 38. Re3 Rc2 39. Kd4 b2 40. Rb3 h5 41. c5 g5 42. c6 Kf6 {It looks like
Black can successfully solve his problems after 8 Be2 b5 regardless of which
Knight move White goes for.} 0-1


