1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 b6 {John Emms: 'This traditional approach
to the Nimzo was a favourite of mine (and others) in my youth. It's refreshing
to see that it's still occasionally played at the elite level, despite the
challenge 5 Nge2 poses.'} 5. Nge2 Ne4 6. Qc2 Bb7 (6... f5 $6 {Committing to f5
at such an early stage should be slightly dubious.} 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. Nxc3 Nxc3 (
8... Bb7 9. d5 $5) 9. Qxc3 Bb7 10. b4 (10. d5 $5 Qe7 (10... Qf6 11. Bd2 O-O (
11... exd5 12. cxd5 $16) 12. Qxf6 Rxf6 13. Bc3 {Doesn't look like fun for black
}) (10... O-O 11. b4) 11. Be2 O-O 12. b4 $14) 10... O-O (10... d6 11. Bb2 Nd7
12. d5 $14 (12. c5 {Yedidia,D (2041)-Cordova,E (2543) 32nd Chicago Open 2023 
(3) 0-1})) 11. Bb2 d6 12. d5 e5 13. Bd3 Nd7 14. O-O Rf7 15. f4 $16 {Franco
Alonso,A (2389)-Tejedor Fuentes,E (2453) TCh-ESP Div Honor 2019 (7.4) ½-½
This is the type of position that black should try to avoid getting in this
line with 6.Qc2. White has pressure in the long diagonal a1-h8 and space
advantage while black lacks a plan to get counterplay.}) 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. Nxc3 (
8. bxc3 $6 {Doesn't make much sense. If white wanted to get the doubled pawns
he should have refrained from playing Qc2.} f5 (8... Qh4 $5 9. Nf4 f5 $15 {
[%cal Yb8c6]}) 9. f3 Qh4+ 10. g3 Qe7 11. Bg2 Nd6 $1 (11... Ng5 {Nakhbayeva,G 
(2371)-Cramling,P (2465) World Rapid Women 2018 (9.14) 0-1}) 12. c5 Nc4 $15) {
Kapnisis,Spyridon: '[#]'} 8... Nxc3 {Kapnisis,Spyridon: '!' Kapnisis,Spyridon:
'Exchanging the knights is the right way to continue with black. Keeping the
knights on the board by playing f5 gives white some interesting options.'} (
8... f5 $6 9. Ne2 $5 {is a somewhat strange looking proposal of Stockfish 16.}
(9. Bd3 Nxc3 10. Qxc3 Qg5 $1 {poses more problems to white and keeps the
