1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. h3 O-O 6. cxd5 Nxd5 7. e4 Nxc3 8.
bxc3 c5 9. Be2 Nc6 {Flear,Glenn: 'This has established itself as the main move
here.'} ({For the alternatives} 9... b6 {see Grachev, B - Turov, M Tuapse 2022,
and for 9...b5 Bluebaum, M - Svidler, P Chessable online rapid 2020, in the
archives.}) 10. Be3 cxd4 ({The immediate} 10... Qa5 {was chosen in Babula, V -
Menezes, C Czech league 2022, a game that I analyzed for ChessPublishing.}) 11.
cxd4 Qa5+ 12. Bd2 Qa3 13. d5 Ne5 14. O-O {Flear,Glenn: 'The most popular of
the three 'reasonable' possibilities here, but do any of them give the
opponent anything to worry about?'} ({In the case of} 14. Rb1 Nxf3+ 15. Bxf3 {
it seems best to take the bait:} Qxa2 ({in Nguyen Ngoc Truong Son - Laylo, D
Ho Chi Minh City 2015, Black continued with} 15... b6 {but my analysis at the
time suggested that it was inferior, see the archives}) 16. O-O a5 {(pushing
the a-pawn generates counterplay and basically brings the a8-rook into the
game, so there's no pressing need to develop the c8-bishop here)} 17. Re1 a4
18. Bb4 Re8 19. Qd3 b6 {(careful, the black queen is on the verge of getting
trapped, so some evasive action is required)} ({possible is} 19... b5 {as} 20.
Qxb5 Ba6 21. Qc5 Rac8 {would offer good play for Black}) 20. e5 Bf5 $1 {
(the best way to attack the opposing queen)} 21. Be4 Bxe4 22. Qxe4 Rac8 23. Ra1
Qb3 {Wojtaszek, R - Giri, A Julius Baer rapid 2022, and Black is fine, even if
White has more or less enough compensation.}) ({After the similar-looking} 14.
Nxe5 Bxe5 15. O-O {there is (compare with the main game) a neat bishop
manoeuvre that Maghsoodloo has previously employed (with Black):} Bd7 $1 16.
Rb1 Ba4 17. Qc1 Qxa2 $1 18. Rxb7 ({alternatively,} 18. Bc4 Qc2 19. Rxb7 Qxc1
20. Rxc1 Rfb8 $1 {(best)} 21. Rxb8+ Rxb8 22. Ba6 Bb5 23. Bxb5 Rxb5 24. Kf1 f5
$11 {Harikrishna, P - Vachier-Lagrave, M Mayrhofen 2022}) 18... Rfc8 19. Rxa7
Rxc1 20. Rxa8+ Rc8 $1 (20... Kg7 21. Bxc1 Qxe2 22. Rxa4 {gives White a
favourable version}) 21. Rxc8+ Kg7 22. Bd1 Qxd2 23. Bxa4 Qf4 24. g3 Qxe4 {
Parligras, M - Maghsoodloo, P German league 2022, and only Black has winning
chances.}) 14... Bd7 (14... Bxh3 {- 80/475}) ({After} 14... Nxf3+ 15. Bxf3 {
play can become quite sharp, but what to capture first?:} Bxh3 (15... Bxa1 16.
Qxa1 f6 17. Rb1 a5 (17... Rf7 $146 {is suggested by Stockfish as best, but
this needs testing}) 18. Bh6 $1 (18. e5 fxe5 19. Qxe5 Qd6 ({Black seems to be
OK after} 19... Rxf3 $1 20. gxf3 Qxf3 21. Bc3 Qf6 22. Qg3 Qf5 $11) 20. Qe3 e6
$2 {(the wrong idea altogether)} 21. dxe6 (21. Bc3 $1 $18) 21... Qxe6 22. Qd4
Qf6 $2 (22... Rxf3 $1 {is the lesser evil}) 23. Bd5+ Kg7 24. Qe3 Qd6 25. Bc3+
Rf6 26. Rb6 {1-0 Ilner, A - Wantiez, F Belgian league 2015}) 18... Rf7 19. e5 (
19. Rb6 $5 Ra6 20. Rb5 {is Stockfish's mysterious idea}) 19... fxe5 20. Qxe5
Qd6 21. Qe3 b5 {(otherwise the pressure is too unpleasant, but White remains
on top)} 22. Rxb5 Rb8 23. Qb3 Rxb5 24. Qxb5 Qd7 25. Qxa5 Bb7 $18 {Hossain, E -
Vakhidov, J Asian Hybrid Tornelo 2021, and Black was clearly not happy}) ({
pushing the a-pawn makes a lot of sense whether White leaves his rook on a1 or
moves it to b1, as it's a source of potential counterplay:} 15... a5 $5 16. Re1
Bxa1 17. Qxa1 f6 18. e5 fxe5 19. Qxe5 Qd6 20. Qxe7 (20. Qd4 $5 Rf6 $5) 20...
Qxe7 21. Rxe7 Rf7 22. Re8+ Rf8 23. Re5 Rf5 {Makarian, R - Sjugirov, S Russian
league 2021, and Black holds firm}) 16. Rb1 Bd7 17. Bb4 Qxa2 18. Bxe7 Rfe8 19.
d6 Bc6 20. e5 Bxf3 21. Qxf3 Qe6 22. Qxb7 $16 {Indjic, A - Paravyan, D Almaty
blitz 2022, and the advanced d-pawn ensures a white advantage. As far as I can
see, both fifteen move captures are acceptable, but in both cases a precise
follow-up will be required. If these don't appeal, then 15...a5 has its points
as well.}) 15. Rb1 Ba4 ({At this point} 15... Qxa2 {seems playable, but is
perhaps not best:} 16. Rxb7 Ba4 17. Qc1 {(this natural queen move doesn't lead
to any advantage)} ({see the note to Black's sixteenth for} 17. Qe1 $1 $14)
17... Rac8 $1 (17... Rfc8 $2 18. Rxa7 $1 Rxc1 $4 {(he seems to have his lines
mixed up!)} 19. Rxa8+ Bf8 20. Bxc1 Nd7 21. Bd1 $18 {Tari, A - Van Foreest, J
Chessable Masters 2021}) 18. Qe1 Rc2 19. Rxa7 Nxf3+ 20. Bxf3 Rxd2 21. Rxa4 Qb2
22. Ra7 Re8 23. Rb7 Qd4 {Cramling, P - Kulaots, K Swedish league 2022, and
despite being a pawn down, Black's activity ensures that he has easy equality.}
) 16. Qe1 (16. Qc1 {could transpose to the previous note and was indeed the
move order in Craming, P - Kulaots, K, see above.}) 16... Nd3 {Flear,Glenn:
'!' Flear,Glenn: 'Eliminating the opponent's light-square bishop seems best.
This possibility isn't available in the analogous variation involving 14.Nxe5
Bxe5 15.0-0 (see the note to White's fourteenth move).'} ({Here} 16... Qxa2 {
definitely seems inferior:} {Flear,Glenn: 'see the note to Black's sixteenth
for'} 17. Rxb7 {Flear,Glenn: '+/=!'} Rfb8 18. Rxe7 Bf6 $2 ({there would still
be some hope after} 18... Nxf3+ 19. Bxf3 Bf6 20. Rc7 Be5 21. Rc1 Bb5 22. Be2
Bxe2 23. Qxe2 a5 $14 {with some compensation for the pawn}) 19. Rxe5 $1 Rb2 20.
Rg5 $5 {(a pretty idea, but not the only way)} Bxg5 $2 21. Bxg5 Rxe2 22. Qb4
Rc8 23. Ne5 h6 24. Qe7 {1-0 Kavutskiy, K - Tiglon, B San Jose 2022.}) 17. Bxd3
Qxd3 18. Bg5 Rfe8 {Diagram [#]} ({Instead,} 18... h6 $2 {is too provocative:}
19. Bxe7 Rfe8 20. Rxb7 Qa6 21. Qb4 $1 Rac8 22. d6 Bc3 23. Qb1 Bc2 24. Qb5 Qxb5
25. Rxb5 $18 {Grischuk, A - Puranik, A Titled Tuesday online blitz 2022, and
the passed d-pawn wins the day.}) 19. Qb4 $146 {Flear,Glenn: 'Finally, we
arrive on virgin territory.'} ({Flear,Glenn: 'Previously, in the two games
that had reached this position, both players captured on b7:'} 19. Rxb7 Bb5 20.
Bxe7 Qxf1+ 21. Qxf1 Bxf1 22. Kxf1 {Flear,Glenn: '(the unbalanced
pseudo-endgame that follows is equal acording to Stockfish)'} Rab8 (22... Bf8
23. Bxf8 Kxf8 24. Ng5 h6 25. Nxf7 Rab8 26. Rxb8 Rxb8 $11 27. Ne5 {Grischuk, A
- Antipov, M Titled Tuesday online blitz 2022.}) 23. Rxa7 Bf8 24. Bxf8 Kxf8 25.
Ng5 h6 26. Nxf7 Rxe4 27. g3 Re7 $11 {Flear,Glenn: 'Sevian, S - Vachier-Lagrave,
M Chess.com rapid 2022'}) 19... b5 20. Rbc1 (20. Bxe7 a5 21. Qd6 b4 22. Rbc1
Bc3 23. e5 Ra6 24. Qc5 Qb5 $13) 20... a5 21. Qc5 {Flear,Glenn: 'Instead of
grabbing pawns, Maghsoodloo gives up his own e-pawn in his quest for the
initiative.'} Qxe4 22. Rfe1 Qf5 23. g4 {Flear,Glenn: 'Chasing the royal
intruder back into it's own camp.'} (23. Bxe7 Rac8 24. Qd6 Rxc1 (24... Rc4 25.
Rxc4 bxc4 26. Qa3 Qd7 27. d6 Qb5 $15) 25. Rxc1 b4 $15) 23... Qc8 (23... Qxf3 $4
{drops the queen to} 24. Re3) 24. Bxe7 {Diagram [#] Flear,Glenn: 'Only now!
The passed d-pawn might seem to be more dangerous than the queenside majority,
but the silicon experts assure me that it's still equal.'} b4 (24... Qxc5 $1
25. Rxc5 (25. Bxc5 $6 b4 $15) 25... Rxe7 26. Rxe7 Bf8 27. d6 (27. Rec7 Bxc5 28.
Rxc5 b4 29. Ne5 b3 30. axb3 Bxb3 31. d6 a4 32. d7 Be6 33. Ra5 Rd8 34. Rxa4 Kf8
35. Rd4 f6 $11) 27... Bxe7 28. dxe7 f6 29. Rd5 Re8 30. Nd4 Rxe7 31. Nxb5 Bxb5
32. Rxb5 Re5 33. Rxe5 fxe5 34. Kg2 Kf7 35. Kf3 Ke6 $11) 25. Qe3 Qb7 26. d6 Rac8
27. Ng5 Rxc1 28. Rxc1 Qd5 29. Qf4 Qxa2 {Diagram [#] Flear,Glenn: '?!' Flear,
Glenn: 'A key decision which proves to be a questionable one.'} ({Flear,Glenn:
'A safeish equality could be achieved with exchanges:'} 29... Bh6 $1 30. Qc4 (
30. Rc5 Bxg5 31. Qxg5 Qxa2 (31... Qxg5 $6 32. Bxg5 Re1+ 33. Kh2 Rd1 34. Bf6 Bd7
35. Rxa5 Bc6 36. Be7 $14) 32. Kg2 Qe6 33. Qf4 f6 $13) 30... Qxc4 31. Rxc4 f5 (
31... Bxg5 32. Bxg5 Re6 $11) 32. Nf3 fxg4 33. hxg4 Bf8 34. Bxf8 Kxf8 35. Rc5
Rd8 36. Rxa5 Bd1 37. Ne5 Rxd6 $11) 30. Rc4 $1 f5 $2 {Flear,Glenn: 'Despite
Erigaisi wanting to seek confusion and perhaps solace in the complications,
the tactics don't really work for him.'} ({Flear,Glenn: 'The best chance was'} 
30... f6 31. Ne4 (31. Ne6 $145 Bb5 $1 32. Nxg7 (32. Rc5 Qxe6 33. Rxb5 Bf8 $11)
32... Qxc4 33. Qxc4+ Bxc4 34. Nxe8 Kf7 35. Nxf6 b3 36. Ne4 b2 37. Nc3 a4 38.
Nb1 Ba2 39. Na3 b1=Q+ 40. Nxb1 Bxb1 $11 {Perunovic,Milos}) 31... g5 {Flear,
Glenn: 'when many an opponent would bail out by capturing on f6 (32.Nxf6+ Bxf6
33.Qxf6 Qxc4 34.Qxg5+ etc.) thus taking a perpetual. Nevertheless, White could
certainly try for more with'} 32. Qc1 (32. Nxf6+ Bxf6 33. Qxf6 Qxc4 34. Qxg5+
Kf7 35. Qf6+ Kg8 36. Qg5+ Kf7 $11) 32... b3 33. Nc3 b2 $1 34. Qf1 (34. Nxa2
bxc1=Q+ 35. Nxc1 Bd7 36. Rc7 Rc8 37. Rxd7 Rxc1+ 38. Kg2 {Flear,Glenn: '+/='
Flear,Glenn: 'but this is probably defensible.'} Kf7 39. Ra7 Rd1 40. Bd8+ (40.
Rxa5 Bf8 $11) 40... Ke8 41. Bxa5 Bf8 $1 42. Bc3 h6 43. Bxf6 Rxd6 44. Bb2 Re6
$11) 34... Qb3 35. Rxa4 Qxc3 36. d7 Rb8 37. Rc4 Qb3 38. Rc8+ Kf7 39. Qb1 Qxh3
40. d8=Q Qxg4+ 41. Kf1 Qh3+ 42. Kg1 Qg4+ $11) 31. gxf5 h6 32. f6 $2 {Flear,
Glenn: '?!'} ({Flear,Glenn: 'The engine gives the strange-looking'} 32. Kg2 $1
{Flear,Glenn: 'as basically winning, a typical continuation being'} Bb5 (32...
hxg5 33. Qe4 gxf5 34. Qe6+ Kh8 35. Rh4+ $18 gxh4 36. Qxa2 $18) 33. f6 $1 Bxc4
34. fxg7 hxg5 (34... Bd5+ 35. Kg3 $18) 35. Qf8+ Kh7 36. Qxe8 Bd5+ 37. Kg3 Bg8
38. d7 $18) 32... hxg5 33. f7+ Kh7 34. fxe8=Q gxf4 35. Qf7 {Diagram [#] Flear,
Glenn: 'The new queen replaces the old one. Now, with an extra exchange in the
tense middlegame it would seem that White is on top. However, it turns out
that Black is OK if he is precise, but this is no easy task, especially just
coming up to move forty.'} Be8 $2 ({Flear,Glenn: 'Correct is'} 35... Qa1+ {
Flear,Glenn: '!'} 36. Kh2 (36. Kg2 Bb3 37. Qxf4 (37. d7 Bxc4 38. Qxc4 f3+ $1 {
and, in all cases, the d-pawn will be seized before it promotes}) 37... Bxc4
38. Qh4+ Bh6 39. Qxc4 Qe5 $11 {with the well-placed black queen thwarting any
efforts to promote the d-pawn.}) 36... Bb3 37. d7 (37. Bh4 Bxc4 38. Qxc4 Qc3
39. Qxc3 bxc3 40. d7 c2 41. d8=Q c1=Q 42. Qxa5 $11) 37... Qf1 $1 38. Qxf4 Be5
$1 39. Qxe5 (39. Bc5 Bxf4+ 40. Rxf4 g5 $1 41. d8=Q gxf4 $11) 39... Qxf2+ $11 {
Flear,Glenn: 'with a draw! How many folk would have found that, I wonder!?'})
36. Qxf4 b3 37. d7 $1 Bxd7 38. Qf7 {Flear,Glenn: '+-!' Flear,Glenn: 'Now the
threat of Rh4+ forces desperate measures, but these come to naught.'} Qa1+ 39.
Kg2 Bxh3+ 40. Kh2 $1 $18 Qe5+ 41. Kxh3 Qf5+ 42. Qxf5 gxf5 43. Rc7 Kg6 44. Ba3
Be5 45. Rc5 Bd4 46. Rxa5 Bxf2 47. Rb5 1-0


