1. b3 d5 2. Bb2 c5 {Black makes an uncompromising response to Larsen's Opening,
setting up a big centre.} 3. Nf3 {A natural developing move, but it does
invite Black's next.} (3. e3 {is more flexible, and the more popular move
overall.}) 3... f6 {This is Black's 2nd most common move here, and has been
essayed several times by Nakamura in blitz games. Instead:} (3... Nc6 4. e3 Nf6
5. Bb5 {is the kind of setup White is aiming for when playing this opening. Now
} Bd7 6. O-O e6 7. d3 Be7 8. Bxc6 Bxc6 9. Ne5 Rc8 10. Nd2 O-O 11. f4 {reaches
a tabiya analyzed in Wadsworth-Parligras in the Archives.}) 4. e4 $5 {The
critical line. The alternatives allow Black more central control:} (4. e3 e5 {
and after} 5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 e4 7. Nfd2 f5 8. c4 Nf6 9. Nc3 {when Black can
try:} Bd6 $1 {is a good novelty, giving White the d5-pawn in return for fast
development. After} (9... Be6 {has often been seen in practice. Now} 10. cxd5
Nxd5 11. Bb5+ Nc6 12. O-O Be7 13. Qh5+ (13. Nc4 O-O {completes Black's
development and leaves him clearly better due to superior central control,
Nepomniachtchi,I (2784)-Nakamura,H (2736) Lichess.org INT 2020 1-0 (31)}) 13...
g6 14. Qh6 {Kayumov,S (2505)-Hirneise,T (2466) Doha 2016 1-0 (55), and now} a6
{gives roughly balanced chances.}) 10. Nxd5 Nxd5 11. cxd5 O-O {Black is for
choice, since it is challenging for White to find permanent king safety.}) (4.
d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 e5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. e3 Be6 8. Be2 Bc5 9. O-O Nge7 {and Black was
fine in Xiong,J (2709)-Nakamura,H (2736) Chess.com INT 2020 0-1 (37)}) 4...
dxe4 {After:} (4... d4 {White can play} 5. e5 {and later on undermine Black's
pawn chain with c2-c3.}) 5. Nh4 g6 {Black prevents Qd1-h5+ and prepares to
fianchetto the f8-bishop, but the alternative:} (5... Nh6 {may be best. Now
White has tried:} 6. Nc3 {and again Black has the choice between a crazy and
sensible pawn thrust:} (6. g3 Nc6 7. Nc3 {and here} e5 {looks simply better
for Black.} (7... g5 {was the wild alternative played in Edouard,R (2640)-Van
Foreest,J (2644) Chess.com INT 2020 0-1 (27), but after} 8. Qh5+ Kd7 9. Ng2 Nd4
10. O-O-O {Black's exposed king leaves the second player in trouble.})) 6... e5
(6... g5 7. Qh5+ Kd7 8. Nxe4 {Not the most accurate.} (8. d3 {can also be
tried since} gxh4 $2 9. O-O-O {gives White a powerful attack}) 8... gxh4 9. d4
Nc6 (9... Kc7 {looks scary but leaves Black better according to the engine.})
10. d5 Ne5 $2 11. Bxe5 fxe5 {Gholami,A (2554)-O'Donnell,C (2345) New Delhi
2019 �-� (70), and now} 12. Bb5+ Kc7 13. Qxe5+ Kb6 14. Qxh8 {leaves White
well on top.}) 7. Nxe4 {Sopur,L (2419)-Malisauskas,V (2516) Police 2010 0-1 
(45), and now} Nc6 8. Bb5 Qb6 {is fine for Black.}) 6. Qe2 {A new move but
White had better:} (6. Nc3 {and now} e5 7. Bb5+ Bd7 8. Bxd7+ Nxd7 9. Nxe4 (9.
d3 $1 exd3 $6 10. Qxd3 {gives White a strong initiative}) 9... Nh6 10. Nf3 Nf7
11. Qe2 Bg7 12. h4 Qe7 13. O-O-O O-O-O {Travadon,L (2424)-Alekseenko,K (2696)
Chess.com INT 2020 1-0 (71) and now} 14. g4 {leaves White with an edge due to
the kingside space advantage.}) 6... Bg7 {Getting ready for the tactics, which
paid off in the game Instead:} (6... Nc6 7. Qxe4 e5 {gives Black a solid
Maroczy structure and chances to gain more time against White's queen.}) 7.
Qxe4 f5 8. Qa4+ Bd7 9. Bxg7 $4 {White either missed Black's 11th move, or
misjudged the resulting material imbalance. White had to continue:} (9. Qa3
Bxb2 10. Qxb2 Nf6 {which is approximately level.}) 9... Bxa4 10. bxa4 {Or:} (
10. Bxh8 Bc6 11. Bb2 e5 12. Nf3 Bxf3 13. gxf3 Nc6 {with a winning position for
Black.}) 10... Nf6 11. Bxh8 Qd4 {A key double attack on the h4-knight and
a1-rook!} 12. Nc3 Qxh4 13. Rb1 Nbd7 14. Rxb7 Kf7 15. Bxf6 Nxf6 16. Be2 Qd4 {
Black has queen for rook, bishop and pawn, but White has weaknesses - this
should have been a straightforward victory for Black.} 17. a5 Ne4 18. O-O Nxd2
19. Nb5 Qa4 20. Rd1 Qxc2 21. a6 {White starts to get a hint of counterplay but
the engine still evaluates this position as -6...} Rd8 22. h3 Nf3+ 23. gxf3
Rxd1+ 24. Bxd1 Qxd1+ 25. Kg2 Qa4 26. Nc7 c4 {It is not ideal to be starting a
race. Here:} (26... Qc6 {suppresses the counterplay involving the knight. After
} 27. Rxa7 c4 {there is nothing to be done.}) 27. Rxa7 c3 28. Nd5 Qc6 $4 (28...
Qa5 29. Rxe7+ Kf8 30. Rc7 Qxd5 {is still a technical win}) 29. Rxe7+ Kf8 30.
Nb4 $1 {Suddenly the a-pawn is on the brink of pushing through.} c2 (30... Qc4
$4 31. Rxh7 Qxb4 32. a7 {wins for White}) 31. Nxc6 c1=Q 32. a7 Qg5+ {Baling
out with a perpetual.} 33. Kf1 Qc1+ 34. Kg2 Qg5+ 35. Kh1 Qc1+ 36. Kg2 1/2-1/2


