1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 c5 5. d5 b5 (5... d6 6. e4 O-O 7. Bd3 b5 8.
cxb5 $5 {is another move order.}) 6. e4 d6 {is the new trend. ist der neue
Trend.} 7. cxb5 $5 {This move is rare, and for a good reason. In general
there's clearly some risk involved in accepting Black's ...b5 gambit in the f3
Nimzo. In addition, Stockfish's instant reaction is one of disapproval.
However, in today's game, deep preparation allows many more lines to be used
as weapons. It's also worth noting that Erigaisi played 7 cxb5 three times in
Almaty, and he scored three wins!} (7. Bd2) ({and} 7. Nge2 {are the most
common choices - see games in the archives.}) 7... exd5 8. exd5 O-O (8... Nbd7
$5) 9. Bd3 $1 ({Supporting the d5-pawn with} 9. Bc4 $6 {runs into problems
against} Nh5 $1 {with the awkward threat of ...Qh4+.}) 9... a6 {Typical play
from Grischuk, who aims for maximum activity.} (9... Nxd5 10. Nge2 $1 {looks
reasonable for White. For example, after} ({and better than} 10. Bxh7+ Kxh7 11.
Qxd5 Re8+) 10... Nf6 11. O-O d5 12. Bg5 {Black's centre isn't as impressive as
it looks.} Bb7 13. a3 Ba5 14. b4 $1 cxb4 15. axb4 Bxb4 $2 16. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 17.
Qb1+ {is a tactical idea which justifies White's strategy.}) ({Sacrificing
another pawn with} 9... Nbd7 10. Nge2 c4 $5 11. Bxc4 Ne5 {could also be
considered.}) 10. Nge2 $1 Qb6 {Preventing 0-0.} ({In an earlier round, Rapport
sacrificed his c-pawn:} 10... c4 $5 11. Bxc4 axb5 12. Bxb5 Qb6 13. a3 (13. Kf1
$5) 13... Bb7 {(Erigaisi,A-Rapport,R/Almaty 2022) and here} 14. Bf4 $1 Qxb5 15.
axb4 Qxb4 16. Rxa8 Bxa8 17. Qd2 {would favour White.}) ({In the World Blitz
Championship Erigaisi faced} 10... axb5 {and after} 11. Bxb5 Ba6 12. Bxa6 Nxa6
13. O-O Re8 14. Bg5 h6 15. Bh4 {White had some advantage in Erigaisi,
A-Donchenko,A/Almaty 2022.}) 11. a3 $146 ({Vorgänger:} 11. bxa6 Nbd7 $1 {
it's difficult to ignore Black's activity.} 12. Bf4 Re8 13. Kf1 Ne5 14. Bb5
Bxa6 15. a4 Bxb5 16. axb5 Rxa1 17. Qxa1 Bxc3 18. Nxc3 {0-1 (27) Touzane,O 
(2250)-Kiselev,S (2510) Podolsk 1991}) 11... axb5 ({There's also} 11... Bxc3+
12. bxc3 ({or} 12. Nxc3 Re8+ $1 13. Kf1 axb5 14. Bxb5 Ba6 {with excellent
compensation}) 12... axb5 13. Rb1 {with level chances.}) 12. Bxb5 Bxc3+ ({
Keeping the bishop and sacrificing the c-pawn is once again a tempting option:
} 12... c4 $5 13. Bxc4 Nbd7 {etc.}) 13. Nxc3 Ba6 14. Bxa6 Qxa6 15. Kf2 Nbd7 {
Black certainly enjoys some Benko-style compensation here, but with some
careful play Erigaisi is able to relieve some of the pressure.} 16. Qc2 Ne5 17.
Rd1 Rfe8 18. Bf4 Nfd7 19. Kg1 c4 20. Ne4 (20. Bg3 $1 Nd3 21. a4 $1 {is the
far-from-obvious way to dampen Black's initiative. The point is that} N7c5 {
can be met effectively by} 22. Nb5 $1 Qb6 23. Kh1) 20... Nd3 21. Bg3 N7e5 22.
Kh1 Rab8 23. Rab1 h6 {Preventing Ng5 in preparation of ...f5, but there was no
need to do so.} ({After} 23... f5 $1 24. Ng5 $6 (24. Nc3 Qa7 $1 {maintains the
pressure.}) 24... Rb3 $1 25. Ne6 Reb8 {Black can play around the knight on e6.}
) 24. h3 f5 25. Nc3 Qb6 26. Rd2 Qb3 {Black still has some play for the pawn
after the queen exchange, but the momentum of the game seems to shift here.} (
26... Qd4 {intending ...Rb3 makes sense.}) 27. a4 Qxc2 28. Rxc2 Rb4 29. Bh2 Nc5
30. Re1 (30. Nb5 $1 $16) 30... Ncd3 31. Rb1 Nc5 (31... Ra8 $1) 32. Re2 $1 Ra8
$2 (32... Kf7 {is more resilient, but by this stage White already had a
significant advantage.}) 33. Bxe5 dxe5 34. Rxe5 Rd8 35. a5 f4 36. d6 Nd3 37.
Rd5 Kf7 38. a6 Ke6 39. Ra1 Kd7 40. a7 Ra8 41. Nb5 Rxb2 42. Nc7 Rxa7 43. Rxa7
Rb1+ 44. Kh2 Nf2 45. g4 Nd3 46. Nb5+ Ke6 47. Nc3 Rb2+ 48. Kg1 1-0


