1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 Ne4 3. Bf4 d5 4. f3 {It's no surprise seeing Erigaisi playing
this way considering his like of Jobava-Prie positions in general.} Nf6 5. Nc3
a6 ({Keeping White out of b5. Even with the extra f2-f3 move compared to the
Jobava-Prie, I suspect that} 5... c5 6. e4 cxd4 7. Qxd4 Nc6 8. Bb5 Bd7 {
is also fine, as we examined in Gareev-Debarshi, Mumbai Open 2018. The latest
engines suggest that this should still be OK for Black.}) 6. e4 e6 {Sensibly
strong-pointing the centre.} 7. Qd2 $5 ({A new try for Erigaisi. This was the
second 10+10 play-off game and back in the first 25+10 one, he had preferred} 
7. Nge2 {, after which} c5 ({a good case can also be made for} 7... b5 $5 {
, and if} 8. a3 Bb7 9. Ng3 c5 {with promising looking counterplay}) 8. Qd2 Nc6
9. O-O-O dxe4 10. fxe4 cxd4 11. Nxd4 Qxd4 12. Qxd4 Nxd4 13. Rxd4 Bc5 {had
seemed very solid for Black in Erigaisi-Azarov, Baku (rapid) 2023, and was
eventually drawn, as were the first five games of this mini-match.}) ({There's
also} 7. Qd3 {when I also suspect that} b5 $5 {is quite critical,} ({and
perhaps even better than the} 7... Nc6 8. O-O-O b5 {of Andreikin-Martinez
Alcantara, Titled Tuesday (blitz) 2020, which can be found in the Archive.}))
7... b5 ({Consistent based on what we've just seen, although with the queen on
d2 White is fairly well placed to switch to a closed centre French structure.
That may explain why} 7... Bb4 {has also been tried and after} 8. Bd3 $6 (8. a3
$1 {feels right, and if} Bxc3 9. Qxc3 dxe4 10. Bxc7) 8... c5 {White was
already struggling in Sailer-Zakarian, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2023.}) 8. e5 $1 ({
While this may not have been deeply prepared, it does improve over} 8. exd5
exd5 ({there's also} 8... b4 $5 9. Ne4 Nxd5 {, which looks fine for Black}) 9.
Bd3 Be6 10. Nge2 Nbd7 {, which just seemed quite unclear in
Sokolin-Yermolinsky, Denver 1998.}) 8... Nfd7 9. Bg5 ({With tempo - an
important point. Instead,} 9. Be3 c5 10. f4 cxd4 11. Bxd4 Nc6 {would surely be
a pretty decent version of a Classical French for Black.}) 9... f6 $5 ({
The dynamic option. The solid one was} 9... Be7 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 {when} 11. f4 c5
12. Nf3 Nc6 {should be closely compared with a Classical French. The
dark-squared bishops are already off the board here and after} 13. dxc5 Nxc5
14. Bd3 {followed by 0-0 and Ne2 I'd slightly prefer to take White, but a
French player might well not be too unhappy on the black side.}) 10. exf6 gxf6
({Continuing dynamically. Instead,} 10... Nxf6 11. O-O-O c5 {feels rather
ambitious to me and} 12. dxc5 Nc6 13. Qe1 $1 {would leave Black beginning to
come under pressure in the centre.}) 11. Bh6 ({This feels principled to me,
although I note that the engines prefer the retreats to e3 and h4: for example,
} 11. Be3 c5 (11... Nc6 $5 12. f4 Nb6 {might also be considered}) 12. dxc5 Nc6
13. O-O-O Bb7 14. Nge2 Nxc5 15. Kb1 {when Stockfish is likely right that White
is slightly for choice, although the position is, of course, pretty complex.})
11... Be7 $6 ({A step in the wrong direction. Black would have done better with
} 11... Qe7 12. Bxf8 Rxf8 13. f4 Bb7 {when he can always go long and surely
can't be more than very slightly worse,}) ({or even} 11... c5 $5 12. Bxf8 Rxf8
13. O-O-O Nc6 {with decent counterplay, and if} 14. Re1 Kf7 {, after which the
engines even slightly prefer his chances, despite the slightly airy king
position.}) 12. O-O-O ({This can hardly be terrible, but} 12. f4 $1 {with the
idea of Be2 and mate on h5 would have been quite annoying to deal with: for
example,} c5 ({or} 12... Nb6 13. Be2 Nc4 {when the simple} 14. Bxc4 dxc4 15. a3
Bb7 16. O-O-O {is one route to a pleasant initiative and advantage for White,
who will look to press down the e-file}) 13. Be2 Qc7 14. Bh5+ Kd8 15. Nge2 {
when White's position is much the more harmonious and better developed, with
ideas of levering open lines with f4-f5 high on the agenda.}) 12... c5 ({
Going for counterplay, although} 12... Nb6 $5 {wasn't ridiculous, and if} 13.
f4 Qd6 14. Nf3 (14. Be2 Nc6 15. Bh5+ $6 Kd8 {actually only helps Black, who is
all set to attack with ...b4 and ...Nc4}) 14... Nc6 {when Black will at least
get ...Bd7 and ...0-0-0 in.}) 13. Re1 ({This dynamic and slightly unusual
structure cannot have been easy to navigate with little time, but here} 13.
Nge2 {was likely correct, since} b4 (13... Nc6 14. Nf4 $1 {works well too,
based on the point} Nxd4 $2 15. Nxe6 $1 Nxe6 16. Qxd5 Nc7 $2 17. Qh5#) 14. Na4
c4 {need not be feared on account of} 15. Qe3 {, and if} Qa5 16. b3 {when the
queenside is secure enough and e6 can quickly be targeted.}) 13... b4 14. Nb1
$2 ({A definite mistake and all of a4, e2 and even d1 would have been better
squares: for instance,} 14. Na4 Qa5 15. b3 Nb6 16. Nxb6 Qxb6 (16... Qxa2 $4 17.
Qd3 {wins}) 17. dxc5 Qxc5 18. Kb1 {when White should still be slightly for
choice as both sides impress with their lack of development at move 18.}) 14...
Nc6 ({This is good and} 14... cxd4 $5 {might have been even better, since} 15.
Qxd4 Nc5 {leaves Black beginning to dominate the board with ...Qa5 and ...e5
both high on the agenda.}) 15. Rxe6 ({There's nothing better because after} 15.
Ne2 Rb8 {Black's play with ...c4 or even ...Nb6-c4 begins to look quite potent.
}) 15... Nxd4 16. Re1 Ne5 {Plugging the e-file while seizing the initiative.
At this stage, Azarov must have been pretty happy with how things were going.}
17. Ne2 {White absolutely must challenge the strong knight on d4, even if
Black is now able to ignore any threat.} Bf5 $1 18. Nxd4 cxd4 19. Qxd4 Qc7 $2 (
19... Qd7 $1 {was somewhat stronger, with the point} 20. c3 $2 ({as such,
White would either have to grovel with} 20. Nd2 Rc8 21. Kb1 Rxc2 22. Ka1) ({
or try} 20. Rxe5 $5 fxe5 21. Qxe5 Rg8 {, but even here Black must be clearly
for choice}) 20... Qa4 {.}) 20. c3 $1 {A fighting response to the mate threat
and now Azarov was to rather collapse.} Kf7 $2 (20... Rd8 $1 {would have
shored up d5 and still been at least OK for Black: for example,} 21. g4 Bg6 22.
f4 $5 Nxg4 23. f5 $5 Bxf5 24. Bf4 Qc6 25. Bd3 {when White has fair play for
the pawn, but surely no more than that.}) 21. f4 $1 {Driving the knight away
so that White can capture on d5 without ...Be6 being possible in response.
Erigaisi has also realised that he need not fear his bishop on h6 being
trapped.} Ng4 $2 (21... Nc6 22. Qxd5+ Kg6 {was a better try, since the
sacrifice on f5 only leads to a draw, so White would have had to find} 23. g4
$1 Kxh6 24. Qxf5 Kg7 25. Bd3 {when he should be winning, although a little
care might still be required in view of the situation down the c-file.}) 22.
Qxd5+ Kg6 23. Qxf5+ $1 ({Ol�! White either picks off the knight on g4 or
mates with} 23. Qxf5+ Kxf5 24. Bd3# {.}) 1-0


