1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 d5 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 c5 5. Nbd2 Qb6 $5 {Just as in
Grieve-Eggleston, this is a rather audacious attempt to bag an early pawn.} 6.
c4 $5 ({Erigaisi meets fire with fire and this bold choice turns out to be new
for us. We've previously only focused on the sensible} 6. Rb1 {, as in
Carlsen-Ding Liren, Carlsen Invitational, Internet (rapid) 2020 - see the
Archive.}) 6... cxd4 ({The limited practice thus far with 6 c4 has also seen
Black try} 6... Nc6 {, whereupon} 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. Bd3 $5 Qxb2 9. O-O O-O 10.
cxd5 exd5 11. Nb3 {gave White decent compensation, but no more than that in A.
Moskalenko-Vidit, Internet (blitz) 2022.}) 7. exd4 dxc4 ({Ruling out any
notion of c4-c5, but allowing White to recapture with tempo. In any case,
Black should avoid} 7... Qxb2 $2 8. cxd5 Nxd5 (8... exd5 9. Rb1 Qa3 10. Bb5+
Bd7 11. O-O {is even worse}) 9. Rb1 Qxa2 10. Bxb8 $1 Rxb8 11. Bb5+ Ke7 12. Ne5
{when White's initiative far more than offsets the two gambitted pawns.}) 8.
Nxc4 ({Very natural, if also new,} 8. Bxc4 Be7 9. Bb3 O-O 10. O-O Nc6 11. Nc4
Qd8 {having previously been about equal in Woeber-Titz, Spitz in der Wachau
2020.}) ({I should also point out that rather than recapture, Stockfish quite
likes} 8. Rc1 $5 {, keeping all options open.}) 8... Bb4+ $2 ({Xiong will
quickly regret the exchange of dark-squared bishops. Indeed, Black absolutely
had to go} 8... Qd8 {when} 9. a3 Be7 10. Bd3 O-O 11. O-O Bd7 $5 {shouldn't be
too bad a version for Black of an IQP scenario.}) 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 Qd8 11.
Qb4 {The problem, and already Black is simply in serious trouble.} Qe7 12. Nd6+
$1 Kf8 13. Ne5 $1 {Erigaisi follows up ruthlessly.} Nc6 ({White had, of course,
prepared to meet} 13... Ne4 {with} 14. Nexf7 {when} Nc6 15. Qa3 Bd7 16. Bd3
Nxd6 17. Nxd6 {leaves him a clear pawn to the good.}) ({Likewise,} 13... Ne8
14. Nexf7 Nc6 15. Qc5 Bd7 16. Bd3 {simply leaves him dominating the board.})
14. Qa3 Nxd4 $2 ({Losing by force, although even after, say,} 14... Bd7 15.
Nexf7 Ne8 16. O-O-O {I somewhat doubt that Black would have survived.}) 15.
O-O-O Nc6 (15... Nf5 16. Nxf5 Qxa3 17. Rd8+ Ne8 18. bxa3 exf5 19. Bc4 Ke7 20.
Nxf7 {is also a killer.}) 16. Nexf7 Rg8 {Sadly necessary now that the knight
on d6 is so well protected.} 17. Bc4 Bd7 18. Rhe1 {The material might be level,
but just compare the difference in coordination and activity between the two
sides! One threat is now simply Ng5.} Ne8 19. Qh3 {Hitting e6 and h7. The game
is pretty much up for Xiong.} Nd8 20. Nxd8 Rxd8 21. Nxe8 (21. Nxe8 Rxe8 22.
Qf3+ Qf6 23. Rxd7 {is simply a whole piece.}) 1-0


