1. c4 e6 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 Nf6 4. Nf3 dxc4 5. Qa4+ Nbd7 6. Qxc4 c5 {Less common
these days, with the mainline instead continuing:} (6... a6 7. Qc2 c5 8. Nc3
Qc7 9. O-O b6 10. d4 {- see Ding Liren-Duda, in the Archives.}) 7. d3 {This
move enables a quick Bc1-f4 which make it harder for Black to develop the
queenside. The alternatives have proven to be less testing: now scores much
better than the old 7.0-0. punktet besser als das ältere 7.0-0.} (7. Qb3 Rb8
8. O-O b6 9. d3 Bd6 10. Na3 a6 11. Nc4 Bc7 12. d4 O-O {is analyzed in
Ganguly-Saduakassova in the Archives.}) (7. O-O b6 8. Nc3 (8. Nd4 {is
adequately met by} Ne5 $1 9. Nc6 Nxc4 10. Nxd8 Nd5 11. Nc3 Kxd8 12. Nxd5 Bb7 {
with level chances}) 8... Bb7 9. d4 Rc8 {and Black was comfortable in the 2015
game Grischuk-Eljanov, also in the Archives.}) 7... a6 {In this position:} (
7... b6 $2 {now doesn't work because of} 8. Nd4 {In contrast to the previous
note, White's queen is now defended, which makes a big difference after} Ne5 9.
Nc6 Nxc6 10. Bxc6+ Bd7 11. Bxa8 Qxa8 12. O-O {and White has extra material,
Dominguez Perez,L (2758)-Zumsande,M (2465) Chess.com INT 2020 1-0 (36)}) 8. Qb3
Bd6 {instead:} (8... b5 $2 9. Ne5 {wins material}) (8... Qc7 {may be Black's
best, for example} 9. Bf4 (9. a4 b6 10. Na3 Bb7 11. Nc4 {and now} Bd6 {it
doesn't feel natural to give up the bishop pair, but after} (11... Be7 12. Bf4
Qc6 (12... Qd8 {is less awkward}) 13. e4 b5 14. Na5 {Nemeth,Z (2246)-Haubro,M 
(2395) Dublin 2023 0-1 (68), and here} Qb6 15. Nxb7 Qxb7 16. axb5 O-O 17. b6 {
leaves White with the slightly better structure.}) 12. Nxd6+ Qxd6 13. O-O O-O
14. Bf4 Qe7 {Black has a very solid position.}) 9... Bd6 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. Nbd2
O-O 12. O-O {Fedoseev,V (2676)-So,W (2769) Chess.com INT 2023 �-� (63),
and now} b5 {is equal}) 9. a4 {An important motif, cramping Black's queenside}
O-O 10. a5 Nd5 11. Nbd2 Rb8 12. O-O b5 {Black frees his position, but is left
with split pawns on the queenside.} 13. axb6 N7xb6 14. Qd1 $146 {The first new
move, varying from:} ({Vorgänger:} 14. Ne4 Nd7 15. Qc2 Be7 16. Bd2 f5 $6 17.
Nc3 Nb4 18. Qb3 Nf6 19. Rfc1 Nc6 20. Qa2 {Sadhwani,R (2603)-Zawadzka,J (2407)
Sharjah Masters 4th 2021 (6) 1-0} Nd4 21. Nxd4 cxd4 22. Na4 Kh8 23. Nc5 {
and White has strong pressure on Black's weak pawns, Sadhwani,R (2603)
-Zawadzka,J (2407) Sharjah 2021 1-0 (64)}) (14. Nc4 Nxc4 15. Qxc4 {Gumularz,S 
(2534)-Kiolbasa,O (2388) Elblag 2022 1-0 (41), when Black can continue with,
for example} Rb5 16. b3 Bb7 17. Bb2 Be7 {followed by ...Be7-f6, with balanced
chances.}) 14... Qc7 15. Ne4 Be7 16. Bd2 Nd7 17. Qc2 Qb6 18. Bc3 Bb7 19. Ned2 {
White's better pawn structure gives him a slight edge.} Nb4 20. Qb1 (20. Qc1 {
is more flexible}) 20... Bd5 21. Rc1 Rfc8 22. Ne5 Nxe5 23. Bxe5 Bd6 24. Bc3 Qb7
{Black wants to trade the light-squared bishops on his own terms. After:} (
24... Bxg2 25. Kxg2 Qc6+ 26. Kg1 {White keeps the structural edge.}) 25. Bh3 (
25. Bxd5 exd5 {allows Black to solve his problems.}) 25... Be7 26. b3 Nc6 27.
e3 Nb4 28. Nc4 Rd8 29. Bf1 Bf8 30. Ra3 Qd7 {Black has manoeuvred well, and is
now back on terms. The text move offers a pawn in return for counterplay.} 31.
Bxb4 Rxb4 32. Rxa6 Rdb8 33. Ra3 h5 34. h4 Qb7 35. Qc2 g6 36. Rca1 {White could
have held on to the b3-pawn, but it is hard to see how to make progress.} Rxb3
37. Ra7 {Over the next few moves, White starts to risk matters by appearing to
push too hard.} (37. Rxb3 Qxb3 38. Qxb3 Rxb3 {is just equal.}) 37... Qb4 38.
Qe2 Qc3 39. Rd1 Rb1 40. Ra3 Qf6 41. Bg2 $4 {Blundering the game.} (41. Ra2 {
is level, since} Bf3 42. Rxb1 Rxb1 43. Qc2 Re1 44. Nd2 {holds for White}) 41...
Bxc4 42. dxc4 R8b2 {White loses the queen or gets checkmated.} 0-1


