1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Bg5 dxc4 6. e4 b5 7. e5 h6 8. Bh4 g5
9. Nxg5 hxg5 10. Bxg5 Nbd7 11. exf6 Bb7 12. Be2 {A rare move. Shirov is
obviously an expert in the lines he plays, but as they are so sharp, it is
easy for his opponents to target a specific line in preparation.} Nxf6 13. Bf3
Be7 14. g3 {A novelty, but it is the engine's top choice.} ({The point is that
the immediate} 14. O-O {allows} Qc7 15. g3 O-O-O $13) 14... Qb6 (14... Nd5 {
is a good alternative.} 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 {The engine top line 16.a4 leads to a
very concrete and forcing line, which usually means that Black will
successfully equalise if they know what they're doing. There are other moves
here but for now let's see the main line:} 16. a4 (16. O-O O-O-O 17. Nxd5 exd5
$13) 16... b4 17. Ne4 O-O-O 18. Qe2 c3 $1 ({The immediate} 18... e5 $6 19. Qxc4
f5 20. Nc5 {doesn't really work as after} exd4+ 21. Kf1 {There is nothing to
show for the completely broken position.}) 19. bxc3 e5 $1 20. cxb4 ({Now if} 
20. Qc4 $2 f5 $1 21. Nc5 exd4+ 22. Kf1 dxc3 $17) (20. c4 Nc7 21. O-O-O exd4 22.
h4 f5 23. Nd2 {The knight prepares to go to b3.} (23. Ng5 $6 Qd7 $15 {[%cal
Gc6c5,Gd7a4]}) 23... Qxe2 24. Bxe2 d3 25. Bf3 Ne6 26. Rhe1 (26. Nb3 Nd4 27.
Nxd4 Rxd4 $11) 26... Nd4 27. Re3 f4 28. Rxd3 c5 29. Bxb7+ Kxb7 $11) 20... Qxb4+
21. Qd2 f5 $1 {Simplest.} 22. Nc5 Nc3 23. Nxb7 Rxd4 24. Qc2 e4 25. Be2 Nxe2+
26. Kxe2 Qxb7 $13) 15. O-O O-O-O 16. Qe2 Qxd4 17. Rfd1 Qc5 18. h4 Rhg8 19.
Rxd8+ ({White could also have flicked in the moves} 19. a4 a6 20. Bxf6 (20.
Rxd8+ Bxd8 21. Bxf6 Bxf6 22. Ne4 Qe5 23. Nxf6 Qxf6 24. h5 Rd8 {would be a
transposition to the game except that White has forced the opponent into
playing ...a6 whereas Shirov took the opportunity to play 24...c3.}) 20... Bxf6
21. Ne4 Qe5 22. Nxf6 Qxf6 23. h5 Kc7 {with a mess, as always in the Botvinnik.}
) 19... Bxd8 20. Bxf6 Bxf6 21. Ne4 Qe5 22. Nxf6 Qxf6 23. h5 Rd8 24. a4 c3 $1 (
24... a6 $13) 25. axb5 cxb2 ({The clean equaliser, supposedly, was} 25... Rd2
$1 26. Qe3 cxb2 27. Rb1 Rc2 $1 28. Be4 Rc4 29. bxc6 (29. Bd3 Rc3 30. h6 c5 31.
h7 c4 32. Qc5+ Kd7 33. Bf1 Rc1 {and a draw is made, typically because both
sides have very extreme counterplay.} 34. Qxa7 Rxb1 35. Qxb7+ Kd8 36. h8=Q+
Qxh8 37. Qb8+ Ke7 38. Qc7+) 29... Bxc6 30. Bxc6 Rxc6 31. h6 Rc2 32. h7 Qg7 33.
Qxa7 Rc1+ 34. Kg2 Rxb1 35. Qa8+ Kc7 $11) 26. Rb1 c5 27. Bc6 $1 {Practically
best.} (27. Bxb7+ Kxb7 28. Rxb2 Rd5 $13) 27... a5 $4 {A losing move.} (27...
Qc3 28. Rxb2 c4 $1 {followed by ...Qd3 feels like an adequate defence.}) ({
or the immediate} 27... c4 $1) 28. Rxb2 (28. Qe4 $4 Rd5 $1 29. Bxd5 Bxd5 {
would have been a shock to the system. After} 30. Qf4 Qc3 {White actually has
to be a bit careful in order not to lose.} 31. b6 $1 e5 32. Qg4+ Kb7 33. Qd7+
Kxb6 34. Qxd5 Qc1+ 35. Rxc1 bxc1=Q+ 36. Kg2 Qh6 $11) 28... a4 29. Rd2 a3 30.
Ra2 $4 (30. Rxd8+ Qxd8 (30... Kxd8 31. Bxb7 $18) 31. h6 Qd4 32. Bxb7+ ({
or even stronger is the immediate} 32. h7) 32... Kxb7 33. Qf3+ $18 {was a win.}
) 30... Qc3 {.} 31. h6 (31. Qe4 $6 Rd5 $3 32. Bxb7+ Kxb7 33. h6 Qd3) 31... Rh8
$4 {Technically a blunder, but both the players' mistakes were excusable. I
think in general this whole variation looks practically difficult for Black if
they are caught off guard.} (31... Bxc6 32. bxc6 c4 33. Kg2 Qd3 34. Qe1 Qd5+
35. f3 c3 36. Qb1 Qxc6 37. Qb3 Qc5 38. h7 Qe5 {and Black miraculously holds on!
}) 32. Qd1 $1 {Simple and strong.} Bxc6 33. bxc6 Qd4 34. Qb3 Qb4 35. Qd3 Rd8
