1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. O-O-O d5 10. Qe1 e5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. exd5 Nxd5 13. Bc4 Be6 14. Kb1 ({
The immediate} 14. Ne4 {is still the main move here when after} f5 15. Ng5 {
rather than retreating his attacked bishop, there is the option for} Qf6 16.
Nxe6 Qxe6 {Probably White's bishop pair is for preference but in the 3
practical outings to date, Black has scored a draw and 2 wins including} 17.
Bc5 Rfd8 18. Qa5 Rd7 19. Kb1 Rad8 20. Ka1 e4 {as seen in the site annotated
Djokic,M (2227)-Corrales Jimenez,F (2532) chess.com INT 2020.}) 14... Re8 ({
Seeking immediate action along the half-open b-file with} 14... Rb8 {is the
direct approach when} 15. Ne4 (15. Bb3 Qc7 16. Ne4 Nxe3 17. Qxe3 Bxb3 18. axb3
Rfd8 19. g4 Rd4 20. g5 a5 21. Rhe1 a4 {had seen Black go from slightly worse
to a bit better in Walter,S (2220)-Winiarski,M (2295) Warsaw POL 2017.}) 15...
f5 (15... Qc7 16. Bc5 {is then the standard white piece configuration that has
long been associated with even the main lines of 9 0-0-0 d5.}) 16. Bxa7 $5 {
was originally brought to our attention on the forum whilst more recently of
course though we've seen 14...a5 which at least ensures that pawn will remain
for now at least.}) 15. Ne4 ({Overwhelmingly the most popular move and
certainly best. Subscribers may recall my surprise at} 15. h4 Qc7 {when
suddenly the black knight was unpinned and there was a direct threat to
White's dark-squared bishop as well as tactical possibilities involving ... e4
in Navara,D (2735)-Edouard,R (2641) Drancy FRA 2016.}) ({Elsewhere rather
impressive (from a Black perspective!) is} 15. g4 $6 Qc7 16. Nxd5 cxd5 17. Bxd5
Bxd5 18. Rxd5 e4 $1 19. Qd1 Rab8 20. Bc1 $2 Qc3 $1 {0-1 as seen in Ziegler,A 
(2294)-Cacciola,A (2098) Split 2015.}) 15... f5 ({Instead} 15... Qc7 16. Bc5 {
is the site annotated Leko,P (2709)-Trent,L (2463) Douglas ENG 2016 game worth
checking out even if White has scored very well in practice there.}) (15... Qb8
$5 16. Bc5 f5 17. Ng5 e4 {(the mate threat on b2 highlighting the reason
behind ...Qb8 plus of course aside from being on the b-file, her majesty can
also travel to e5.)} 18. Bd4 Bxd4 19. Rxd4 Qe5 20. c3 e3 21. f4 Qf6 22. h4 h6
23. Nxe6 Qxe6 {was quite accurate chess. It may now be objectively better for
White but Black wasn't without chances in Pauwels,C (2551)-Haugen,A (2526)
ICCF email 2010.}) ({Another idea for Black is to look to park a pawn on a4 
(making the b-file blocking retreat Bb3 impossible. Hence} 15... a5 {with:} 16.
g4 ({Alternatively} 16. h4 h6 {(the standard approach in such systems is for
Black to prepare to meet g4-g5 with ...h6-h5 and h4-h5 with ...g6-g5 and it's
generally up to White to decide which of and when those moves should occur.)}
17. Qd2 f5 (17... Kh7 18. h5 {and as discussed in the past, Black has to
choose between advancing his g-pawn or taking on h5.}) 18. Nc5 f4 19. Bf2 Bf7
20. Ka1 Qc7 21. Rhe1 Rad8 22. Qe2 Nf6 23. Rxd8 Rxd8 24. Bxf7+ Qxf7 {and with
that block on e4, White held a positional advantage in Kolesar, M (2512)
-Westera,B (2446) ICCF email 2011.}) 16... a4 17. h4 {and an intriguing game
was} h6 18. Bc5 Qc7 19. h5 g5 20. Rh2 Red8 21. Rhd2 Nc3+ 22. Nxc3 Rxd2 23. Rxd2
Bxc4 24. Qe4 Be6 25. Rd6 Rd8 26. Rxd8+ Qxd8 27. Kc1 Qa5 28. Qxc6 {�-�
Siigur, J (2425)-Windhausen,G (2486) ICCF email 2010. Although White was
generally for preference throughout, at the end Black was better!}) 16. Ng5 Bc8
({Enthusiastic followers of this variation will know that I had wondered about
} 16... a5 {(also useful for stopping the white queen from parking itself on
that square should the black queen move away.)} 17. Nxe6 {(of course certainly
not forced just yet.)} Rxe6 {previously remarking 'A slightly tricky c4-g8
diagonal but there will always be play against b2 and whereas White may look
to g2-g4 at some point, equally the black a-pawn has ambitions!'. However
whereas I also added 'Alas to date there have been no takers for that idea
with the logical preservation of the bishop instead being the predominant
preference.' in fact I can update that with} 18. g4 Rb8 (18... fxg4 19. fxg4 e4
$5 {is more what I had in mind. Three isolanis but clear possible action for
the pieces.}) 19. gxf5 gxf5 20. Bb3 Qe7 21. Rg1 Kh8 {with White for preference
