{[%evp 0,98,25,20,9,9,23,23,22,10,9,0,17,-3,-3,-3,-10,-31,27,27,24,24,42,12,19,
-4,-1,-25,6,2,2,4,-1,-26,-26,-21,-10,-13,-20,-31,-28,-21,-21,-28,15,10,18,-9,
-13,-3,-3,-2,-2,-4,0,-13,13,0,0,-35,-36,-50,-27,-60,-60,-63,-59,-54,0,-25,0,0,
0,0,0,0,0,0,0,-175,-135,-135,-18,-50,0,0,0,0,114,115,110,226,224,0,0,0,0,12,45,
0,327]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 {In a must-draw, Erigaisi plays the
most solid opening that exists, the Berlin defense.} 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1 Nd6 6.
a4 {A little sideline, a clever approach, when in a must-win situation.} Be7 7.
Nc3 O-O 8. d4 e4 {Returning the pawn one way or the other is a common way of
trying to deal with White's gambit approach. Black could have also included a6
at some point.} 9. Nxe4 Nxe4 10. Rxe4 d5 11. Re3 {Interesting, intending to
swing the rook accross, along the third rank, potentially.} Bd6 12. Bxc6 {
White creates some imbalance, as Black was ready to transfer the knight with
Ne7, keeping the symmetry. Now White gets a better pawn structure, in return
for the bishop pair.} bxc6 13. h3 {Modest, but the tempting 13.Ne5 also
doesn't exactly kill, after 13...c5.} c5 {Logical, trying to undouble the
pawns, but it wasn't neccessary. Now White gets to eventually control the
important dark squares d4-c5.} 14. dxc5 Bxc5 15. Rc3 {The rook proves useful
on the third rank.} Bb4 16. Rd3 c6 17. Bf4 {Finishing the development. White
really doesn't have much, but there is quite some play left here.} Re8 {
Black plays very natural moves- rooks belong on open files.} 18. c3 Bf8 19. b4
{White highlights the ambition of controlling the dark squares. Black though
has a strong light squared bishop and shouldn't be doing badly just yet.} Bf5
20. Re3 Rxe3 $6 {Stronger was 20...Be4!, when the bishop on f4 is also
potentially vulnerable to Qf6 at some point. Now Black forces White to
reposition the dark squared bishop to a better square, a protected one, from
which it also controls the c5 square.} 21. Bxe3 Bd6 22. Nd4 Bd7 {Black has to
go passive here, having very slightly misplayed it.} 23. Qf3 {White gets to
activate the pieces now and slowly start bullying Black on the dark squares.}
Qc7 24. Nb3 {A beautiful regroup. Black is still solid, but the dark squares
are fully under White's control.} Re8 25. Bc5 Be5 26. a5 Bc8 {It is still hard
for White to do much, as Arjun remains patient and there isn't anything
obvious White can try here.} 27. Qd3 h6 28. Bd4 Bd6 29. Qd2 {White hints at a
trade of rooks... or a potential queen sacrifice!?} Bh2+ 30. Kh1 Bf4 31. Re1 $1
{An incredible idea frankly. It takes deep understanding to realize when the
rook and a bishop can match a queen, since the childhood math they teach us,
claims that queen is worth a couple of points more.} Bxd2 {Arjun grabs the
queen and indeed, there is no need to panic, as even though White has enough
compensation, Black's position is full of resources as well.} 32. Rxe8+ Kh7 33.
Nxd2 Be6 {Hinting at some Qd7 Bxh3 ideas.} 34. Nb3 {It was also possible to
play it more slowly with 34.Kg1!? anticipating the Qd7 Bxh3 idea.} Qd7 35. Ra8
Bxh3 {Now Black is threatening the perpetual with Bxg2 and Qg4-d1, which White
must have missed when allowing 34...Qd7! (in fact I suspect he missed Qd7
itself). Being in a must win, though, Christopher shrugs it off and keeps on
fighting.} 36. f3 $5 {White has to try, but of course now it is clear that
Black has to be in a great shape.} Bf5 {A more brutal solution was also
possible. 36...Qf5!? hinting at Qb1+, and followed by h5-h4, ready to
sacrifice the h3 bishop with strong attack against the naked white king.} 37.
Rxa7 Qe6 38. Kh2 Qe1 {Black is chasing a perpetual. White is desperate.} 39. g4
$6 {Draw was not an option...} Qe2+ {A slow 39...Bg6! followed by h5 would
lead to mating attack, but I can imagine Arjun relaxed somewhat here.} 40. Kg3
Qe1+ {Surprisingly, simplifying makes Black's life only harder. Stronger was
still Bg6! intending h5 and a slow, yet quick attack.} 41. Bf2 Qxc3 42. gxf5
Qxb3 43. Rxf7 {Suddenly there are threats of a6, but also Bd4! and Arjun
panics.} Qxb4 $2 {This lands Black in trouble, as the a-pawn keeps on walking.
From the possible defense I like 43...h5!?, intending h4+, but also giving h6
square for the king, which can be relevant after an eventualy Bd4 Rxg7.} 44. a6
{Black has suddenly found himself at the edge of a cliff and now stumbles
again.} Qa4 $2 {It was neccessary to find a strong idea here- 44....Qd2!
intending to grab the f7 rook with Qg5-Qh5-Qxf7 was still holding.} 45. a7 {
Now Black is actually lost.} d4 46. f6 {This gives Black some chances, but the
win with 46.Re7!! was not findable with the time White had. The natural 46.Rd7
wasn't good enough because of c5!.} Kg6 {Black keeps on fighting, but White
still has the a7 pawn and it remains a near hopeless mission to stop that pawn.
} 47. Rd7 gxf6 48. Rxd4 {Using the fact that Qxa7 loses to Rg4+ discovery.} Qa5
49. Rc4 {Black has to be super accurate here to not lose immediately.} Qa6 $2 {
A final mistake, now White gets access to the 8th rank and there turns out to
be no perpetual anywhere.} 50. Rb4 $1 Qa5 51. Rb8 $1 {The bishop on f2 does
the job of stopping the perpetual on its own.} Qg5+ 52. Kh3 Qh5+ 53. Kg2 Qg5+
54. Kh1 Qh5+ 55. Kg1 Qg5+ 56. Kf1 Qc1+ 57. Be1 {Very accurate play by White,
now Qc4+ is met with Kg2! and the final check along the 2nd rank will be
dodged with Bf2!. Accurately done.} Qe3 (57... Qc4+ 58. Kg2 Qe2+ 59. Bf2 $1)
58. Rg8+ Kf7 59. a8=Q Qxf3+ 60. Kg1 {Black can give two more checks but after
Qe3+ Bf2 Qc1+ Kg2 it is all over. What a fight!} 1-0


