1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 Na5 (5... b5 6. Bf1 $1 Nxd5 (
6... Qxd5 $6 7. Nc3 Qc5 8. Bxb5 Be7 9. d3 $16) (6... h6 $5 7. Nxf7 $1 {see
Vallejo Pons,F-Naiditsch,A in the PGN Archive.}) 7. Bxb5 Bb7 8. Qh5 Qd7 9. d4
g6 (9... exd4 $2 10. O-O $16 {is far too dangerous for the black king.}) 10.
Qe2 O-O-O 11. dxe5 Qf5 12. Bd3 ({According to the engine, it is possibly
stronger to play} 12. Nf3 Ndb4 13. Na3 Bg7 14. O-O $14 {but personally, I
would exchange queens into a slightly better endgame if I have the chance.})
12... Qxe5 13. Nxf7 Qxe2+ 14. Bxe2 Re8 15. Nxh8 Nd4 16. Be3 Nxc2+ ({Or} 16...
Nxe3 17. fxe3 Nxc2+ 18. Kd2 {which transposes.}) 17. Kd2 Nxa1 18. Nf7 Nxe3 $8 {
(square symbol means "only move")} 19. fxe3 Bd5 (19... Bc5 $6 20. Na3 Bxe3+ 21.
Kc3 {and the knight on a3 struggles to survive. Black has some superficial way
to keep it alive with:} Bf4 22. Bc4 (22. Rd1 $1 $16) 22... Re3+ 23. Kb4 Re1 $1
24. Rxe1 Bd2+ 25. Kc5 Bxe1 26. Be6+ Kb8 27. g4 $16) 20. Ba6+ Kb8 21. Nc3 $1
Bxf7 22. Rxa1 Bh6 23. Re1 $14) (5... Nxd5 $6 6. Nxf7 Kxf7 7. Qf3+ Ke6 8. Nc3
Ncb4 9. O-O $1 c6 10. d4 $1 Qf6 11. Qe2 Ke7 12. dxe5 Qg6 13. Ne4 Bf5 14. f3 $16
{This is an awful position for the black king which is in a permanent state of
danger.}) 6. Bb5+ c6 (6... Bd7 7. Qe2 Bd6 (7... Be7 8. Nf3 $1 {Immediately
targeting the weak e5-pawn.} (8. Nc3 {has been covered many times in the
Archives.}) 8... O-O (8... Nxd5 9. Nxe5 c6 10. Bd3 Be6 11. O-O Nf4 12. Qe4 Nxd3
13. Nxd3 $14) 9. Bxd7 Qxd7 10. Nxe5 Qxd5 (10... Qf5 11. d4 Nxd5 12. Qd3 $1 Qh5
13. Qf3 Qxf3 14. Nxf3 $16) 11. Nf3 Rae8 12. O-O Bd6 13. Qd1 $16) 8. Bxd7+ Qxd7
(8... Nxd7 $4 9. Ne4 $18) 9. Nc3 c6 (9... O-O $6 10. a3 $1 {The knight on a5
is a problem piece.} b6 11. O-O $14) 10. dxc6 Nxc6 11. d3 Nd4 12. Qd1 O-O 13.
O-O Rac8 14. Nge4 Nxe4 15. dxe4 f5 16. Be3 (16. Bd2 h6 17. a3) 16... Ba3 $5 (
16... Bc5 $2 17. Ne2 $1 {Threatening to win with c3.} Qb5 18. Bxd4 exd4 19.
exf5 Qxb2 20. Qd3 $16 {Somehow White manages to keep the extra pawn and
maintain play, for instance on the b-file.}) 17. Rb1 Bxb2 18. Rxb2 Rxc3 19.
exf5 Rf7 20. Bxd4 exd4 21. Re1 Rxf5 22. Rb3 Rfc5 23. Rxc3 Rxc3 24. Qd2 $14) 7.
dxc6 bxc6 8. Bd3 Nd5 $1 {The only move that equalises according to modern
chess theory.} (8... h6 $6 9. Ne4 {is White's point. Black doesn't have enough
compensation after} Nxe4 ({A natural continuation is} 9... Nd5 10. O-O Nf4 11.
Be2 {Notice that ...f5 is always too weakening for the black king now as ...h6
weakened too much already.} Be7 (11... f5 $6 12. Ng3 Bd6 13. d4 $1 O-O 14. dxe5
Bxe5 15. Bxf4 Bxf4 16. Qxd8 Rxd8 17. Nc3 $16) 12. d3 O-O 13. Bxf4 exf4 14. Nbd2
$16 {White is a healthy pawn up. The problem for Black in this line is that
not only are they a pawn down but their pawn structure is fractured.}) 10. Bxe4
Bd6 (10... f5 $4 11. Qh5+ $18 {is clearly impossible for Black.}) 11. d3 O-O
12. g4 $1 {Anticipating ...f5.} Rb8 (12... f5 $2 13. gxf5 Bxf5 14. Bxf5 Rxf5
15. Qg4 Qf6 16. Nd2 $1 {Black cannot take on f2 due to Ne4. Whatever the case,
the knight is about to go there anyway with a winning position.}) 13. Nc3 Nb7
14. h4 $5 {Going on the attack. Black is probably just in big danger now.
White's king is actually safe in the centre.}) (8... Bd6 9. Nc3 O-O $6 10. b3
h6 11. Nge4 Nxe4 12. Nxe4 Bc7 (12... f5 $2 13. Nxd6 Qxd6 14. Bb2 $18 {Although
Black has a slightly imposing pawn centre, they are losing: White is a pawn up,
with the two bishops in quite an open position. Black cannot really make use
of the e- and f-pawns without weakening their own position.} e4 $6 15. Be2 f4
16. f3 $1 exf3 17. Bxf3 Re8+ 18. Kf2 $18 {The king is surprisingly very safe
as ...Qc5+ can always be answered by d4.}) 13. g4 $5 {Again this move to
secure the knight on e4 against ...f5 threats.} Qd4 (13... f5 14. gxf5 Bxf5 15.
Qe2 Qh4 16. Qf3 $1 {The idea is to swap queens with Qg3. Note that} Bxe4 $2 17.
Qxe4 Qxf2+ 18. Kd1 {is actually completely losing for Black as their king is
the one which is trouble now. Again the white king is very safe.}) 14. Rb1 f5
15. gxf5 Bxf5 16. Qe2 Nb7 17. Ba3 Rf7 18. Rg1 $16 {Apparently White must stay
calm with the king going to d1 in most lines. If given the chance, you will
probably stabilise his position, but he is also not in any particular danger.
The black king is in more trouble!}) (8... Be7 9. Nc3 O-O (9... h6 10. Nf3 Bd6
11. O-O O-O {transposes.}) 10. O-O h6 11. Nf3 Bd6 12. Re1 Re8 13. b3 {This is
the usual setup White is aiming for.} c5 14. Ne4 Bb7 15. Qe2 Nd5 16. Bb2 Nf4 (
16... Bf8 $4 17. Nxe5 $18) 17. Qe3 Nd5 18. Qe2 Nf4 19. Qf1 Bc7 20. Ba6 $5 (20.
Bb5 $1 Re7 21. Re3 (21. Nxc5 $5 Bxf3 22. gxf3 {Black has compensation but even
this is not out of the question. Nd3 next, eliminating the strong knight on f4.
}) 21... Nd5 22. Rd3 $16) 20... Bxa6 21. Qxa6 f5 22. Nxc5 e4 23. Nd4 $14 {
Quite a strange position where Black is arguably more lose than White but you
need to play well with your pieces. There will always be a question whether
you'll need to play the weakening move g2-g3 in order to prevent attacks
against your king.}) 9. Nf3 Bd6 10. O-O {There are now two main lines.} O-O ({
The other very big and also tempting line for Black is} 10... Nf4 11. Nc3 {
A lesser known line but one which I believe forces Black to be more precise.} (
11. Re1 Nxd3 12. cxd3 O-O 13. b3 $5 $13 (13. Nc3)) 11... Nxd3 (11... O-O $6 12.
Be2 {Notice that the knight on c3 prevents ...e5-e4.} c5 13. d3 $14 {White
keeps the extra pawn without having to fracture the structure.}) 12. cxd3 O-O
13. Ne4 Bc7 {Sidestepping Nxd6 so they can consider playing for f5.} (13... c5
14. b3 {A typical reaction. White will put the bishop on a3 in most cases.} Ba6
15. Re1 {Threatening the e5-pawn after 16.Nxd6 Qxd6 17.Nxe5.} f6 16. Ba3 $1 Nb7
$2 17. Nxd6 Qxd6 18. d4 $1 exd4 19. b4 $1 c4 (19... cxb4 20. Qb3+ $18) 20. Qa4
Qb6 21. Nxd4 $1 Qxd4 22. Qxa6 $16) 14. Qc2 {Protecting the d3-pawn and
threatening 15.b4 Nb7 16.Qxc6.} c5 $1 {It seems that only 2600s and
correspondence players are finding this move so I wouldn't be worried at all.
More likely that the opponent makes a mistake with one of the other moves I
provided.} (14... Qd5 15. b4 Nb7 16. Bb2 Bg4 17. Qc4 Bxf3 18. gxf3 $14 {
White has lots of doubled pawns now... but there's also pressure along the
c-file and in the endgame White can think about taking advantage of that.}) (
14... f5 $6 15. Nc5 Nb7 16. b3 e4 17. Nxb7 Bxb7 18. dxe4 c5 $1 19. Bb2 fxe4 20.
Ne5 $14 Qd6 21. Rac1 Rfe8 22. Ng4 $1 (22. Qxc5 Qxc5 23. Rxc5 Bd6 $1 24. Ra5 Bc7
25. Rc5 Bd6 $11) 22... h5 $4 23. Qxc5 $18) (14... Bg4 $6 15. b4 $1 {White just
grabs the pawn on c6 and this is more serious for Black than the doubled
f-pawns are for White!} f5 $2 16. Ng3 Nb7 (16... Bxf3 17. gxf3 $16) 17. Qxc6
Rf6 18. Qc4+ Kh8 19. Bb2 Rc8 20. Rfc1 f4 21. Ne4 Rg6 22. Kh1 Bb6 23. Qf7 Rxc1+
24. Rxc1 Bxf3 25. gxf3 {1-0 (25) Kovalev,V (2596)-Sanikidze,T (2533) Konya 2016
}) 15. Qxc5 Ba6 (15... Bg4 16. b4 Bxf3 17. bxa5 Be2 18. Re1 Bxd3 19. Ba3 Re8
20. Bb4 $14) 16. Re1 Bxd3 17. b3 Re8 18. Ba3 Bb6 (18... Rc8 $4 19. Rac1 $18)
19. Qd6 Nb7 20. Qxd8 Raxd8 21. Rac1 f5 22. Nc5 Nxc5 23. Bxc5 e4 24. Bxb6 axb6
25. Ng5 h6 26. Nh3 {White will neutralise the pressure with f3 or f4 soon. It
doesn't look so pleasant but apparently it's a draw.} g5 27. f3 exf3 28. Rxe8+
Rxe8 29. gxf3 Re2 30. Rc6 $11) 11. Re1 f5 $1 {Not the most common move, but
the only one that equalises. Like in the ...Nf4 line, I believe you will only
face this if you are playing a 2600 or a correspondence player! They really
need to be professional players to know this...} (11... Nf4 $2 12. Bf1 $16) (
11... Re8 $6 {is the main line but it is actually not equalising.} 12. Nc3 f5 (
12... h6 13. Ne4 Bc7 14. Ng3 {Prevents ...f5.} c5 15. b3 Nc6 16. Ba3 $1 $16)
13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. Bf1 {If Black does nothing, White can go d3, and press on
the queenside. It turns out that Black's attacking chances are not better than
White's queenside play.} e4 (14... Nc6 15. Bb5 $1 Bd7 (15... Qc7 16. c4 Bd7 (
16... e4 $4 17. cxd5 {The e-pawn is pinned.}) 17. d3 $14 {A strange position.
Somehow Black cannot make use of their pawn centre.} Rab8 (17... e4 $4 18. dxe4
dxe4 19. c5 $1 exf3 20. Rxe8+ Rxe8 21. cxd6 $18) 18. Bd2 h6 (18... e4 19. Bxc6
$1 Bxc6 20. cxd5 Bxd5 (20... exf3 $2 21. dxc6 Bxh2+ 22. Kh1 fxg2+ 23. Kxg2 $18)
21. dxe4 Bxe4 22. Rc1 Qb7 23. Bc3 $16)) 16. d4 e4 17. Ne5 Nxe5 18. dxe5 Rxe5
19. Bxd7 Qxd7 20. Bf4 $16) 15. Nd4 Qf6 16. c3 {White follows up with d3xe4
next. But just as importantly, White threatens a devious trick 17.Qa4 with a
double attack on the rook and knight (Black can defend by pulling their queen
back to d8 but then they have lost any hopes of an initiative).} Bd7 ({
Illustration if Black does nothing:} 16... h6 17. Qa4 (17. d3 $18 f4 18. dxe4
dxe4 19. b4 Nb7 20. Bc4+ Kh8 21. Bd5 $18) 17... Qd8 18. d3 Bd7 19. Qd1 f4 $2
20. dxe4 dxe4 21. b4 Nb7 22. Bc4+ Kh8 23. Bd5 $18) (16... f4 $2 17. Qa4 $1 {
is a nasty trick.} Qd8 (17... Re5 $5 {Black hopes to gain play for the piece
after ...Rh5. In fact, it is more important for White now to reduce the
pressure in the centre with} 18. d3 $1 (18. Qxa5 Rh5) 18... Nb7 (18... e3 19.
fxe3 fxe3 20. Bxe3 $18) (18... Rh5 $4 19. Qe8+ $18) 19. dxe4 dxe4 (19... Nc5
20. Qd1 dxe4 21. b4 $1 Nb7 22. Qc2 {Again Black's e4-pawn falls.}) 20. Qc6 $18)
18. b4 Nb7 19. d3 Bg4 {1-0 (34) Espinosa Veloz,E (2485) -Terletsky,O (2203)
Chess.com INT 2021} 20. dxe4 dxe4 21. Qc2 {Black cannot hold onto the pawn
centre.} e3 (21... Qe7 22. f3 $18) 22. fxe3 fxe3 23. Rxe3 $18) (16... Nc4 17.
d3 Ne5 18. dxe4 fxe4 19. Be2 $14 {Finally White stabilises the position!} Rf8
20. Be3 Qh4 21. g3 Qh3 22. f4 $1 {Neutralising any threatening play from Black:
} Ng4 23. Bxg4 Bxg4 24. Qb3 Qh5 25. f5 Qf7 26. Rf1 $14) (16... Bb7 {is an
interesting idea to prepare ... f4 in the event of 17.d3.} 17. d3 f4 18. b4 Nc6
{This is the point of Bb7.} 19. Nb5 Rad8 20. dxe4 dxe4 21. Qd5+ Kf8 (21... Kh8
$4 22. Nxd6 Rxd6 23. Rxe4 $1 $18) 22. Rxe4 Be5 23. Qc5+ Re7 24. Ba3 a6 25. Nd4
Nxd4 26. Rxe5 Qxe5 27. cxd4 Qxc5 28. bxc5 Bc6 29. Bb2 $14) 17. d3 Nc6 (17... f4
$4 18. dxe4 dxe4 19. Nb5 $18) 18. dxe4 Nxd4 (18... dxe4 $4 19. Nb5) 19. Qxd4
Qxd4 20. cxd4 fxe4 21. Be3 $14 a5 22. Rec1 a4 23. Rc2 Reb8 24. Be2 Rb6 25. Rd1
Rab8 26. Bc1 Kf7 27. f3 Bf5 28. fxe4 Bxe4 29. Bd3 Bxd3 30. Rxd3 Rb4 31. h3 Be7
32. Rc7 R4b7 33. Rf3+ Kg8 34. Rc2 Bf6 35. Rd3 Rb4 36. Rcd2 Bg5 37. Rd1 Bxc1 38.
Rxc1 Rxb2 39. Rc7 Rxa2 40. Re3 a3 41. Ree7 Ra1+ 42. Kh2 a2 43. Rxg7+ Kf8 44.
Rcf7+ Ke8 45. Ra7 Kf8 46. Rxh7 Kg8 47. Rh5 Rb2 48. Rxd5 Rf1 49. Rd8+ Rf8 50.
Rxf8+ Kxf8 51. h4 {1-0 (51) Melkumyan,H (2663)-Salimova,N (2372) Chess.com INT
2020}) 12. Nxe5 Qf6 13. Nf3 g5 14. c4 Nf4 15. Bf1 g4 $8 16. d4 $1 {White will
have such a strong initiative on the queenside that he was prepared to
sacrifice a piece. After all, he is already two pawns up!} gxf3 17. Qxf3 Ne6 $8
(17... Ng6 $4 18. c5 Bc7 19. b4 Nb7 20. Qb3+ Kg7 (20... Rf7 21. Bc4 $18) 21.
Bb2 $18) 18. Qc3 Nxd4 {Sacrificing the piece back.} (18... Nb7 19. c5 Bc7 20.
b4 a5 (20... Bd7 $2 {1-0 (64) Pichot,A (2630)-Yilmaz,M (2630) Chess.com INT
2021} 21. d5 $1 cxd5 22. Qxf6 Rxf6 23. Nc3 d4 24. Nd5 Rf7 25. Bc4 $18) (20...
Qxd4 $2 21. Qxd4 Nxd4 22. Bc4+ {Black has to return material as} Kh8 23. Bb2 {
wins immediately.} Rd8 24. Nd2 $18) 21. b5 Qxd4 $2 {So,W (2770) -Carlsen,M 
(2862) chess24.com INT 2021} ({There is some deep theory after} 21... cxb5 22.
Bxb5 a4 23. Bc4 Na5 (23... Ba5 24. Qg3+ Kh8 25. Rxe6 $1 Bxe6 26. Bf4 Bxc4 27.
Be5 Rae8 28. Bxf6+ Rxf6 29. Na3 $14) 24. Bd5 {but White just has good
compensation as the black king is vulnerable, see Janik,I-Nasuta,G in the PGN
Archive.}) 22. Bc4 $1 (22. Qxd4 $6 Nxd4 23. Bc4+ Be6 {is now good for Black as
the c5-pawn has been weakened:} 24. Bxe6+ Nxe6 25. Rxe6 Nxc5 $17 {0-1 (55) So,
W (2770)-Carlsen,M (2862) chess24. com INT 2021 Extra [Stohl,I]}) 22... Qxc3
23. Nxc3 Nbxc5 24. Ba3 cxb5 25. Nxb5 Bb6 26. Bxc5 Bxc5 27. Nc7 $16) 19. c5 Bc7
20. b4 Rb8 21. bxa5 Be6 22. Bc4 ({Now the engines give an unclear evaluation
after} 22. f4 $13 {which is meant to be White's best move. Anyway, he played
something else and went on to win a complicated game.}) 22... Bxc4 23. Qxc4+
Rf7 24. Nd2 Rd8 $4 25. Bb2 $18 Qh4 (25... Ne2+ 26. Qxe2 Qxb2 27. Nb3 Qxe2 28.
Rxe2 $18) 26. Bxd4 $4 (26. Kf1 {Maintains the pin.}) 26... Rxd4 27. g3 Rxc4 28.
gxh4 Rxc5 29. Nb3 Rc4 30. Rac1 Rg4+ 31. Kf1 Bxh2 32. Re8+ Kg7 33. Rxc6 $14 f4
34. f3 Rg1+ 35. Kf2 Rb1 36. Re2 Bg1+ 37. Kg2 Be3 38. Nc5 Rf6 39. Rc7+ Kg8 40.
Ne4 Rg6+ 41. Kh2 Kf8 42. Rxh7 Rgg1 43. Kh3 Rbf1 44. Rc2 Rxf3+ 45. Kh2 Rc1 46.
Rb2 1-0


