1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 Nc6 5. Qd2 g6 6. b3 Bh6 7. f4 f5 $5 {
This is the second most popular move here.} ({The natural} 7... Nf6 {is more
than twice as common,1-0 (51) Womacka,M (2436)-Shevchenko,K (2542) Tegernsee
2019 [Collins,Sam]: 1-0 (48) Grischuk,A (2777)-Vachier-Lagrave,M (2767)
Yekaterinburg RUS 2021 [Collins,Sam]: 0-1 (38) Shirov,A (2704) -Dominguez
Perez,L (2752) Berlin 2022 [Collins,Sam]}) 8. Bb2 Nf6 9. O-O-O {This is the
critical try for White.} (9. Bd3 Qa5 (9... e5 $6 10. Nge2 $14 {Jones}) 10. exf5
$1 {The most challenging move.} (10. Nge2 $5 fxe4 $1 11. Nxe4 Qxd2+ 12. Kxd2 (
12. Nxd2 $6 {1/2 (31)-1/2 (31) Thrish,K (2095)-Doraszelski,A (1898) Veliko
Gradiste SRB 2022} Rf8 $1 $15 {[%cal Gf6d5] already looks favourable for Black.
}) 12... Nxe4+ 13. Bxe4 Rf8 $11 {is fine for Black, as noted by Sam in the
archives (and Gawain and Carsten Hansen in their books!)}) 10... Bxf5 11. Nge2
O-O-O $1 (11... Bxd3 $6 12. Qxd3 $14 {White is very comfortable here.} Nb4 $6
13. Qd2 Rc8 $6 (13... g5 {is Gawain's attempt to improve Black's play, but he
still claims an edge for White after} 14. O-O-O $1 gxf4 15. Kb1 Rg8 16. g3 $14
{Black's exposed King and ragged structure certainly do seem to give White
good chances here.}) 14. a3 $1 Nc6 15. O-O-O $16 {was quoted by Sam in the
archives, H. Nakamura - A. Grischuk, Leuven 2018 (1-0 in 42).}) (11... Rf8 $5 {
Gawain considers this to be dubious, but it actually looks OK for Black.} 12.
Bxf5 (12. O-O-O $5 {is worth exploring, but Black should be OK after} Bg4 $5
$132) 12... Qxf5 $1 {is a good try for Black.} (12... gxf5 $2 {This is the
real mistake.} 13. O-O-O Rc8 $2 (13... O-O-O $5 14. Kb1 Rg8 15. g3 $14 {
