regains material with a winning advantage.}) 15. Qxd5 (15. g3 $5 a6 $11 {
is OK for Black.}) 15... Bxf4 16. Qxe4+ Qe7 17. Qa4 $44 {Gawain gives this as
compensation for White, but Black is OK after the precise} Qb4 $1 18. Qxb4 (18.
Bc4 $5 Qxa4 19. Rhe1+ Nge7 20. bxa4 a6 $1 $11 {is fine for Black as the Knight
on e7 is protected!}) 18... Nxb4 19. Rd4 Nc6 20. Rxf4 Rxf4 21. Nc7+ Kd8 22.
Nxa8 Be6 $11 {with White's Knight on a8 out of play compensating for the lost
pawn.}) 13. Qe1 $1 exf4 14. Nxe4 $5 (14. Qh4 $5 $14 {also looks promising.})
14... Nxe4 15. Nc3 Bf5 16. Bc4 $14) (10... Nxe4 11. Qe1 $1 {is the most
accurate response. Black will most likely play} Qa5 {which could transpose to
the game after} 12. a3 ({but} 12. Kb1 $1 {[%cal Ge1h4] is even stronger.} Nf6
13. h3 $14)) 11. a3 (11. h3 $5 Nxe4 12. Qe1 $5 Be6 13. g4 $1 $44 {This is
worth a try. White has sufficient compensation and Black has several
reasonable ways to continue e.g.,} (13. Kb1 $6 {is too slow:} O-O-O $15 {
0-1 (34) Swinkels,R (2523) -Warmerdam,M (2608) Rotterdam NED 2021}) 13... Rf7
$5) 11... Nxe4 12. Qe1 Be6 13. Kb1 {White's set-up is surprisingly poisonous.
Black's Bishops are both loose and his King will be permanently draughty no
matter where it decides to take up residence.} Rf7 14. g4 O-O-O $4 {This loses
tactically.} (14... Bg7 $1 {is playable for Black, although White retains some
pressure following} 15. b4 Qb6 16. gxf5 Nxc3+ 17. Nxc3 Bxc3 18. Bxc3 Bxf5 19.
