1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 6. g3 Qb6 7. Ndb5 Ne5 8.
Bf4 {One of the sharp mainlines of the Symmetrical English with 6 g3 Qb6.} Nfg4
9. e3 a6 {The players have reached a tabiya which has been frequently debated
in high-level games over the last few years.} 10. Qa4 {Exploiting the pin
along the a-file in order to prepare long castling. A key alternative is:} (10.
h3 axb5 11. hxg4 Nxc4 {with another important choice for White:} 12. Rc1 (12.
g5 d5 13. a4 bxa4 14. Bxc4 dxc4 15. Rxa4 Rxa4 (15... Qc6 {is sharper but
objectively fine for Black}) 16. Qxa4+ Qc6 17. Qxc6+ bxc6 18. Be5 {with a
two-results endgame for White in Caruana-Dominguez Perez, which is included in
the Archives.}) (12. Qb3 d5 13. Bxc4 dxc4 14. Qxb5+ Qxb5 15. Nxb5 {is a
quieter alternative reviewed in Fridman-Steingrimsson}) 12... d5 13. b3 {
was featured in Giri-Nepomniachtchi, which is covered in the Archives.}) 10...
g5 {Black has also played:} (10... Ra7 {is fine for Black if followed up
accurately, for example} 11. h3 axb5 12. Qxb5 Qc6 13. hxg4 Nd3+ $1 (13... Qxh1
{is not as accurate, see Topalov-Caruana in the Archives}) 14. Bxd3 Qxh1+ 15.
Bf1 Qc6 {with a dynamically balanced game, Meskovs,N (2467)-Kulaots,K (2568)
Viljandi 2016 1/2-1/2 (57)}) (10... Rb8 {forces White to sacrifice a piece with
} 11. Be2 {and now} axb5 12. Nxb5 g5 13. Bxg5 Qc6 14. O-O (14. O-O-O {is also
possible, and far from clear}) 14... b6 15. Qa7 Rb7 16. Qa8 {gives White
adequate compensation, with two pawns for the piece and better developed
forces, Ben Ari,Y (2367)-Musyuk,L (2343) Petah Tikva 2020 1/2-1/2 (47)}) 11.
Bxe5 Nxe5 12. O-O-O Rb8 13. Nd4 {Reaching another important branching point.}
Be7 {A novelty, but this appears to give White hopes for an edge. Practice has
shown that the g7-square is usually a better post for the f8-bishop in this
setup. Not only does the bishop have more scope on the long diagonal, but the
e7-square can sometimes be a useful bolt-hole for Black's queen. In fact Black
has several decent alternatives here:} (13... Bg7 14. Qc2 O-O $2 (14... Qc7 {
is called for}) 15. g4 $1 {gave White strong attacking chances in
Predke-Vachier-Lagrave, which is analyzed in the Archives.}) (13... Qc7 14. Be2
Be7 (14... Bg7 {is once again a better post for the bishop}) 15. Kb1 Nc6 {
Aronian, L (2739) -Leko, P (2753) Morelia/Linares 2008 1/2-1/2 (51), and here}
16. Qc2 {threatening 17 Nd5 gives White a plus}) (13... Qb4 14. Qc2 {Rambaldi,
F (2560)-Abdumalik, Z (2390) Doha 2015 �-� (43)} b6 15. a3 Qe7 {gives the
queen a safe posting, and Black should be fine after following up with ...
Bc8-b7.}) 14. Be2 Qb4 15. Qc2 {Declining the queen trade and offering a
sacrifice of the c4-pawn. White is banking on his lead in development and the
fact that Black's queen is exposed.} Nxc4 {Instead of grabbing the pawn, Black
should perhaps consider a pawn sac of his own in search of counterplay:} (15...
b5 {and now} 16. cxb5 Bb7 17. Rhf1 axb5 18. Ndxb5 g4 {leaves Black with some
compensation, since White's extra pawn is in front of the king, so it is
harder for White to consolidate.}) 16. a3 Nxa3 {Black needs to take the plunge
with this piece sac, since:} (16... Qc5 17. Ne4 Qb6 18. Bxc4 d5 19. Bxd5 exd5
20. Nc3 {just leaves White with a much superior structure and a clear
advantage.}) 17. bxa3 Qxa3+ {Material is roughly balanced (3 pawns for a piece)
but White's more active pieces outweigh the risk to White's exposed king.} 18.
Kd2 d5 {After this, White starts to establish a grip on the position. Instead:}
(18... b5 {is more active. After} 19. Ra1 Qd6 20. Rhc1 Bb7 {Black is still in
the game.}) 19. Rb1 Bd7 {Now:} (19... b5 {can be well met by} 20. Nc6) 20. Rb3
Qd6 21. Rhb1 b5 22. Bxb5 $1 {An important tactical blow. Without this, Black's
pawns are rolling forward to good effect.} axb5 23. Ncxb5 Bxb5 24. Nxb5 Rxb5 {
The point is that Black can't avoid losing material here. If:} (24... Qd8 25.
Nc7+ Kd7 26. Rxb8 {White wins.}) 25. Rxb5 O-O 26. Ke2 {White is an exchange up
for a pawn, but the technical task ahead is not trivial.} Bf6 27. f4 {A bit
loosening.} (27. Kf1 {looks sensible, safeguarding the king before initiating
pawn breaks.}) 27... h6 28. Rb6 Qd8 {Over the next few moves, Black misses
some chances to go for activity and make the ...d5-d4 break to open up White's
king. Here:} (28... Qa3 29. f5 d4 {is a better attempt at counterplay.}) 29.
Rc6 (29. f5 $1 {was a good time for this break}) 29... Bg7 30. Rd1 Qa8 31. Kf3
Qa3 32. Rd3 Qa1 33. Kg2 Ra8 34. Rd2 Qa3 35. Re2 Rd8 (35... d4 {was again the
best chance.}) 36. f5 {Finally changing the structure to open lines for the
heavy pieces.} exf5 37. Qxf5 Qe7 38. Kf3 {A curious move.} (38. Rf2 {ties
Black to the defence of the f7-pawn, and White remains in control.}) 38... Qb7
39. Rec2 d4 {Black is back with chances since White's 38th move exposed his
own king.} 40. exd4 Rxd4 41. Qc8+ {Trading queens since otherwise White's king
is too open.} Qxc8 42. Rxc8+ Kh7 43. R2c7 Kg6 44. Rc6+ Bf6 45. Rg8+ Kh7 46. Ra8
Be5 47. Ra7 Kg7 48. Rc5 Bb8 {Opting for passive defence but White has to prove
how to break through.} 49. Rb7 Rd8 50. Rf5 Rf8 51. Rd5 Rc8 52. Rdd7 Rf8 53. Rb6
h5 $2 {A fatal weakening of Black's pawn structure.} (53... Rc8 54. Kg4 Rc7 $5
{keeps Black's defences intact.}) 54. Rb5 g4+ 55. Kg2 Rc8 {Giving up the
h5-pawn, but after:} (55... Kg6 56. Rdb7 {the bishop is dominated and lost
after} Bd6 57. R7b6 {pinning and winning!}) 56. Rxh5 {After this breakthrough,
White quickly wraps up the game.} Rc2+ 57. Kf1 Kg6 58. Rb5 Bc7 59. Rb4 f5 60.
Ra4 Kg5 61. Ra6 Be5 62. Re7 Bd4 63. Ree6 {Black's king is caught in mating net.
} 1-0


