{[%evp 0,59,42,12,100,79,100,36,32,-2,-16,-31,-12,6,-5,-5,67,10,65,-14,23,32,
31,52,52,56,56,64,133,92,106,69,77,69,108,97,106,102,98,102,140,120,128,116,
163,115,125,127,103,108,113,108,108,98,109,90,90,84,84,86,95,105]} 1. e4 {
Erigaisi, Arjun} c5 2. Nf3 e6 {This came as a surprise so I decided to counter
surprise him over the board with this calm move.} 3. g3 ({instead of entering
the mainstream theory with} 3. d4) 3... Nc6 4. Bg2 {White aims to develop
quickly on the kingside instead of going for the central break.} d5 {With this
move Black decides to accept IQP and tries to look for activity} (4... Nf6 {
is by far the main move} 5. d3 {[%cal Gb1d2,Ge1g1,Gh1f1] I was intending to do
this during the game.} (5. e5 {runs into} Ng4 6. Qe2 Qc7 {[%csl Re5]}) (5. Qe2
e5 {[%cal Gd7d6,Gf8e7,Ge8g8,Gh8f8] is a popular line. It feels weird for Black
to play e6 and then e5, but Black seems to be doing alright here as White's
queen on e2 is not the best piece in the world.})) 5. exd5 exd5 6. O-O Nf6 7.
d4 cxd4 (7... Be7 8. dxc5 Bxc5 {[%csl Gc5,Rf2] is another version which is
also fine but I assume he was unhappy to move the bishop twice. Trying to go
after Black's uncastled king doesn't really help as the bishop on c5 is
staring down the a7-f2 diagonal.} (8... O-O 9. Be3 Ng4 10. Bd4 {[%csl Gc5]
White preserves the extra pawn.}) 9. Re1+ Be6 10. Ng5 $6 O-O 11. Nxe6 fxe6 12.
Rxe6 $2 Ne4 $17 {[%csl Rf2]}) 8. Nxd4 Be7 (8... Bg4 {only helps White as the
queen would be better placed on d3 and White gains a tempo with h3.} 9. Qd3 Be7
10. h3 Bd7 11. Nc3 O-O 12. Bf4) 9. h3 {Preventing all kinds of Ng4/Bg4
business before playing Be3.} O-O 10. Be3 (10. Nc3 {also possible to start
with this move but I wanted to keep it flexible as I had some Nd2 ideas in my
mind in the game.}) 10... Nxd4 $6 (10... Re8 {clearly should have been played.
Releasing the tension was not the best idea but his whole point with 10...Nxd4
is based on 13...Bb4 which turns out to be a blunder.}) 11. Bxd4 Bf5 {Qc8 with
a double attack is the threat for now.} 12. Nc3 $14 {This is already a slight
edge for White as the bishop on d4 looks like a monster.} Ne4 (12... Rc8 13.
Re1) 13. Re1 {Unfortunate that he touched the bishop intending Bb4 which runs
into Bxg7.} Bf6 {This was the best move available for him after touching the
bishop, but this is already close to lost as Black is losing a pawn by force
and it's psychologically very tough for him to continue and offer most
resistance as he ended up in such a horrendous position in just 13 moves!} (
13... Re8 14. Qd3 {and White keeps a good advantage as Black's setup is not
harmonious}) (13... Bb4 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Qd4+ Qf6 16. Qxb4 $18) (13... Nxc3
14. Bxc3 Be6 15. Bd4 Bf6 16. c3 {[%csl Rd5,Re6,Gg2] is an excellent advantage
for White as his light-squared bishop spits fire on the poor d5 pawn.}) 14.
Bxf6 Nxf6 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. Qxd5 Qxd5 (16... Bxc2 {is another variation that I
considered during the game but keeping the queens only helps White as White's
queen is superior to Black's} 17. Qxb7) 17. Bxd5 Bxc2 (17... Bxh3 {taking this
pawn is a bad idea as after} 18. Bxb7 Rab8 19. Re7 {[%csl Ga2,Ra7,Gb2,Gc2] I
have a clear 2 pawn majority on the queenside and my pawns will soon start
marching down the board.}) 18. Re7 (18. Bxb7 {is also possible but the that
pawn is mine in any case}) 18... Rad8 (18... Bf5 {is what I was expecting
during the game.} 19. Bxb7 Rab8 20. b4 $1 (20. Bg2 Rxb2 21. Rxa7 {is also
possible with fair chances of converting this into a win.}) 20... Bxh3 21. b5 {
[%cal Gb7c6,Ga2a4] although the material is equal White's activity and the
outside passer on the queenside give him a big advantage.}) 19. Bxb7 {White's
aim is to win the a7 pawn and create outside passers on the queenside.} a5 {
Black intends to get the pawn to a4 and restrict White's b2 pawn.} (19... Bf5
20. Bg2 {[%cal Ge7a7]}) 20. Rae1 ({Hence} 20. b3 $1 {would have been a good
move here:} a4 21. b4) 20... a4 (20... Bf5 {is a critical line as Black would
have good drawing chances if he managed to bring the bishop to e6.} 21. R7e5
Be6 (21... Bxh3 22. Rxa5 $18 {[%csl Ra2,Rb2]}) 22. b3 $1 (22. Rxa5 Rb8 23. Ra7
(23. Bf3 Rxb2 {and Black has decent drawing chances as the R on a5 is badly
placed}) 23... Rfd8 {White is kind of paralyzed and Black gets good chances to
hold.}) 22... Rd7 23. Bf3 a4 24. bxa4 Bxa2 25. a5 {The whole point is now
White's own rook is not blocking its own pawn, unlike after 22.Rxa5. This is
winning but some technique is still required.}) 21. Bc6 $1 {Putting pressure
on the target.} Rd4 22. Rd7 {Trying to trade off Black's active rook after
which the pawn on a4 would be extremely weak.} Rb4 23. Rd2 Bf5 (23... Rc4 24.
Bd5 (24. Bb5 Rc5 25. Bd7 g6 26. Rc1 Rd8 27. Rdxc2 Rxc2 28. Rxc2 Rxd7 29. Kf1 {
This is a debatable endgame.}) 24... Rcc8 25. Rc1 {true to the spirit -
trading off Black's active rook} Bf5 26. Rxc8 Rxc8 27. Bc6 a3 28. b4 {and
White is on the verge of winning.}) (23... Rxb2 {runs into} 24. Be4 $18) 24. a3
(24. Kg2 {has a different approach,keeping the h3 pawn alive and playing it
slow which is perfectly sensible too.}) 24... Rb6 25. Bxa4 Bxh3 {White finally
achieved what he wanted and now it's a matter of technique.} 26. Re5 (26. Re3 {
[%cal Gb3b4,Gb2b4] is the most precise} Be6 27. b4) (26. Re8 {would have been
the simplest if it weren't for} Rxe8 27. Bxe8 Kf8 28. Ba4 Bg4 {after which
White's bishop is stranded and it's tough to roll the pawns although this
still should be won with some struggle.}) ({White should not rush with} 26. b4
$2 {as after} Ra6 {he loses the pawn on a3.}) 26... Rfb8 $6 {Doesn't change
the result of the game but it is a dubious move because it makes White's job
easier.} (26... g6 {would have offered more resistance as now Rb5 can be met
with} 27. Rb5 Ra6) 27. Rb5 $1 Kf8 28. Rd8+ (28. Rxb6 {wins too:} Rxb6 29. Bd1
Ke7 30. b4 Bd7 31. f4 $18) 28... Rxd8 29. Rxb6 Be6 ({He could have tried to
offer better resistance with} 29... g5) 30. Bb3 {Black resigned here although
White still needs to show some precision.} 1-0


