1. d4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. Bf4 e6 4. Nb5 ({The topical move, although I still
suspect many club players will prefer} 4. e3 {, as covered, or so I'm told, in
Simon Williams's forthcoming repertoire for Everyman Chess.}) 4... Na6 ({
Erigaisi has also faced} 4... Bb4+ $5 5. c3 Ba5 {and following} 6. e3 a6 7. Na3
Nbd7 8. Nf3 O-O {White wasted no time in regrouping with} 9. Nb1 {, which led
in Erigaisi-Dubov, Internet (rapid) 2022, after} c5 $5 10. dxc5 Bc7 11. Bxc7
Qxc7 12. b4 b6 13. cxb6 Nxb6 14. Be2 e5 {to a position where the engines
slightly prefer White, but from a practical perspective at least it would be
surprising if Black didn't have decent play for his pawn.}) 5. e3 Be7 6. h4 $5
({Immediately! Only in April's update did we see the no less striking and
closely-related} 6. Nf3 O-O 7. h4 $5 c6 8. Nc3 c5 {in Van Foreest-Giri, Oslo
Esports Cup (rapid) 2022, where I suspected that White should now go} 9. h5 $5
{.}) 6... c6 7. Nc3 c5 8. Nf3 {Play now looks very likely to transpose to our
previous note, but actually it never does as Harsha now elects not to castle.}
Bd7 $5 9. Ne5 {A thematic leap, not least when Black's knight is on the rim
rather than c6.} Nb4 $6 ({Heading for c6 is sensible, but also rather slow.
Black needed to disrupt with} 9... Qb6 $1 {when} 10. Qd2 (10. Nxd7 Nxd7 11. Bb5
{is also possible, but here Black has at least} Rd8) 10... Rc8 {remains pretty
unclear and certainly I wouldn't feel too confident as White going} 11. O-O-O {
here,} ({with} 11. Rh3 $5 {perhaps a good way to cover across to c3 and so
safely continue to swap b2 for b7.})) 10. g4 $1 {Another thematic move and one
which seizes the initiative.} O-O {Brave, but at least this way the knight
obtains a retreat square on e8.} 11. dxc5 {This wasn't essential, but it
certainly doesn't do White any harm to take the options of ...cxd4 and ...c4
off the table.} Bxc5 12. g5 Ne8 13. h5 f6 $6 ({An understandable bid for
freedom and to fight back on the kingside, but it seems that nothing too awful
should be happening to Black after} 13... Bd6 {, and if} 14. g6 (14. Nxd7 Qxd7
15. a3 Nc6 16. Qd2 {followed by 0-0-0 should at least favour White}) 14... fxg6
15. hxg6 h6 {.}) 14. gxf6 Nxf6 15. Rg1 ({Eyeing g7 while getting off the h1-a8
diagonal. This makes a lot of sense, although even after} 15. Qd2 d4 16. exd4
Bxd4 17. h6) ({and} 15. Qe2 $5 d4 16. exd4 Bxd4 17. O-O-O $1 {White should be
doing quite well.}) 15... Be8 $1 ({Good defence. Erigaisi's idea against} 15...
d4 {was presumably} 16. h6 $1 g6 (16... dxc3 $2 17. Rxg7+ Kh8 18. Nxd7 cxb2 19.
Rb1 Qa5 20. Bc4 $1 {seems to be winning for White}) 17. a3 {, and if} dxc3 18.
axb4 Bxb4 19. b3 {when White is in control and menaces a rather large
sacrifice on g6.}) 16. Bh3 $2 ({Losing the thread. White should have settled
for simply} 16. h6 g6 17. a3 Nc6 {and only then} 18. Bh3 {, thereby preserving
control and a definite plus.}) 16... Nxh5 $1 (16... Bxh5 $5 17. Bh6 g6 {
was also promising.}) 17. Bxe6+ Kh8 18. Nxd5 {The point of White's play, but
his huddle of centralised pieces creates a strange impression and, moreover,
they are vulnerable.} Nxd5 (18... Rf6 $1 {would have been hard to spot in a
rapid game, but after} 19. Nxf6 ({or, and importantly,} 19. Bg5 Rxe6 $1 20.
Bxd8 Rxd8 {when Black will pick up a third piece as well as the initiative for
the queen}) 19... Qxf6 {there wouldn't have been anything for the king on h8
to fear, in contrast to which its counterpart would very much have felt the
heat.}) 19. Qxd5 Nxf4 20. exf4 Bxf2+ $4 ({Tempting, but flawed. Instead, with} 
20... Qe7 21. Nd3 Bd6 22. O-O-O Bxf4+ 23. Kb1 Bc6 {Black would have been
slightly for choice with his bishops and/or pressure against f2.}) 21. Kxf2
Qh4+ 22. Rg3 ({Or even} 22. Kg2 $1 Rxf4 23. Raf1 Qg5+ 24. Kh2 {when the bishop
can drop back to h3.}) 22... Rd8 $2 (22... Qh2+ 23. Qg2 Rxf4+ {was a better
try, if still rather good for White after} 24. Rf3 Rxf3+ 25. Nxf3 Qc7 {.}) 23.
Nf3 $1 Rxf4 ({The black queen suddenly lacks a great square in view of} 23...
Qf6 24. Qe5) ({and} 23... Qe7 24. Qe5 {followed by Rh1.}) 24. Rh1 {It's all
over bar a few final desperate kicks.} Qxh1 25. Qxd8 Rf8 26. Qe7 Qh2+ 27. Kf1
Rxf3+ 28. Rxf3 Qh1+ 29. Ke2 Qg2+ 30. Rf2 Bh5+ 31. Kd3 $1 Bg6+ 32. Kc3 Qg3+ 33.
Kc4 b5+ 34. Kd5 1-0


