1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 Ne4 3. Bf4 d5 4. e3 c5 5. Bd3 g6 $5 {An extremely rare move
at this stage and a new one for ChessPub. I wonder if it may become more
popular though, in part due to this game and in part because it makes it into
Stockfish's top three moves.} 6. Be5 $6 ({A new move, ChessBase tells me, and
probably not a great one. Previously,} 6. dxc5 $5 Bg7 7. Bxe4 $1 (7. c3 $6 Nxc5
8. Bc2 Nc6 {would just leave Black taking over}) 7... Bxb2 (7... dxe4 $1 8.
Qxd8+ Kxd8 {looks OK for Black, and if} 9. Nd2 $1 Bxb2 10. Rb1 Ba3 11. Nxe4 Na6
{with rough equality}) 8. Bxd5 Bxa1 9. c3 {had given White promising
compensation for the exchange in Dimitrov-Azarov, Cattolica 2022, and soon
more than that after} Nc6 $2 (9... Nd7 10. Ne2 O-O 11. O-O Nxc5 12. Bh6 Bf5 $1
{seems to be the critical line}) 10. Ne2 Qa5 11. O-O O-O 12. Nd2 {when Black's
bishop was trapped in view of} Bxc3 13. Nb3 Qb4 14. a3 $1 {.}) ({There's also
the simple} 6. Nd2 {, after which} Nxd2 7. Qxd2 Bg7 8. c3 Nc6 9. Nf3 {can't be
any more than a tiny bit better for White.}) 6... f6 {Correctly forcing the
pace.} 7. Bxb8 (7. Bg3 cxd4 8. exd4 Bg7 {would merely give Black active and
easy play.}) 7... Rxb8 {Presumably Erigaisi hoped there was a good way to show
up ...f6 as being weakening, but there doesn't seem to be one and already
Black is just quite comfortable from what I can see.} 8. Nf3 $6 (8. c3 {
would be safer, if still nothing for Black to worry about after} Bg7 9. Nd2 f5
{.}) 8... Bg7 $6 ({With the engine idea} 8... Qb6 9. Qc1 Bh6 $1 {Black might
have seized an early initiative and advantage.}) 9. O-O cxd4 10. exd4 O-O ({
Another tempting possibility for Black is} 10... Bg4 $5 11. c4 f5 {when} 12.
cxd5 O-O {would transpose to the game.}) 11. c4 {Attempting to destabilise
Black in the centre, but he isn't forced by any means to go ...e6.} Bg4 $1 {
The first of a two-part sequence which leaves Black actively placed, as well
as again with easy play.} 12. cxd5 f5 {The key follow-up, maintaining control
of e4. I can't believe that Erigaisi was feeling too happy here as White and
it's safe to say that his opening hasn't been a huge success.} 13. Be2 ({
This seems sensible, although if White didn't mind simplification,} 13. Nc3 $5
Bxf3 14. gxf3 (14. Qxf3 $2 Nd2 {wins the exchange}) 14... Nxc3 15. bxc3 Qxd5 (
15... Kh8 $5 16. Qb3 Qc7 {offers Black pleasant compensation, but is it any
more than that?}) 16. Qb3 {wasn't ridiculous, already looking to the drawing
potential of the opposite-coloured bishops.}) 13... Qb6 14. Qb3 ({Only now
does Erigaisi look to simplify. I can't help wondering if the early events in
the game had thrown him slightly off kilter. Here there was also} 14. Nbd2 $5 {
, fighting for the initiative, and if} Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Qxb2 16. Bxe4 fxe4 17.
Nxe4 {when both sides have their trumps and all three results would be
possible, even after} Rf4 18. Re1 $1 Bxd4 19. Rb1 Bxf2+ 20. Nxf2 Qxf2+ 21. Kh1
{.}) 14... Qxb3 15. axb3 Bxf3 ({A decent case might also be made for
activating the black rooks beginning with} 15... Rfc8 $5 {.}) 16. gxf3 ({
Retaining pieces and a fair degree of complexity. I dare say that Erigaisi
didn't want to have to grovel against his Kazakh IM opponent, although after} 
16. Bxf3 Bxd4 17. Bxe4 fxe4 {White should be OK if he finds} 18. Ra4 $1 {.})
16... Ng5 17. Rd1 {Prudently electing to hold on to the bishop-obstructing
pawn on d4.} Nh3+ $1 {Zhalmakhanov finds just about the only way to retain a
degree of pressure, by causing a few problems for the white king.} 18. Kf1 a6
19. b4 $1 ({A precise choice, whereas} 19. Nc3 {would have allowed} Rf6 $1 20.
b4 b5 {followed by ...Nf4 when Black would have been in full control.}) 19...
Nf4 ({Now} 19... Rf6 20. b5 {should be OK for White, as shown by} axb5 21. Bxb5
Rb6 22. Ra5 Nf4 23. Na3 {, with a draw the most likely result.}) 20. Nc3 Rfd8
21. Ra5 $1 {Correctly fighting to maintain both d-pawns. Black's position is
quite pleasant here, but it's far from easy to see how he's supposed to turn
that into more than a draw.} Kf8 $5 {A fairly clever try, stepping off the
a2-g8 diagonal and provoking Bc4.} 22. Bc4 $2 ({Erigaisi would love to follow
up with Rc5, but he won't be allowed the time for that. Instead,} 22. b5 $1 {
was correct when} Bf6 $5 (22... Nxd5 23. bxa6 Nxc3 24. bxc3 bxa6 25. Rxa6 {
is very likely to end in a draw}) 23. Bc4 axb5 24. Rxb5 Kg7 {would have
retained the rough balance.}) 22... b5 $1 23. Bb3 Rb6 {Black continues to
outplay his much high-rated opponent. Just what is that rook now doing on a5?}
24. Raa1 (24. Rda1 {doesn't especially help in view of} Rdd6 {.}) 24... Bf6 25.
Ke1 Ng2+ 26. Ke2 Nf4+ 27. Ke1 Ng2+ 28. Kf1 Nf4 29. Ke1 {Wisely acquiescing to
the repetition.} Ng2+ $2 ({With such pleasant control of the position and
White so tied down, Black should really have continued. Following, for example,
} 29... Kg7 30. Kf1 h5 $1 31. Ra3 h4 {White would have found himself getting
squeezed and even the radical} 32. Ne2 $5 Nxd5 33. Bxd5 Rxd5 34. f4 {would
have left him somewhat worse and having to fight hard to hold a draw.}) 1/2-1/2


