1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 Bc5 {This popular try continues to crop up on a
regular basis.} 4. Nc3 {By far White's most common move overall, but the
alternative:} (4. d3 {has been tested in a number of high-level games,
including} O-O 5. Nc3 c6 6. Nf3 d6 7. O-O a5 8. d4 exd4 9. Nxd4 a4 {which was
played in Ding Liren-Firouzja from the 2022 Candidates - see the game in the
Archives.}) 4... c6 5. e3 {White goes for the logical setup involving Ng1-e2
and an early d2-d4, also eschewing the sharp complications that arise after:} (
5. Nf3 e4 6. Nh4 d5 7. cxd5 cxd5 8. d3 Ng4 9. O-O g5 {which is analyzed in
Liu-Ju Wenjun and earlier games in the Archives.}) 5... Bb6 {A prophylactic
move, anticipating White's d2-d4 push, while remaining flexible. In particular,
keeping options open for either ...d7-d5 or ...d7-d6. Black has also played:} (
5... d6 {This is a little passive, and allows White to achieve the desired
setup. Now} 6. Nge2 a5 7. d4 Ba7 8. b3 Na6 9. Bb2 O-O 10. h3 Re8 11. Qd2 Bf5
12. O-O h6 13. Rad1 {was pleasant for White in Kosten-Fedorchuk, which is
included in the Archives.}) (5... d5 6. cxd5 {and now:} cxd5 (6... O-O $5 {
offering a pawn, is possible. Now} 7. Nge2 (7. dxc6 Nxc6 {gives Black good
compensation due to White's exposure on the light squares.}) 7... Nxd5 8. Nxd5
cxd5 9. d4 exd4 10. Nxd4 Nc6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. O-O Qb6 {was balanced in
Zarubitski,V (2460)-Goganov,A (2527) Cheliabinsk 2022 0-1 (47)}) (6... Nxd5 {
if Black commits to this capture immediately (rather than waiting for 6...0-0
7 Nge2), White has the option of} 7. Nf3 {which is a more active post for the
knight.}) 7. d4 exd4 8. exd4 Bb4 9. Nge2 O-O 10. O-O h6 11. Nf4 Bxc3 12. bxc3
Nc6 13. Re1 Qa5 14. Bd2 Qd8 {and now} 15. Qc2 {leaves White with an edge, as
he has the bishop pair and move active pieces.} (15. Bc1 Qa5 16. Bd2 Qd8 17.
Bc1 {was instead, a repetition draw in �-� (17) Xu,Y (2554)-Ju,W (2560)
Xinghua 2021})) 6. d4 (6. Nge2 d5 7. cxd5 cxd5 8. d4 e4 {This illustrates the
point behind the move 5...Bb6 - Black is not forced to trade on the d4-square
and instead has the space-gaining ...e5-e4 thrust available.} 9. O-O O-O 10. f3
exf3 11. Bxf3 {was played in Sawyer,B (2172)-Wagner,D (2584) Chess.com INT
2022 0-1 (30), and here} Nc6 12. Nf4 Be6 {is fine for Black.}) 6... exd4 7.
exd4 O-O {Instead:} (7... d5 {is also playable. After} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 (8... cxd5
{is inadvisable due to} 9. Bg5) 9. Qe2+ Be6 10. Nf3 O-O 11. O-O Re8 12. Ng5 Bf5
13. Qf3 Bg6 14. Nxd5 cxd5 {the position is balanced, but White now went wrong
with} 15. Qg4 $6 (15. Qxd5 {is equal}) 15... h6 16. Nh3 Nd7 17. Be3 Nf6 {
and Black's pieces are better coordinated, Piorun,K (2623)-Navara,D (2703)
Germany 2021 0-1 (56)}) 8. Nge2 d6 {Compared to lines with ...d7-d5, this
keeps more tension in the position, so retains more long term chances for
Black to play for a win. On the other hand, it does cede White more space, and
likely an objective advantage as well.} (8... d5 9. cxd5 Nxd5 {Dann,M (2508)
-Kurmann,O (2424) Mulhouse 2021 �-� (21), is similar to Piorun-Navara from
the previous note, and is fine for Black.}) 9. O-O Re8 10. Bf4 {The first new
move, but perhaps not the most purposeful place for the bishop. If White plays
Bc1-e3 instead, the d4-pawn is defended and this frees up White's queen and
e2-knight for active play, for example:} (10. h3 d5 {Black decides to play
this even with a loss of tempo.} 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 cxd5 13. Nf4 Nc6 14.
Be3 Be6 {�-� (30) Firsching,G (2502)-Koenig,U (2451) Remote email 2014 and
now} 15. a4 {leaves White with slight pressure.}) (10. Be3 {is also possible.
Now} Be6 11. Qb3 Qc8 12. Nf4 {leaves White for choice.}) 10... Be6 11. Qd3 {
After this, the game gravitates towards equality. Alternatively:} (11. d5 {
is more ambitious, although after} cxd5 12. cxd5 Bg4 13. Qd2 Nbd7 14. Bxd6 Bxe2
15. Nxe2 Ng4 {Black gets sufficient counterplay.}) 11... Na6 12. a3 Qd7 13.
Rfe1 d5 14. c5 Bd8 15. b4 Nc7 16. a4 Bf5 {Black is a bit cramped but has no
real problems.} 17. Qd2 Ne6 18. Bd6 Be7 19. Bxe7 Rxe7 20. Nf4 Rae8 21. Nxe6
Rxe6 22. Rxe6 Qxe6 23. b5 h5 {Around here, both players underestimate White's
potential chances on the queenside.} (23... a6 {would stop further advances,
and then} 24. bxa6 bxa6 25. a5 (25. Bf1 {is met with} a5) 25... Bh3 {is level.}
) 24. h4 {After:} (24. a5 $1 a6 25. bxa6 bxa6 26. Bf1 {Black is forced to
defend the weak a6-pawn.}) 24... Bh3 25. Qf4 Bxg2 26. Kxg2 Ng4 27. bxc6 bxc6
28. Rb1 Qc8 29. Ne2 f6 30. Nc3 {Both players are probing for chances.} Kh7 31.
Rb2 Qa6 32. Rb8 Rxb8 33. Qxb8 Qd3 34. Qb1 Qxb1 35. Nxb1 g5 {After the trade of
heavy pieces, the knight endgame remains balanced.} 36. Nd2 gxh4 37. gxh4 Nh6
38. Nb3 Nf5 39. Kf3 Nxh4+ 40. Kf4 Kg7 41. Na5 Ng6+ 42. Kf5 h4 43. Kg4 Ne7 44.
Kxh4 Nf5+ 45. Kg4 Nxd4 {Black has won a pawn, but White has things under
control.} 46. Kf4 Kf7 47. Ke3 Nf5+ 48. Kf4 Ne7 49. Nb3 Kg6 50. Nd4 Kh5 51. Ne6
Kh4 52. Nf8 Kh3 53. Nd7 Kg2 54. Nxf6 Kxf2 55. Ke5 Ke3 56. Kd6 d4 57. Ng4+ Kf3
58. Ne5+ Ke4 59. Nc4 d3 60. Kxe7 Kd5 {All of White's pawns will disappear, but
the knight holds.} 61. Nb2 d2 62. Kf6 a5 63. Nd1 Kxc5 64. Ke5 Kb4 65. Kd4 Kxa4
66. Kc3 c5 67. Nb2+ 1/2-1/2


