{[%evp 0,114,16,26,26,53,63,-17,8,-17,-52,-62,-15,13,13,17,17,41,51,-7,15,-1,7,
16,42,-7,0,0,85,58,76,76,77,-1,24,1,-14,-38,-39,-50,-14,-33,-15,-71,-74,-75,
-61,-63,-65,-78,-101,-101,-63,-113,-65,-58,-58,-72,-78,-78,-81,-95,-95,-84,
-102,-102,-117,-78,-121,-142,-91,-81,-56,-58,-58,-49,-36,-27,-86,-56,-63,-112,
-100,-138,-183,-137,-174,-197,-211,-216,-255,-223,-314,-671,-314,-314,-314,
-314,-341,-341,-341,-347,-445,-703,-957,-1002,-973,-1012,-1012,-813,-1013,-716,
-1479,-1479,-1499,-1499,-28707]} 1. e4 {Erigaisi, Arjun} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
a6 4. Ba4 Bc5 {An old move which is being tried out in the modern days
although not as frequntely as the main Ruy Lopez. Black intends to put his N
on e7 here} 5. c3 {The most challenging move with the intention to strike in
the centre immediately.} (5. O-O d6 {is important here as} (5... Nge7 {would
run into} 6. Nxe5 Nxe5 7. d4 $14) 6. c3 Ba7 {is how the line continues.}) 5...
Nge7 6. d4 exd4 7. cxd4 Bb4+ {The whole point. If not for this move, Black is
close to lost already as White gets a predominant hold of the centre after} (
7... Ba7 8. d5 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4]}) 8. Bd2 (8. Nc3 d5 {is another possible line.})
8... Bxd2+ 9. Qxd2 (9. Nbxd2 {Safer but also less ambitious.} d5) 9... d5 10.
exd5 Qxd5 (10... Nxd5 {is a possible line which is less risky but also keeps
less chances.}) 11. Nc3 (11. O-O {is a safer line and White preserves a very
little edge after} O-O 12. Nc3) 11... Qe6+ 12. Kf1 {The most natural move with
the rook swinging over to the e-file and the isolated pawn forking. At first
sight it looks like Black is not well coordinated but there is a wonderful
resource.} (12. Qe3 {was necessary and it ensures that White remains on top in
the endgame.}) 12... Qc4+ 13. Kg1 Be6 $1 {The check followed by this move does
not come naturally at all as it looks like queen is getting trapped on c4, but
magically nothing is working out for White.} 14. Ne5 (14. a3 {does not work
due to} O-O-O 15. b3 Nxd4 $1 {The whole point.} 16. bxc4 Nxf3+ 17. gxf3 Rxd2
$19) (14. b3 Qb4 {[%cal Gb4d6,Gb4b6] and we escape with our queen.}) 14... Qb4
15. a3 {A slightly dubious move in practice in my opinion, as White doesn't
get any structural advantage in return for wasting some tempi with the king.} (
15. Nxc6 Nxc6 16. Bxc6+ bxc6 17. Rd1 {would lead to a double edged game.})
15... Qb6 16. Bxc6+ (16. Nxc6 Nxc6 17. d5 O-O-O 18. Rd1 Ne7 19. Qg5 Qc5 20. h4
$13) 16... Nxc6 17. Nxc6 Qxc6 $1 {A very smart move.} 18. h4 $2 {This was
certainly a bad move as Black now gets a dream position where he is more
active and White has a weak IQP.} (18. d5 O-O-O 19. Rd1 {was necessary as
White trades off the queens and liquidates into an endgame where it should be
very close to equal but fighting.} ({Black is much better in the endgame after
} 19. dxc6 Rxd2 {due to his activity}) 19... Qb6 20. Qe3 Qxe3 21. fxe3 Bd7 $11)
18... O-O-O 19. h5 {White tries to get the rook into life from h4. I really
love the way I dealt with this.} Bd5 {Hitting the g2 pawn} 20. f3 (20. Nxd5
Rxd5 21. Rh4 Rhd8 {[%csl Rd4,Rh5] is better for Black as there is a lot of
pressure on the d4 and h5 pawns.}) 20... Qf6 {Preventing the R from coming to
h4.} 21. Qf2 Bb3 {Hitting the d4 pawn.} 22. Rh4 {and it seems like White
achieved what was intended. Doesn't it?} Rhe8 {Yes, the rook is active now and
that is pretty much what White wanted, but now the problem for White is the
poor coordination amongst his pieces. Q is paralyzed on f2 as it has to
protect h4 and f2, R on a1 struggles to find a good square, N on c3 cannot be
moved, and the R on h4 can move but it doesn't really help White. On the other
hand, Black's every single piece is very active.} 23. Rg4 Qh6 {Giving way for
the f7-pawn and hitting the P on h5 at the same time.} 24. Re1 f5 25. Rh4 Bf7 {
Nevertheless,Black is still much better.} (25... Rxe1+ 26. Qxe1 Qf6 27. Qf2 {
It's precise to paralyze White's major pieces completely and only now return
with the bishop to put pressure on the h5 pawn.} Bf7) 26. Kh2 (26. Rxe8 Rxe8
$17) 26... Bxh5 {Grabbing the pawn!} (26... Rxe1 27. Qxe1 Bxh5 28. Qe5 (28. Qe7
g5 29. Rh3 g4) 28... Qg5 29. Rh3 Re8) 27. Rxe8 Rxe8 28. Qg3 (28. g4 {doesn't
win the biship because Black has a check along the h2-b8 diagonal.} fxg4 29.
fxg4 Qd6+ $19) 28... Qg6 {When up material, trade pieces!} 29. Qf4 Qf7 {
Consolidating the extra pawn by getting everything stable.} 30. d5 Bg6 31. d6 {
White finally gets rid of the weak d-pawn, but it's too late as the damage is
already done.} Rd8 {Liquidating to an endgame.} 32. dxc7 Qxc7 33. Qxc7+ Kxc7
34. Ne2 {Not a blunder,White tries to do something concrete which is sensible.}
(34. Rc4+ Kb8 {is just an extra pawn for Black.}) 34... Rd2 (34... h6 35. Rc4+
Kb8 36. Rd4 $17) 35. Nf4 Rxb2 (35... Kb6 $5 36. Nxg6 hxg6 37. Rh7 Rd7) 36. Nxg6
hxg6 37. Rh7 {The whole point.} Kb6 $2 {I was lured into doing this as it
intuitively seemed winning as Black's king is more active.} (37... Rb6 38.
Rxg7+ Kb8 {[%cal Ga5a4,Gb8a7,Ga7a6,Ga6a5] Black keeps the extra pawn on the
queenside and with some difficulty, this can be converted into a win:} 39. Kg3
a5 40. Kf4 a4 $19 {[%cal Gb8a7,Ga7a6,Ga6a5]}) 38. Rxg7 Ka5 39. Rxg6 Ka4 40. Rg5
$2 {This loses because of ...} (40. Rf6 $1 {is the only move that holds and
the point is after} Rb5 (40... Kxa3 41. Rxf5 b5 42. Kh3 {This is holding
because Black cannot rush with his b-pawn as it runs into Ra5 and after} a5 (
42... b4 43. Ra5+ Kb3 44. Rxa6) 43. g4 a4 44. g5 {White is in time to march
his g-pawn:} b4 45. g6 Rb1 46. Kg2 (46. g7 Rg1) 46... Rb2+ 47. Kh3 Rb1 $11 {
with a repitition.}) 41. g4 fxg4 42. fxg4 Kxa3 43. Kg3 {White seems to be
holding as Black's rook comes in the way of his own pawns whereas White's pawn
has no obstacle to navigate through.}) 40... f4 $3 (40... Rb5 41. g4 Rb2+ (
41... fxg4 {ends in a forced draw after} 42. Rxb5 axb5 43. fxg4 Kxa3 44. g5 b4
45. g6 b3 46. g7 b2 47. g8=Q b1=Q 48. Qa8+ Kb2 49. Qxb7+ Ka1 50. Qxb1+ Kxb1)
42. Kg3 fxg4 43. f4 $1 {[%cal Gf4f5,Gf5f6] Like before, Black's rook comes in
the way of his own pawns and quality over quantity! White's single pawn
marches forward very quickly which is enough to hold the game to a draw.}) 41.
Rf5 Kxa3 42. Rxf4 b5 {The difference between this and the other line in which
White's R was on f5 is now Black can rush with his b-pawn} 43. Kh3 (43. Rf5 {
is one tempo short:} a5 44. Kh3 a4 45. g4 b4 46. g5 Rc2 47. g6 Rc8 $19 {
[%cal Gb4b3,Gc8g8]}) 43... b4 44. g4 b3 45. Rf5 (45. g5 Rb1 46. Rf6 a5 47. Rb6
b2 48. f4 Rf1 $19) 45... Ra2 $1 {Another important move! Ensuring that the
a-pawn lives} 46. g5 (46. Ra5+ Kb4) 46... b2 47. Rf6 a5 {No rush!} (47... b1=Q
$4 {would have been a terrible blunder:} 48. Rxa6+ Kb3 49. Rb6+ Kc2 50. Rxb1
Kxb1 51. Kg4 $11 {and White can make a draw.}) 48. Rb6 Ra1 49. f4 b1=Q 50. Rxb1
Rxb1 51. g6 Rg1 52. f5 Rg5 {White resigned here.} ({A possible continuation
could have been} 52... Rg5 53. Kh4 Rxf5 54. g7 Rf1 $1 55. g8=Q Rh1+ 56. Kg5
Rg1+ 57. Kf6 Rxg8 $19) 0-1


