Bf4 Ne5 14. Nb4 Bb7 (14... Qxc5 15. Nd3 Nxd3 16. Qxd3 e5 {White seems to be
holding as Black's rook comes in the way of his own pawns whereas White's pawn
has no obstacle to navigate through.} 17. Be3 Qc7 18. Rac1 Qa5 {This is
holding because Black cannot rush with his b-pawn as it runs into Ra5 and after
} 19. Bc5 Re8 20. Bd6 Rb6 {White is in time to march his g-pawn:} 21. Bc7) 15.
Bxb7 Qxb7 16. Nd3 Nxd3 $1 {is the only move that holds and the point is after}
17. Qxd3) 11... Rxb5 12. Nd6 {The most natural move with the rook swinging
over to the e-file and the isolated pawn forking. At first sight it looks like
Black is not well coordinated but there is a wonderful resource.} Bxd6 (12...
Rb8 {ends in a forced draw after} 13. b3 Ba6 14. Ba3) 13. Qxd6 Bb7 $1 {The
check followed by this move does not come naturally at all as it looks like
queen is getting trapped on c4, but magically nothing is working out for White.
} 14. Na3 (14. b3 Ne7 $1 {[%cal Gf4f5,Gf5f6] Like before, Black's rook comes
in the way of his own pawns and quality over quantity! White's single pawn
marches forward very quickly which is enough to hold the game to a draw.})
14... Rb6 15. Be3 {A slightly dubious move in practice in my opinion, as White
doesn't get any structural advantage in return for wasting some tempi with the
king.} (15. Nc4 Ra6 16. Bd2 Ne7 17. Qd3 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 $19 {[%cal Gb4b3,Gc8g8]}
Qa8+ 19. f3 d5 20. Ne5) 15... Rxb2 16. Bc5 Re8 17. Rab1 (17. Nc4 Rxe2 (17...
Rb5 18. a4 Rb3 $19 19. Qd1 {is one tempo short:} Rc3 20. Nd6) 18. Qd3 Ba6 19.
Qxe2 d5) 17... Rxb1 $1 {A very smart move.} 18. Rxb1 $2 {This was certainly a
bad move as Black now gets a dream position where he is more active and White
has a weak IQP.} Ba6 19. Nb5 {White tries to get the rook into life from h4. I
really love the way I dealt with this.} Bxb5 {Hitting the g2 pawn} 20. Rxb5 Qc8
{Preventing the R from coming to h4.} 21. a4 h6 {Hitting the d4 pawn.} 22. Ba3
{and it seems like White achieved what was intended. Doesn't it?} Qa6 {Yes,
the rook is active now and that is pretty much what White wanted, but now the
problem for White is the poor coordination amongst his pieces. Q is paralyzed
on f2 as it has to protect h4 and f2, R on a1 struggles to find a good square,
N on c3 cannot be moved, and the R on h4 can move but it doesn't really help
White. On the other hand, Black's every single piece is very active.} 23. Bb2
Qxa4 {Giving way for the f7-pawn and hitting the P on h5 at the same time.} 24.
Bxc6 dxc6 25. Rb4 Qa5 {Nevertheless,Black is still much better.} 26. Bxf6 gxf6
{Grabbing the pawn!} 27. Rg4+ Kh7 28. Qxc6 Rd8 {When up material, trade pieces!
} 29. Qc2+ (29. Ra4 Qe1+ {White resigned here.} (29... Qb6 30. Qc2+ f5 31. e4
fxe4 32. Rxe4 f5 $11 {and White can make a draw.} 33. Rc4) {A possible
continuation could have been} 30. Kg2 Rd1 31. Qc7 Qh1+ (31... Kg6 $19 32. Rg4+
$4 {would have been a terrible blunder:}) 32. Kh3 $1 Qf1+ 33. Kh4 Qxf2 34.
Qxf7+ Kh8) 29... f5 {Consolidating the extra pawn by getting everything stable.
} 30. Ra4 Qe1+ 31. Kg2 {White finally gets rid of the weak d-pawn, but it's
too late as the damage is already done.} Rd1 {Liquidating to an endgame.} 32.
Qc7 Kg6 33. Kf3 Qh1+ 34. Ke3 {Not a blunder,White tries to do something
concrete which is sensible.} Ra1 35. Qc2 Rxa4 36. Qxa4 Qc1+ 37. Kf3 {The whole
point.} Qc3+ $2 {I was lured into doing this as it intuitively seemed winning
as Black's king is more active.} 38. Kg2 a5 39. g4 Qe5 40. gxf5+ $2 {This
loses because of ...} Kxf5 $3 41. Qe8 Kg6 42. Qf8 a4 {The difference between
this and the other line in which White's R was on f5 is now Black can rush
with his b-pawn} 43. e3 Qe4+ 44. Kg3 Qd3 45. h4 a3 $1 {Another important move!
Ensuring that the a-pawn lives} 46. Kh2 Qf5 47. Qxa3 Qxf2+ {No rush!} 48. Kh3
Qf3+ 49. Kh2 Kh5 50. Qf8 Qf2+ 51. Kh1 Kg4 0-1


