1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 c5 3. d5 Ne4 ({A sensible choice, although you do have to
wonder why Black didn't prefer 2...Ne4 if he wants to play this way. One
reason is to bypass the 3 Bf4 c5 4 f3 lines (4 d5 would be our main game here),
and in any case I'd certainly prefer the text move as Black to} 3... Qb6 {when}
4. Nc3 {is, of course, the Vaganian Gambit, as seen in a couple of fairly
high-level blitz games of late:} Qxb2 (4... d6 5. e4 g6 $6 {is just a Schmid
Benoni with Black's queen misplaced, as in Erigaisi-Martirosyan, Internet 
(blitz) 2022, where} 6. Bb5+ Nbd7 7. a4 a6 8. a5 $1 Qc7 9. Be2 Bg7 10. Nf3 O-O
11. Nd2 b5 12. axb6 Nxb6 13. O-O {left White in control and with a very
pleasant edge, not least with the f-pawn primed to advance}) 5. Bd2 Qb6 6. e4
d6 7. f4 g6 $2 8. Nf3 Bg7 9. e5 Nfd7 10. Rb1 Qc7 11. Nb5 $1 Qd8 12. exd6 O-O $1
13. Nc7 exd6 14. Nxa8 Nf6 15. Be2 Nxd5 16. O-O {gave Black some but not enough
compensation for the exchange, with f4-f5 this time high on the agenda in
Bacrot-Petrovskyi, Internet (blitz) 2022.}) 4. Bf4 Qb6 ({Curiously Erigaisi
has also faced another long-out-of-fashion line in} 4... e6 5. f3 Bd6 $5 {
of late. It may not be too topical, but does still seem fine for Black, with}
6. Bxd6 Nxd6 7. Nc3 b5 8. e4 b4 9. Nb5 $5 (9. Na4 Qc7 10. Qd2 O-O {seemed OK
for Black in Yakubboev-Sindarov, Uzbek Championship, Tashkent 2021, as we've
noted before}) 9... Nxb5 10. Bxb5 Qb6 11. Bc4 Ba6 12. Qd3 exd5 $6 ({allowing
White to take control} 12... O-O 13. Ne2 Bxc4 14. Qxc4 Na6 {followed by ...
Nc7 is likely OK for Black}) 13. Qxd5 Bxc4 14. Qxc4 Nc6 15. Ne2 O-O 16. O-O {
favouring White thanks to the hole on d5 in Erigaisi-Tabatabaei, Internet 
(blitz) 2022.}) 5. Bc1 g6 6. f3 Nd6 $5 ({This doesn't seem to equalise
according to the latest engines and theory, but then again neither does} 6...
Nf6 7. e4 Bg7 8. c4 {followed by Ng1-e2-c3 with a likely improved version of
the S�misch variation for White.}) 7. e4 Bg7 8. Nd2 $6 ({Presumably Erigaisi
was caught out, as this doesn't seem especially good. Instead, the main line
has been considered to be} 8. Nc3 f5 9. exf5 Nxf5 {- see the Archive for
Eric's thorough coverage, and do also note that the latest engines rather like}
10. g4 $5 {for White.}) ({There's also} 8. c3 $5 {and after} O-O 9. Nh3 ({
I still feel that} 9. h4 $1 f5 10. h5 {makes good sense too, since} fxe4 11.
hxg6 hxg6 12. Nd2 {leaves Black's kingside looking rather vulnerable}) 9... f5
10. exf5 Nxf5 11. Na3 Na6 12. Be2 Nc7 {(Kindermann-Derakhshani, Munich (rapid)
2016)} 13. O-O $1 d6 14. g4 $5 {White is for choice, as we've noted before.})
8... O-O ({Calm and sensible, although I dare say that Black could also
consider the immediate} 8... e6 $5 {.}) 9. Bd3 (9. f4 $5 {would be both more
active and also battle for the key c4 point. It's also been tried before, with}
e6 10. e5 Nf5 11. Nc4 Qd8 12. dxe6 dxe6 ({would the 2022 version of MVL prefer
} 12... d5 $5 13. exf7+ Rxf7 {with promising compensation?}) 13. Qxd8 Rxd8 14.
c3 b6 15. Nf3 Bb7 16. Be2 {seen in Bauer-Vachier Lagrave, French Championship,
Pau 2012, where} h5 {would have restricted White to a small edge thanks to his
bridgehead on e5 and the hole on d6.}) 9... f5 $5 ({Black decides to break
before White rolls with f3-f4 and e4-e5, which makes good sense, although it
seems that} 9... e6 $1 {would have been even stronger:} 10. c3 ({this
restrained choice seems necessary or at least} 10. c4 $6 exd5 11. cxd5 Na6 {
and only then ...f5 leaves Black very actively placed}) 10... exd5 11. exd5
Re8+ 12. Ne2 Qc7 {and with ...b5 and ...c4 both high on the agenda, Black must
be at least OK.}) 10. c4 e5 $2 ({Blocking the centre, Czech Benoni style,
gives White too much time to get organised and also leaves Black struggling
for counterplay. A young MVL had preferred} 10... fxe4 11. fxe4 Nf7 {and after}
12. Ngf3 d6 13. O-O Nd7 14. Rb1 Nf6 {he had regrouped whilst obtaining a
comfortable set-up in Pankov-Vachier Lagrave, Russian Team Championship 2009.})
11. Ne2 ({Even} 11. exf5 $5 gxf5 ({or} 11... Nxf5 12. Ne4) 12. Ne2 {is
promising for White according to the engines, and no surprise - just what is
that knight doing on d6?}) 11... f4 ({Further closing the position so seems
sensible. You might also wonder about regrouping with} 11... Qd8 12. Nc3 Ne8 {
, but after} 13. exf5 $1 gxf5 14. O-O d6 15. Kh1 $1 {the g2-g4 break is high
on White's agenda and he just seems to be doing pretty well from what I can
see.}) 12. Nc3 Qd8 13. Qe2 Nf7 ({Finally conceding that the knight has to move
if Black is to coordinate his queenside forces. Instead,} 13... Qh4+ 14. Qf2 (
14. Kd1 $5 {is also possible as per the game}) 14... Qxf2+ 15. Kxf2 {followed
by a2-a3 and b2-b4 would have left White beginning to expand.}) 14. b3 d6 15.
Bb2 {Not the most active role for the bishop you might think, but just watch
what happens.} Qh4+ 16. Kd1 $5 g5 (16... Qe7 17. Kc2 h5 $5 {is preferred by
the engines, although even here White seems definitely for choice after} 18. g3
{.}) 17. Kc2 {The king is perfectly safe here and now, despite Black's
advances, it is White who will look to attack on the kingside.} g4 ({Likewise,
} 17... Qh6 18. Rag1 Kh8 19. g3 Bh3 20. Nd1 $1 {just seems to leave Black in
long-term trouble on the king's flank.}) 18. Rag1 {Erigaisi knows exactly what
his plan is: to rip open lines against the king on g8.} Na6 19. a3 Ng5 20. Nb5
$1 {Not just awkwardly for Black is d6 now attacked, but the bishop on b2 has
been unfurled.} Rf6 21. g3 $1 {Crowning White's strategy. Ayush has been
completely outplayed.} Qh5 (21... Qh6 {would have avoided dropping d6, but
after} 22. gxf4 Rxf4 23. fxg4 Nh3 24. Rg3 {the result surely wouldn't have
changed.}) 22. gxf4 Rxf4 23. Nxd6 $1 {Further good judgement from Erigaisi.
Black will obtain a protected passed pawn on f3, but of far greater importance
is the open g-file and the central gains White has just made.} gxf3 24. Qe3 Bh3
{Desperately trying to prevent h2-h4, but now White is able to pivot and eye
the key defensive piece on g7.} 25. Nf5 ({It was also possible to force
matters:} 25. Bxe5 $5 Bxe5 26. Nxf3 Rxf3 27. Qxg5+ Qxg5 28. Rxg5+ Kf8 29. Rxe5
{and wins.}) 25... Bf6 26. Rg3 ({Simple chess, but White might have crowned
his strategic masterpiece in style with} 26. Qxf4 $3 exf4 27. Bxf6 {, and if}
Bg2 28. h4 Nf7 29. Rh2 {followed by Nxf3 or} Kf8 $2 30. Be7+ Ke8 31. Ng7+ {.})
26... Bg2 (26... Kf8 $5 27. Rhg1 h6 {would still have left White with a bit of
work to do.}) 27. Rg1 ({And here} 27. h4 $5 Bxh1 28. hxg5 Bh8 29. Bf1 {would
have been a more vigorous route to overwhelming the defence.}) 27... Qxh2 28.
Qf2 Kf8 29. Rxg5 $1 {Finally White sacrifices and Black's game immediately
folds on the dark squares.} Bxg5 30. Bxe5 Re8 31. Bd6+ Kf7 32. Nxf3 $1 ({
Crushing, as would have been} 32. e5 $5 {.}) 32... Rxf3 33. Qxf3 Qxg1 34. Qh5+
Kf6 35. e5+ $1 {The key check. Erigaisi has spotted that only one king is in
serious trouble, and it isn't White's.} Rxe5 36. Bxe5+ Kxe5 37. Qxg5 Qf2+ 38.
Kc3 Qe1+ 39. Kb2 Qf2+ 40. Bc2 {The checks are over for Black and White's
discovery finally about to be realised.} Bf3 41. Nh4+ 1-0



